11   /**
12    * Lexing or parsing positional information for error reporting.
13    * This object is immutable.
14    */
15   class SourceLocation {
16     // The + prefix indicates that these fields aren't writeable
17     // Lexer holding the input string.
18     // Start offset, zero-based inclusive.
19     // End offset, zero-based exclusive.
20     constructor(lexer, start, end) {
21       this.lexer = void 0;
22       this.start = void 0;
23       this.end = void 0;
24       this.lexer = lexer;
25       this.start = start;
26       this.end = end;
27     }
28     /**
29      * Merges two `SourceLocation`s from location providers, given they are
30      * provided in order of appearance.
31      * - Returns the first one's location if only the first is provided.
32      * - Returns a merged range of the first and the last if both are provided
33      *   and their lexers match.
34      * - Otherwise, returns null.
35      */
36   
37   
38     static range(first, second) {
39       if (!second) {
40         return first && first.loc;
41       } else if (!first || !first.loc || !second.loc || first.loc.lexer !== second.loc.lexer) {
42         return null;
43       } else {
44         return new SourceLocation(first.loc.lexer, first.loc.start, second.loc.end);
45       }
46     }
47   
48   }
49   
50   /**
51    * Interface required to break circular dependency between Token, Lexer, and
52    * ParseError.
53    */
54   
55   /**
56    * The resulting token returned from `lex`.
57    *
58    * It consists of the token text plus some position information.
59    * The position information is essentially a range in an input string,
60    * but instead of referencing the bare input string, we refer to the lexer.
61    * That way it is possible to attach extra metadata to the input string,
62    * like for example a file name or similar.
63    *
64    * The position information is optional, so it is OK to construct synthetic
65    * tokens if appropriate. Not providing available position information may
66    * lead to degraded error reporting, though.
67    */
68   class Token {
69     // don't expand the token
70     // used in \noexpand
71     constructor(text, // the text of this token
72     loc) {
73       this.text = void 0;
74       this.loc = void 0;
75       this.noexpand = void 0;
76       this.treatAsRelax = void 0;
77       this.text = text;
78       this.loc = loc;
79     }
80     /**
81      * Given a pair of tokens (this and endToken), compute a `Token` encompassing
82      * the whole input range enclosed by these two.
83      */
84   
85   
86     range(endToken, // last token of the range, inclusive
87     text // the text of the newly constructed token
88     ) {
89       return new Token(text, SourceLocation.range(this, endToken));
90     }
91   
92   }

94   /**
95    * This is the ParseError class, which is the main error thrown by KaTeX
96    * functions when something has gone wrong. This is used to distinguish internal
97    * errors from errors in the expression that the user provided.
98    *
99    * If possible, a caller should provide a Token or ParseNode with information
100   * about where in the source string the problem occurred.
101   */
102  class ParseError {
103    // Error start position based on passed-in Token or ParseNode.
104    // Length of affected text based on passed-in Token or ParseNode.
105    // The underlying error message without any context added.
106    constructor(message, // The error message
107    token // An object providing position information
108    ) {
109      this.name = void 0;
110      this.position = void 0;
111      this.length = void 0;
112      this.rawMessage = void 0;
113      var error = "KaTeX parse error: " + message;
114      var start;
115      var end;
116      var loc = token && token.loc;
117  
118      if (loc && loc.start <= loc.end) {
119        // If we have the input and a position, make the error a bit fancier
120        // Get the input
121        var input = loc.lexer.input; // Prepend some information
122  
123        start = loc.start;
124        end = loc.end;
125  
126        if (start === input.length) {
127          error += " at end of input: ";
128        } else {
129          error += " at position " + (start + 1) + ": ";
130        } // Underline token in question using combining underscores
131  
132  
133        var underlined = input.slice(start, end).replace(/[^]/g, "$&\u0332"); // Extract some context from the input and add it to the error
134  
135        var left;
136  
137        if (start > 15) {
138          left = "…" + input.slice(start - 15, start);
139        } else {
140          left = input.slice(0, start);
141        }
142  
143        var right;
144  
145        if (end + 15 < input.length) {
146          right = input.slice(end, end + 15) + "…";
147        } else {
148          right = input.slice(end);
149        }
150  
151        error += left + underlined + right;
152      } // Some hackery to make ParseError a prototype of Error
153      // See http://stackoverflow.com/a/8460753
154      // $FlowFixMe
155  
156  
157      var self = new Error(error);
158      self.name = "ParseError"; // $FlowFixMe
159  
160      self.__proto__ = ParseError.prototype;
161      self.position = start;
162  
163      if (start != null && end != null) {
164        self.length = end - start;
165      }
166  
167      self.rawMessage = message;
168      return self;
169    }
170  
171  } // $FlowFixMe More hackery
172

204  var ESCAPE_LOOKUP = {
205    "&": "&amp;",
206    ">": "&gt;",
207    "<": "&lt;",
208    "\"": "&quot;",
209    "'": "&#x27;"
210  };
211  var ESCAPE_REGEX = /[&><"']/g;
212  /**
213   * Escapes text to prevent scripting attacks.
214   */
215  
216  function escape(text) {
217    return String(text).replace(ESCAPE_REGEX, match => ESCAPE_LOOKUP[match]);
218  }
219  /**
220   * Sometimes we want to pull out the innermost element of a group. In most
221   * cases, this will just be the group itself, but when ordgroups and colors have
222   * a single element, we want to pull that out.
223   */
224  
225  
226  var getBaseElem = function getBaseElem(group) {
227    if (group.type === "ordgroup") {
228      if (group.body.length === 1) {
229        return getBaseElem(group.body[0]);
230      } else {
231        return group;
232      }
233    } else if (group.type === "color") {
234      if (group.body.length === 1) {
235        return getBaseElem(group.body[0]);
236      } else {
237        return group;
238      }
239    } else if (group.type === "font") {
240      return getBaseElem(group.body);
241    } else {
242      return group;
243    }
244  };
245  /**
246   * TeXbook algorithms often reference "character boxes", which are simply groups
247   * with a single character in them. To decide if something is a character box,
248   * we find its innermost group, and see if it is a single character.
249   */
250  
251  
252  var isCharacterBox = function isCharacterBox(group) {
253    var baseElem = getBaseElem(group); // These are all they types of groups which hold single characters
254  
255    return baseElem.type === "mathord" || baseElem.type === "textord" || baseElem.type === "atom";
256  };

258  var assert = function assert(value) {
259    if (!value) {
260      throw new Error('Expected non-null, but got ' + String(value));
261    }
262  
263    return value;
264  };
265  /**
266   * Return the protocol of a URL, or "_relative" if the URL does not specify a
267   * protocol (and thus is relative), or `null` if URL has invalid protocol
268   * (so should be outright rejected).
269   */
270  
271  var protocolFromUrl = function protocolFromUrl(url) {
272    // Check for possible leading protocol.
273    // https://url.spec.whatwg.org/#url-parsing strips leading whitespace
274    // (U+20) or C0 control (U+00-U+1F) characters.
275    // eslint-disable-next-line no-control-regex
276    var protocol = /^[\x00-\x20]*([^\\/#?]*?)(:|&#0*58|&#x0*3a|&colon)/i.exec(url);
277  
278    if (!protocol) {
279      return "_relative";
280    } // Reject weird colons
281  
282  
283    if (protocol[2] !== ":") {
284      return null;
285    } // Reject invalid characters in scheme according to
286    // https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc3986#section-3.1
287  
288  
289    if (!/^[a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9+\-.]*$/.test(protocol[1])) {
290      return null;
291    } // Lowercase the protocol
292  
293  
294    return protocol[1].toLowerCase();
295  };

401  function getDefaultValue(schema) {
402    if (schema.default) {
403      return schema.default;
404    }
405  
406    var type = schema.type;
407    var defaultType = Array.isArray(type) ? type[0] : type;
408  
409    if (typeof defaultType !== 'string') {
410      return defaultType.enum[0];
411    }
412  
413    switch (defaultType) {
414      case 'boolean':
415        return false;
416  
417      case 'string':
418        return '';
419  
420      case 'number':
421        return 0;
422  
423      case 'object':
424        return {};
425    }
426  }
427  /**
428   * The main Settings object
429   *
430   * The current options stored are:
431   *  - displayMode: Whether the expression should be typeset as inline math
432   *                 (false, the default), meaning that the math starts in
433   *                 \textstyle and is placed in an inline-block); or as display
434   *                 math (true), meaning that the math starts in \displaystyle
435   *                 and is placed in a block with vertical margin.
436   */
437  
438  
439  class Settings {
440    constructor(options) {
441      this.displayMode = void 0;
442      this.output = void 0;
443      this.leqno = void 0;
444      this.fleqn = void 0;
445      this.throwOnError = void 0;
446      this.errorColor = void 0;
447      this.macros = void 0;
448      this.minRuleThickness = void 0;
449      this.colorIsTextColor = void 0;
450      this.strict = void 0;
451      this.trust = void 0;
452      this.maxSize = void 0;
453      this.maxExpand = void 0;
454      this.globalGroup = void 0;
455      // allow null options
456      options = options || {};
457  
458      for (var prop in SETTINGS_SCHEMA) {
459        if (SETTINGS_SCHEMA.hasOwnProperty(prop)) {
460          // $FlowFixMe
461          var schema = SETTINGS_SCHEMA[prop]; // TODO: validate options
462          // $FlowFixMe
463  
464          this[prop] = options[prop] !== undefined ? schema.processor ? schema.processor(options[prop]) : options[prop] : getDefaultValue(schema);
465        }
466      }
467    }
468    /**
469     * Report nonstrict (non-LaTeX-compatible) input.
470     * Can safely not be called if `this.strict` is false in JavaScript.
471     */
472  
473  
474    reportNonstrict(errorCode, errorMsg, token) {
475      var strict = this.strict;
476  
477      if (typeof strict === "function") {
478        // Allow return value of strict function to be boolean or string
479        // (or null/undefined, meaning no further processing).
480        strict = strict(errorCode, errorMsg, token);
481      }
482  
483      if (!strict || strict === "ignore") {
484        return;
485      } else if (strict === true || strict === "error") {
486        throw new ParseError("LaTeX-incompatible input and strict mode is set to 'error': " + (errorMsg + " [" + errorCode + "]"), token);
487      } else if (strict === "warn") {
488        typeof console !== "undefined" && console.warn("LaTeX-incompatible input and strict mode is set to 'warn': " + (errorMsg + " [" + errorCode + "]"));
489      } else {
490        // won't happen in type-safe code
491        typeof console !== "undefined" && console.warn("LaTeX-incompatible input and strict mode is set to " + ("unrecognized '" + strict + "': " + errorMsg + " [" + errorCode + "]"));
492      }
493    }
494    /**
495     * Check whether to apply strict (LaTeX-adhering) behavior for unusual
496     * input (like `\\`).  Unlike `nonstrict`, will not throw an error;
497     * instead, "error" translates to a return value of `true`, while "ignore"
498     * translates to a return value of `false`.  May still print a warning:
499     * "warn" prints a warning and returns `false`.
500     * This is for the second category of `errorCode`s listed in the README.
501     */
502  
503  
504    useStrictBehavior(errorCode, errorMsg, token) {
505      var strict = this.strict;
506  
507      if (typeof strict === "function") {
508        // Allow return value of strict function to be boolean or string
509        // (or null/undefined, meaning no further processing).
510        // But catch any exceptions thrown by function, treating them
511        // like "error".
512        try {
513          strict = strict(errorCode, errorMsg, token);
514        } catch (error) {
515          strict = "error";
516        }
517      }
518  
519      if (!strict || strict === "ignore") {
520        return false;
521      } else if (strict === true || strict === "error") {
522        return true;
523      } else if (strict === "warn") {
524        typeof console !== "undefined" && console.warn("LaTeX-incompatible input and strict mode is set to 'warn': " + (errorMsg + " [" + errorCode + "]"));
525        return false;
526      } else {
527        // won't happen in type-safe code
528        typeof console !== "undefined" && console.warn("LaTeX-incompatible input and strict mode is set to " + ("unrecognized '" + strict + "': " + errorMsg + " [" + errorCode + "]"));
529        return false;
530      }
531    }
532    /**
533     * Check whether to test potentially dangerous input, and return
534     * `true` (trusted) or `false` (untrusted).  The sole argument `context`
535     * should be an object with `command` field specifying the relevant LaTeX
536     * command (as a string starting with `\`), and any other arguments, etc.
537     * If `context` has a `url` field, a `protocol` field will automatically
538     * get added by this function (changing the specified object).
539     */
540  
541  
542    isTrusted(context) {
543      if (context.url && !context.protocol) {
544        var protocol = utils.protocolFromUrl(context.url);
545  
546        if (protocol == null) {
547          return false;
548        }
549  
550        context.protocol = protocol;
551      }
552  
553      var trust = typeof this.trust === "function" ? this.trust(context) : this.trust;
554      return Boolean(trust);
555    }
556  
557  }

559  /**
560   * This file contains information and classes for the various kinds of styles
561   * used in TeX. It provides a generic `Style` class, which holds information
562   * about a specific style. It then provides instances of all the different kinds
563   * of styles possible, and provides functions to move between them and get
564   * information about them.
565   */
566  
567  /**
568   * The main style class. Contains a unique id for the style, a size (which is
569   * the same for cramped and uncramped version of a style), and a cramped flag.
570   */
571  class Style {
572    constructor(id, size, cramped) {
573      this.id = void 0;
574      this.size = void 0;
575      this.cramped = void 0;
576      this.id = id;
577      this.size = size;
578      this.cramped = cramped;
579    }
580    /**
581     * Get the style of a superscript given a base in the current style.
582     */
583  
584  
585    sup() {
586      return styles[sup[this.id]];
587    }
588    /**
589     * Get the style of a subscript given a base in the current style.
590     */
591  
592  
593    sub() {
594      return styles[sub[this.id]];
595    }
596    /**
597     * Get the style of a fraction numerator given the fraction in the current
598     * style.
599     */
600  
601  
602    fracNum() {
603      return styles[fracNum[this.id]];
604    }
605    /**
606     * Get the style of a fraction denominator given the fraction in the current
607     * style.
608     */
609  
610  
611    fracDen() {
612      return styles[fracDen[this.id]];
613    }
614    /**
615     * Get the cramped version of a style (in particular, cramping a cramped style
616     * doesn't change the style).
617     */
618  
619  
620    cramp() {
621      return styles[cramp[this.id]];
622    }
623    /**
624     * Get a text or display version of this style.
625     */
626  
627  
628    text() {
629      return styles[text$1[this.id]];
630    }
631    /**
632     * Return true if this style is tightly spaced (scriptstyle/scriptscriptstyle)
633     */
634  
635  
636    isTight() {
637      return this.size >= 2;
638    }
639  
640  } // Export an interface for type checking, but don't expose the implementation.
641  // This way, no more styles can be generated.

670  /* 
671   * This file defines the Unicode scripts and script families that we 
672   * support. To add new scripts or families, just add a new entry to the 
673   * scriptData array below. Adding scripts to the scriptData array allows 
674   * characters from that script to appear in \text{} environments. 
675   */
676  
677  /**
678   * Each script or script family has a name and an array of blocks.
679   * Each block is an array of two numbers which specify the start and
680   * end points (inclusive) of a block of Unicode codepoints.
681   */
682  
683  /**
684   * Unicode block data for the families of scripts we support in \text{}.
685   * Scripts only need to appear here if they do not have font metrics.
686   */
687  var scriptData = [{
688    // Latin characters beyond the Latin-1 characters we have metrics for.
689    // Needed for Czech, Hungarian and Turkish text, for example.
690    name: 'latin',
691    blocks: [[0x0100, 0x024f], // Latin Extended-A and Latin Extended-B
692    [0x0300, 0x036f] // Combining Diacritical marks
693    ]
694  }, {
695    // The Cyrillic script used by Russian and related languages.
696    // A Cyrillic subset used to be supported as explicitly defined
697    // symbols in symbols.js
698    name: 'cyrillic',
699    blocks: [[0x0400, 0x04ff]]
700  }, {
701    // Armenian
702    name: 'armenian',
703    blocks: [[0x0530, 0x058F]]
704  }, {
705    // The Brahmic scripts of South and Southeast Asia
706    // Devanagari (0900–097F)
707    // Bengali (0980–09FF)
708    // Gurmukhi (0A00–0A7F)
709    // Gujarati (0A80–0AFF)
710    // Oriya (0B00–0B7F)
711    // Tamil (0B80–0BFF)
712    // Telugu (0C00–0C7F)
713    // Kannada (0C80–0CFF)
714    // Malayalam (0D00–0D7F)
715    // Sinhala (0D80–0DFF)
716    // Thai (0E00–0E7F)
717    // Lao (0E80–0EFF)
718    // Tibetan (0F00–0FFF)
719    // Myanmar (1000–109F)
720    name: 'brahmic',
721    blocks: [[0x0900, 0x109F]]
722  }, {
723    name: 'georgian',
724    blocks: [[0x10A0, 0x10ff]]
725  }, {
726    // Chinese and Japanese.
727    // The "k" in cjk is for Korean, but we've separated Korean out
728    name: "cjk",
729    blocks: [[0x3000, 0x30FF], // CJK symbols and punctuation, Hiragana, Katakana
730    [0x4E00, 0x9FAF], // CJK ideograms
731    [0xFF00, 0xFF60] // Fullwidth punctuation
732    // TODO: add halfwidth Katakana and Romanji glyphs
733    ]
734  }, {
735    // Korean
736    name: 'hangul',
737    blocks: [[0xAC00, 0xD7AF]]
738  }];
739  /**
740   * Given a codepoint, return the name of the script or script family
741   * it is from, or null if it is not part of a known block
742   */
743  
744  function scriptFromCodepoint(codepoint) {
745    for (var i = 0; i < scriptData.length; i++) {
746      var script = scriptData[i];
747  
748      for (var _i = 0; _i < script.blocks.length; _i++) {
749        var block = script.blocks[_i];
750  
751        if (codepoint >= block[0] && codepoint <= block[1]) {
752          return script.name;
753        }
754      }
755    }
756  
757    return null;
758  }
759  /**
760   * A flattened version of all the supported blocks in a single array.
761   * This is an optimization to make supportedCodepoint() fast.
762   */
763  
764  var allBlocks = [];
765  scriptData.forEach(s => s.blocks.forEach(b => allBlocks.push(...b)));
766  /**
767   * Given a codepoint, return true if it falls within one of the
768   * scripts or script families defined above and false otherwise.
769   *
770   * Micro benchmarks shows that this is faster than
771   * /[\u3000-\u30FF\u4E00-\u9FAF\uFF00-\uFF60\uAC00-\uD7AF\u0900-\u109F]/.test()
772   * in Firefox, Chrome and Node.
773   */
774  
775  function supportedCodepoint(codepoint) {
776    for (var i = 0; i < allBlocks.length; i += 2) {
777      if (codepoint >= allBlocks[i] && codepoint <= allBlocks[i + 1]) {
778        return true;
779      }
780    }
781  
782    return false;
783  }

785  /**
786   * This file provides support to domTree.js and delimiter.js.
787   * It's a storehouse of path geometry for SVG images.
788   */
789  // In all paths below, the viewBox-to-em scale is 1000:1.
790  var hLinePad = 80; // padding above a sqrt vinculum. Prevents image cropping.
791  // The vinculum of a \sqrt can be made thicker by a KaTeX rendering option.
792  // Think of variable extraVinculum as two detours in the SVG path.
793  // The detour begins at the lower left of the area labeled extraVinculum below.
794  // The detour proceeds one extraVinculum distance up and slightly to the right,
795  // displacing the radiused corner between surd and vinculum. The radius is
796  // traversed as usual, then the detour resumes. It goes right, to the end of
797  // the very long vinculum, then down one extraVinculum distance,
798  // after which it resumes regular path geometry for the radical.
799  
800  /*                                                  vinculum 
801                                                     / 
802           /▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒←extraVinculum 
803          / █████████████████████←0.04em (40 unit) std vinculum thickness 
804         / / 
805        / / 
806       / /\ 
807      / / surd 
808  */
809

842    // sqrtTall is from glyph U23B7 in the font KaTeX_Size4-Regular

844    // to a point near (14 units) the bottom of the surd. The vinculum

850  var sqrtPath = function sqrtPath(size, extraVinculum, viewBoxHeight) {
851    extraVinculum = 1000 * extraVinculum; // Convert from document ems to viewBox.
852  
853    var path = "";
854  
855    switch (size) {
856      case "sqrtMain":
857        path = sqrtMain(extraVinculum, hLinePad);
858        break;
859  
860      case "sqrtSize1":
861        path = sqrtSize1(extraVinculum, hLinePad);
862        break;
863  
864      case "sqrtSize2":
865        path = sqrtSize2(extraVinculum, hLinePad);
866        break;
867  
868      case "sqrtSize3":
869        path = sqrtSize3(extraVinculum, hLinePad);
870        break;
871  
872      case "sqrtSize4":
873        path = sqrtSize4(extraVinculum, hLinePad);
874        break;
875  
876      case "sqrtTall":
877        path = sqrtTall(extraVinculum, hLinePad, viewBoxHeight);
878    }
879  
880    return path;
881  };

1032 /**
1033  * This node represents a document fragment, which contains elements, but when
1034  * placed into the DOM doesn't have any representation itself. It only contains
1035  * children and doesn't have any DOM node properties.
1036  */
1037 class DocumentFragment {
1038   // HtmlDomNode
1039   // Never used; needed for satisfying interface.
1040   constructor(children) {
1041     this.children = void 0;
1042     this.classes = void 0;
1043     this.height = void 0;
1044     this.depth = void 0;
1045     this.maxFontSize = void 0;
1046     this.style = void 0;
1047     this.children = children;
1048     this.classes = [];
1049     this.height = 0;
1050     this.depth = 0;
1051     this.maxFontSize = 0;
1052     this.style = {};
1053   }
1054 
1055   hasClass(className) {
1056     return utils.contains(this.classes, className);
1057   }
1058   /** Convert the fragment into a node. */
1059 
1060 
1061   toNode() {
1062     var frag = document.createDocumentFragment();
1063 
1064     for (var i = 0; i < this.children.length; i++) {
1065       frag.appendChild(this.children[i].toNode());
1066     }
1067 
1068     return frag;
1069   }
1070   /** Convert the fragment into HTML markup. */
1071 
1072 
1073   toMarkup() {
1074     var markup = ""; // Simply concatenate the markup for the children together.
1075 
1076     for (var i = 0; i < this.children.length; i++) {
1077       markup += this.children[i].toMarkup();
1078     }
1079 
1080     return markup;
1081   }
1082   /**
1083    * Converts the math node into a string, similar to innerText. Applies to
1084    * MathDomNode's only.
1085    */
1086 
1087 
1088   toText() {
1089     // To avoid this, we would subclass documentFragment separately for
1090     // MathML, but polyfills for subclassing is expensive per PR 1469.
1091     // $FlowFixMe: Only works for ChildType = MathDomNode.
1092     var toText = child => child.toText();
1093 
1094     return this.children.map(toText).join("");
1095   }
1096 
1097 }

3177 /**
3178  * This file contains metrics regarding fonts and individual symbols. The sigma
3179  * and xi variables, as well as the metricMap map contain data extracted from
3180  * TeX, TeX font metrics, and the TTF files. These data are then exposed via the
3181  * `metrics` variable and the getCharacterMetrics function.
3182  */
3183 // In TeX, there are actually three sets of dimensions, one for each of
3184 // textstyle (size index 5 and higher: >=9pt), scriptstyle (size index 3 and 4:
3185 // 7-8pt), and scriptscriptstyle (size index 1 and 2: 5-6pt).  These are
3186 // provided in the arrays below, in that order.
3187 //
3188 // The font metrics are stored in fonts cmsy10, cmsy7, and cmsy5 respectively.
3189 // This was determined by running the following script:
3190 //
3191 //     latex -interaction=nonstopmode \
3192 //     '\documentclass{article}\usepackage{amsmath}\begin{document}' \
3193 //     '$a$ \expandafter\show\the\textfont2' \
3194 //     '\expandafter\show\the\scriptfont2' \
3195 //     '\expandafter\show\the\scriptscriptfont2' \
3196 //     '\stop'
3197 //
3198 // The metrics themselves were retrieved using the following commands:
3199 //
3200 //     tftopl cmsy10
3201 //     tftopl cmsy7
3202 //     tftopl cmsy5
3203 //
3204 // The output of each of these commands is quite lengthy.  The only part we
3205 // care about is the FONTDIMEN section. Each value is measured in EMs.
3206 var sigmasAndXis = {
3207   slant: [0.250, 0.250, 0.250],
3208   // sigma1
3209   space: [0.000, 0.000, 0.000],
3210   // sigma2
3211   stretch: [0.000, 0.000, 0.000],
3212   // sigma3
3213   shrink: [0.000, 0.000, 0.000],
3214   // sigma4
3215   xHeight: [0.431, 0.431, 0.431],
3216   // sigma5
3217   quad: [1.000, 1.171, 1.472],
3218   // sigma6
3219   extraSpace: [0.000, 0.000, 0.000],
3220   // sigma7
3221   num1: [0.677, 0.732, 0.925],
3222   // sigma8
3223   num2: [0.394, 0.384, 0.387],
3224   // sigma9
3225   num3: [0.444, 0.471, 0.504],
3226   // sigma10
3227   denom1: [0.686, 0.752, 1.025],
3228   // sigma11
3229   denom2: [0.345, 0.344, 0.532],
3230   // sigma12
3231   sup1: [0.413, 0.503, 0.504],
3232   // sigma13
3233   sup2: [0.363, 0.431, 0.404],
3234   // sigma14
3235   sup3: [0.289, 0.286, 0.294],
3236   // sigma15
3237   sub1: [0.150, 0.143, 0.200],
3238   // sigma16
3239   sub2: [0.247, 0.286, 0.400],
3240   // sigma17
3241   supDrop: [0.386, 0.353, 0.494],
3242   // sigma18
3243   subDrop: [0.050, 0.071, 0.100],
3244   // sigma19
3245   delim1: [2.390, 1.700, 1.980],
3246   // sigma20
3247   delim2: [1.010, 1.157, 1.420],
3248   // sigma21
3249   axisHeight: [0.250, 0.250, 0.250],
3250   // sigma22
3251   // These font metrics are extracted from TeX by using tftopl on cmex10.tfm;
3252   // they correspond to the font parameters of the extension fonts (family 3).
3253   // See the TeXbook, page 441. In AMSTeX, the extension fonts scale; to
3254   // match cmex7, we'd use cmex7.tfm values for script and scriptscript
3255   // values.
3256   defaultRuleThickness: [0.04, 0.049, 0.049],
3257   // xi8; cmex7: 0.049
3258   bigOpSpacing1: [0.111, 0.111, 0.111],
3259   // xi9
3260   bigOpSpacing2: [0.166, 0.166, 0.166],
3261   // xi10
3262   bigOpSpacing3: [0.2, 0.2, 0.2],
3263   // xi11
3264   bigOpSpacing4: [0.6, 0.611, 0.611],
3265   // xi12; cmex7: 0.611
3266   bigOpSpacing5: [0.1, 0.143, 0.143],
3267   // xi13; cmex7: 0.143
3268   // The \sqrt rule width is taken from the height of the surd character.
3269   // Since we use the same font at all sizes, this thickness doesn't scale.
3270   sqrtRuleThickness: [0.04, 0.04, 0.04],
3271   // This value determines how large a pt is, for metrics which are defined
3272   // in terms of pts.
3273   // This value is also used in katex.scss; if you change it make sure the
3274   // values match.
3275   ptPerEm: [10.0, 10.0, 10.0],
3276   // The space between adjacent `|` columns in an array definition. From
3277   // `\showthe\doublerulesep` in LaTeX. Equals 2.0 / ptPerEm.
3278   doubleRuleSep: [0.2, 0.2, 0.2],
3279   // The width of separator lines in {array} environments. From
3280   // `\showthe\arrayrulewidth` in LaTeX. Equals 0.4 / ptPerEm.
3281   arrayRuleWidth: [0.04, 0.04, 0.04],
3282   // Two values from LaTeX source2e:
3283   fboxsep: [0.3, 0.3, 0.3],
3284   //        3 pt / ptPerEm
3285   fboxrule: [0.04, 0.04, 0.04] // 0.4 pt / ptPerEm
3286 
3287 }; // This map contains a mapping from font name and character code to character
3288 // should have Latin-1 and Cyrillic characters, but may not depending on the
3289 // operating system.  The metrics do not account for extra height from the
3290 // accents.  In the case of Cyrillic characters which have both ascenders and
3291 // descenders we prefer approximations with ascenders, primarily to prevent
3292 // the fraction bar or root line from intersecting the glyph.
3293 // TODO(kevinb) allow union of multiple glyph metrics for better accuracy.
3294

3370 /**
3371  * This function adds new font metrics to default metricMap
3372  * It can also override existing metrics
3373  */
3374 function setFontMetrics(fontName, metrics) {
3375   fontMetricsData[fontName] = metrics;
3376 }
3377 /**
3378  * This function is a convenience function for looking up information in the
3379  * metricMap table. It takes a character as a string, and a font.
3380  *
3381  * Note: the `width` property may be undefined if fontMetricsData.js wasn't
3382  * built using `Make extended_metrics`.
3383  */
3384 
3385 function getCharacterMetrics(character, font, mode) {
3386   if (!fontMetricsData[font]) {
3387     throw new Error("Font metrics not found for font: " + font + ".");
3388   }
3389 
3390   var ch = character.charCodeAt(0);
3391   var metrics = fontMetricsData[font][ch];
3392 
3393   if (!metrics && character[0] in extraCharacterMap) {
3394     ch = extraCharacterMap[character[0]].charCodeAt(0);
3395     metrics = fontMetricsData[font][ch];
3396   }
3397 
3398   if (!metrics && mode === 'text') {
3399     // We don't typically have font metrics for Asian scripts.
3400     // But since we support them in text mode, we need to return
3401     // some sort of metrics.
3402     // So if the character is in a script we support but we
3403     // don't have metrics for it, just use the metrics for
3404     // the Latin capital letter M. This is close enough because
3405     // we (currently) only care about the height of the glyph
3406     // not its width.
3407     if (supportedCodepoint(ch)) {
3408       metrics = fontMetricsData[font][77]; // 77 is the charcode for 'M'
3409     }
3410   }
3411 
3412   if (metrics) {
3413     return {
3414       depth: metrics[0],
3415       height: metrics[1],
3416       italic: metrics[2],
3417       skew: metrics[3],
3418       width: metrics[4]
3419     };
3420   }
3421 }
3422 var fontMetricsBySizeIndex = {};
3423 /**
3424  * Get the font metrics for a given size.
3425  */
3426 
3427 function getGlobalMetrics(size) {
3428   var sizeIndex;
3429 
3430   if (size >= 5) {
3431     sizeIndex = 0;
3432   } else if (size >= 3) {
3433     sizeIndex = 1;
3434   } else {
3435     sizeIndex = 2;
3436   }
3437 
3438   if (!fontMetricsBySizeIndex[sizeIndex]) {
3439     var metrics = fontMetricsBySizeIndex[sizeIndex] = {
3440       cssEmPerMu: sigmasAndXis.quad[sizeIndex] / 18
3441     };
3442 
3443     for (var key in sigmasAndXis) {
3444       if (sigmasAndXis.hasOwnProperty(key)) {
3445         metrics[key] = sigmasAndXis[key][sizeIndex];
3446       }
3447     }
3448   }
3449 
3450   return fontMetricsBySizeIndex[sizeIndex];
3451 }
3452 
3453 /**
3454  * This file contains information about the options that the Parser carries
3455  * around with it while parsing. Data is held in an `Options` object, and when
3456  * recursing, a new `Options` object can be created with the `.with*` and
3457  * `.reset` functions.
3458  */
3459 var sizeStyleMap = [// Each element contains [textsize, scriptsize, scriptscriptsize].
3460 // The size mappings are taken from TeX with \normalsize=10pt.
3461 [1, 1, 1], // size1: [5, 5, 5]              \tiny
3462 [2, 1, 1], // size2: [6, 5, 5]
3463 [3, 1, 1], // size3: [7, 5, 5]              \scriptsize
3464 [4, 2, 1], // size4: [8, 6, 5]              \footnotesize
3465 [5, 2, 1], // size5: [9, 6, 5]              \small
3466 [6, 3, 1], // size6: [10, 7, 5]             \normalsize
3467 [7, 4, 2], // size7: [12, 8, 6]             \large
3468 [8, 6, 3], // size8: [14.4, 10, 7]          \Large
3469 [9, 7, 6], // size9: [17.28, 12, 10]        \LARGE
3470 [10, 8, 7], // size10: [20.74, 14.4, 12]     \huge
3471 [11, 10, 9] // size11: [24.88, 20.74, 17.28] \HUGE
3472 ];
3473 var sizeMultipliers = [// fontMetrics.js:getGlobalMetrics also uses size indexes, so if
3474 // you change size indexes, change that function.
3475 0.5, 0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 1.0, 1.2, 1.44, 1.728, 2.074, 2.488];
3476 
3477 var sizeAtStyle = function sizeAtStyle(size, style) {
3478   return style.size < 2 ? size : sizeStyleMap[size - 1][style.size - 1];
3479 }; // In these types, "" (empty string) means "no change".
3480 
3481 
3482 /**
3483  * This is the main options class. It contains the current style, size, color,
3484  * and font.
3485  *
3486  * Options objects should not be modified. To create a new Options with
3487  * different properties, call a `.having*` method.
3488  */
3489 class Options {
3490   // A font family applies to a group of fonts (i.e. SansSerif), while a font
3491   // represents a specific font (i.e. SansSerif Bold).
3492   // See: https://tex.stackexchange.com/questions/22350/difference-between-textrm-and-mathrm
3493 
3494   /**
3495    * The base size index.
3496    */
3497   constructor(data) {
3498     this.style = void 0;
3499     this.color = void 0;
3500     this.size = void 0;
3501     this.textSize = void 0;
3502     this.phantom = void 0;
3503     this.font = void 0;
3504     this.fontFamily = void 0;
3505     this.fontWeight = void 0;
3506     this.fontShape = void 0;
3507     this.sizeMultiplier = void 0;
3508     this.maxSize = void 0;
3509     this.minRuleThickness = void 0;
3510     this._fontMetrics = void 0;
3511     this.style = data.style;
3512     this.color = data.color;
3513     this.size = data.size || Options.BASESIZE;
3514     this.textSize = data.textSize || this.size;
3515     this.phantom = !!data.phantom;
3516     this.font = data.font || "";
3517     this.fontFamily = data.fontFamily || "";
3518     this.fontWeight = data.fontWeight || '';
3519     this.fontShape = data.fontShape || '';
3520     this.sizeMultiplier = sizeMultipliers[this.size - 1];
3521     this.maxSize = data.maxSize;
3522     this.minRuleThickness = data.minRuleThickness;
3523     this._fontMetrics = undefined;
3524   }
3525   /**
3526    * Returns a new options object with the same properties as "this".  Properties
3527    * from "extension" will be copied to the new options object.
3528    */
3529 
3530 
3531   extend(extension) {
3532     var data = {
3533       style: this.style,
3534       size: this.size,
3535       textSize: this.textSize,
3536       color: this.color,
3537       phantom: this.phantom,
3538       font: this.font,
3539       fontFamily: this.fontFamily,
3540       fontWeight: this.fontWeight,
3541       fontShape: this.fontShape,
3542       maxSize: this.maxSize,
3543       minRuleThickness: this.minRuleThickness
3544     };
3545 
3546     for (var key in extension) {
3547       if (extension.hasOwnProperty(key)) {
3548         data[key] = extension[key];
3549       }
3550     }
3551 
3552     return new Options(data);
3553   }
3554   /**
3555    * Return an options object with the given style. If `this.style === style`,
3556    * returns `this`.
3557    */
3558 
3559 
3560   havingStyle(style) {
3561     if (this.style === style) {
3562       return this;
3563     } else {
3564       return this.extend({
3565         style: style,
3566         size: sizeAtStyle(this.textSize, style)
3567       });
3568     }
3569   }
3570   /**
3571    * Return an options object with a cramped version of the current style. If
3572    * the current style is cramped, returns `this`.
3573    */
3574 
3575 
3576   havingCrampedStyle() {
3577     return this.havingStyle(this.style.cramp());
3578   }
3579   /**
3580    * Return an options object with the given size and in at least `\textstyle`.
3581    * Returns `this` if appropriate.
3582    */
3583 
3584 
3585   havingSize(size) {
3586     if (this.size === size && this.textSize === size) {
3587       return this;
3588     } else {
3589       return this.extend({
3590         style: this.style.text(),
3591         size: size,
3592         textSize: size,
3593         sizeMultiplier: sizeMultipliers[size - 1]
3594       });
3595     }
3596   }
3597   /**
3598    * Like `this.havingSize(BASESIZE).havingStyle(style)`. If `style` is omitted,
3599    * changes to at least `\textstyle`.
3600    */
3601 
3602 
3603   havingBaseStyle(style) {
3604     style = style || this.style.text();
3605     var wantSize = sizeAtStyle(Options.BASESIZE, style);
3606 
3607     if (this.size === wantSize && this.textSize === Options.BASESIZE && this.style === style) {
3608       return this;
3609     } else {
3610       return this.extend({
3611         style: style,
3612         size: wantSize
3613       });
3614     }
3615   }
3616   /**
3617    * Remove the effect of sizing changes such as \Huge.
3618    * Keep the effect of the current style, such as \scriptstyle.
3619    */
3620 
3621 
3622   havingBaseSizing() {
3623     var size;
3624 
3625     switch (this.style.id) {
3626       case 4:
3627       case 5:
3628         size = 3; // normalsize in scriptstyle
3629 
3630         break;
3631 
3632       case 6:
3633       case 7:
3634         size = 1; // normalsize in scriptscriptstyle
3635 
3636         break;
3637 
3638       default:
3639         size = 6;
3640       // normalsize in textstyle or displaystyle
3641     }
3642 
3643     return this.extend({
3644       style: this.style.text(),
3645       size: size
3646     });
3647   }
3648   /**
3649    * Create a new options object with the given color.
3650    */
3651 
3652 
3653   withColor(color) {
3654     return this.extend({
3655       color: color
3656     });
3657   }
3658   /**
3659    * Create a new options object with "phantom" set to true.
3660    */
3661 
3662 
3663   withPhantom() {
3664     return this.extend({
3665       phantom: true
3666     });
3667   }
3668   /**
3669    * Creates a new options object with the given math font or old text font.
3670    * @type {[type]}
3671    */
3672 
3673 
3674   withFont(font) {
3675     return this.extend({
3676       font
3677     });
3678   }
3679   /**
3680    * Create a new options objects with the given fontFamily.
3681    */
3682 
3683 
3684   withTextFontFamily(fontFamily) {
3685     return this.extend({
3686       fontFamily,
3687       font: ""
3688     });
3689   }
3690   /**
3691    * Creates a new options object with the given font weight
3692    */
3693 
3694 
3695   withTextFontWeight(fontWeight) {
3696     return this.extend({
3697       fontWeight,
3698       font: ""
3699     });
3700   }
3701   /**
3702    * Creates a new options object with the given font weight
3703    */
3704 
3705 
3706   withTextFontShape(fontShape) {
3707     return this.extend({
3708       fontShape,
3709       font: ""
3710     });
3711   }
3712   /**
3713    * Return the CSS sizing classes required to switch from enclosing options
3714    * `oldOptions` to `this`. Returns an array of classes.
3715    */
3716 
3717 
3718   sizingClasses(oldOptions) {
3719     if (oldOptions.size !== this.size) {
3720       return ["sizing", "reset-size" + oldOptions.size, "size" + this.size];
3721     } else {
3722       return [];
3723     }
3724   }
3725   /**
3726    * Return the CSS sizing classes required to switch to the base size. Like
3727    * `this.havingSize(BASESIZE).sizingClasses(this)`.
3728    */
3729 
3730 
3731   baseSizingClasses() {
3732     if (this.size !== Options.BASESIZE) {
3733       return ["sizing", "reset-size" + this.size, "size" + Options.BASESIZE];
3734     } else {
3735       return [];
3736     }
3737   }
3738   /**
3739    * Return the font metrics for this size.
3740    */
3741 
3742 
3743   fontMetrics() {
3744     if (!this._fontMetrics) {
3745       this._fontMetrics = getGlobalMetrics(this.size);
3746     }
3747 
3748     return this._fontMetrics;
3749   }
3750   /**
3751    * Gets the CSS color of the current options object
3752    */
3753 
3754 
3755   getColor() {
3756     if (this.phantom) {
3757       return "transparent";
3758     } else {
3759       return this.color;
3760     }
3761   }
3762 
3763 }
3764 
3765 Options.BASESIZE = 6;
3766 
3767 /**
3768  * This file does conversion between units.  In particular, it provides
3769  * calculateSize to convert other units into ems.
3770  */
3771 // Thus, multiplying a length by this number converts the length from units
3772 // into pts.  Dividing the result by ptPerEm gives the number of ems
3773 // *assuming* a font size of ptPerEm (normal size, normal style).
3774 
3775 var ptPerUnit = {
3776   // https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/LaTeX/Lengths and
3777   // https://tex.stackexchange.com/a/8263
3778   "pt": 1,
3779   // TeX point
3780   "mm": 7227 / 2540,
3781   // millimeter
3782   "cm": 7227 / 254,
3783   // centimeter
3784   "in": 72.27,
3785   // inch
3786   "bp": 803 / 800,
3787   // big (PostScript) points
3788   "pc": 12,
3789   // pica
3790   "dd": 1238 / 1157,
3791   // didot
3792   "cc": 14856 / 1157,
3793   // cicero (12 didot)
3794   "nd": 685 / 642,
3795   // new didot
3796   "nc": 1370 / 107,
3797   // new cicero (12 new didot)
3798   "sp": 1 / 65536,
3799   // scaled point (TeX's internal smallest unit)
3800   // https://tex.stackexchange.com/a/41371
3801   "px": 803 / 800 // \pdfpxdimen defaults to 1 bp in pdfTeX and LuaTeX
3802 
3803 }; // Dictionary of relative units, for fast validity testing.
3804 
3805 var relativeUnit = {
3806   "ex": true,
3807   "em": true,
3808   "mu": true
3809 };
3810 
3811 /**
3812  * Determine whether the specified unit (either a string defining the unit
3813  * or a "size" parse node containing a unit field) is valid.
3814  */
3815 var validUnit = function validUnit(unit) {
3816   if (typeof unit !== "string") {
3817     unit = unit.unit;
3818   }
3819 
3820   return unit in ptPerUnit || unit in relativeUnit || unit === "ex";
3821 };
3822 /* 
3823  * Convert a "size" parse node (with numeric "number" and string "unit" fields, 
3824  * as parsed by functions.js argType "size") into a CSS em value for the 
3825  * current style/scale.  `options` gives the current options. 
3826  */
3827 
3828 var calculateSize = function calculateSize(sizeValue, options) {
3829   var scale;
3830 
3831   if (sizeValue.unit in ptPerUnit) {
3832     // Absolute units
3833     scale = ptPerUnit[sizeValue.unit] // Convert unit to pt
3834     / options.fontMetrics().ptPerEm // Convert pt to CSS em
3835     / options.sizeMultiplier; // Unscale to make absolute units
3836   } else if (sizeValue.unit === "mu") {
3837     // `mu` units scale with scriptstyle/scriptscriptstyle.
3838     scale = options.fontMetrics().cssEmPerMu;
3839   } else {
3840     // Other relative units always refer to the *textstyle* font
3841     // in the current size.
3842     var unitOptions;
3843 
3844     if (options.style.isTight()) {
3845       // isTight() means current style is script/scriptscript.
3846       unitOptions = options.havingStyle(options.style.text());
3847     } else {
3848       unitOptions = options;
3849     } // TODO: In TeX these units are relative to the quad of the current
3850     // *text* font, e.g. cmr10. KaTeX instead uses values from the
3851     // comparably-sized *Computer Modern symbol* font. At 10pt, these
3852     // match. At 7pt and 5pt, they differ: cmr7=1.138894, cmsy7=1.170641;
3853     // cmr5=1.361133, cmsy5=1.472241. Consider $\scriptsize a\kern1emb$.
3854     // TeX \showlists shows a kern of 1.13889 * fontsize;
3855     // KaTeX shows a kern of 1.171 * fontsize.
3856 
3857 
3858     if (sizeValue.unit === "ex") {
3859       scale = unitOptions.fontMetrics().xHeight;
3860     } else if (sizeValue.unit === "em") {
3861       scale = unitOptions.fontMetrics().quad;
3862     } else {
3863       throw new ParseError("Invalid unit: '" + sizeValue.unit + "'");
3864     }
3865 
3866     if (unitOptions !== options) {
3867       scale *= unitOptions.sizeMultiplier / options.sizeMultiplier;
3868     }
3869   }
3870 
3871   return Math.min(sizeValue.number * scale, options.maxSize);
3872 };
3873 /**
3874  * Round `n` to 4 decimal places, or to the nearest 1/10,000th em. See
3875  * https://github.com/KaTeX/KaTeX/pull/2460.
3876  */
3877 
3878 var makeEm = function makeEm(n) {
3879   return +n.toFixed(4) + "em";
3880 };
3881 
3882 /**
3883  * These objects store the data about the DOM nodes we create, as well as some
3884  * extra data. They can then be transformed into real DOM nodes with the
3885  * `toNode` function or HTML markup using `toMarkup`. They are useful for both
3886  * storing extra properties on the nodes, as well as providing a way to easily
3887  * work with the DOM.
3888  *
3889  * Similar functions for working with MathML nodes exist in mathMLTree.js.
3890  *
3891  * TODO: refactor `span` and `anchor` into common superclass when
3892  * target environments support class inheritance
3893  */
3894 
3895 /**
3896  * Create an HTML className based on a list of classes. In addition to joining
3897  * with spaces, we also remove empty classes.
3898  */
3899 var createClass = function createClass(classes) {
3900   return classes.filter(cls => cls).join(" ");
3901 };
3902 
3903 var initNode = function initNode(classes, options, style) {
3904   this.classes = classes || [];
3905   this.attributes = {};
3906   this.height = 0;
3907   this.depth = 0;
3908   this.maxFontSize = 0;
3909   this.style = style || {};
3910 
3911   if (options) {
3912     if (options.style.isTight()) {
3913       this.classes.push("mtight");
3914     }
3915 
3916     var color = options.getColor();
3917 
3918     if (color) {
3919       this.style.color = color;
3920     }
3921   }
3922 };
3923 /**
3924  * Convert into an HTML node
3925  */
3926 
3927 
3928 var toNode = function toNode(tagName) {
3929   var node = document.createElement(tagName); // Apply the class
3930 
3931   node.className = createClass(this.classes); // Apply inline styles
3932 
3933   for (var style in this.style) {
3934     if (this.style.hasOwnProperty(style)) {
3935       // $FlowFixMe Flow doesn't seem to understand span.style's type.
3936       node.style[style] = this.style[style];
3937     }
3938   } // Apply attributes
3939 
3940 
3941   for (var attr in this.attributes) {
3942     if (this.attributes.hasOwnProperty(attr)) {
3943       node.setAttribute(attr, this.attributes[attr]);
3944     }
3945   } // Append the children, also as HTML nodes
3946 
3947 
3948   for (var i = 0; i < this.children.length; i++) {
3949     node.appendChild(this.children[i].toNode());
3950   }
3951 
3952   return node;
3953 };
3954 /**
3955  * https://w3c.github.io/html-reference/syntax.html#syntax-attributes
3956  *
3957  * > Attribute Names must consist of one or more characters
3958  * other than the space characters, U+0000 NULL,
3959  * '"', "'", ">", "/", "=", the control characters,
3960  * and any characters that are not defined by Unicode.
3961  */
3962 
3963 
3964 var invalidAttributeNameRegex = /[\s"'>/=\x00-\x1f]/;
3965 /**
3966  * Convert into an HTML markup string
3967  */
3968 
3969 var toMarkup = function toMarkup(tagName) {
3970   var markup = "<" + tagName; // Add the class
3971 
3972   if (this.classes.length) {
3973     markup += " class=\"" + utils.escape(createClass(this.classes)) + "\"";
3974   }
3975 
3976   var styles = ""; // Add the styles, after hyphenation
3977 
3978   for (var style in this.style) {
3979     if (this.style.hasOwnProperty(style)) {
3980       styles += utils.hyphenate(style) + ":" + this.style[style] + ";";
3981     }
3982   }
3983 
3984   if (styles) {
3985     markup += " style=\"" + utils.escape(styles) + "\"";
3986   } // Add the attributes
3987 
3988 
3989   for (var attr in this.attributes) {
3990     if (this.attributes.hasOwnProperty(attr)) {
3991       if (invalidAttributeNameRegex.test(attr)) {
3992         throw new ParseError("Invalid attribute name '" + attr + "'");
3993       }
3994 
3995       markup += " " + attr + "=\"" + utils.escape(this.attributes[attr]) + "\"";
3996     }
3997   }
3998 
3999   markup += ">"; // Add the markup of the children, also as markup
4000 
4001   for (var i = 0; i < this.children.length; i++) {
4002     markup += this.children[i].toMarkup();
4003   }
4004 
4005   markup += "</" + tagName + ">";
4006   return markup;
4007 }; // Making the type below exact with all optional fields doesn't work due to
4008 // - https://github.com/facebook/flow/issues/4582
4009 // - https://github.com/facebook/flow/issues/5688
4010 // However, since *all* fields are optional, $Shape<> works as suggested in 5688
4011 // above.
4012 // This type does not include all CSS properties. Additional properties should
4013 // be added as needed.
4014 
4015 
4016 /**
4017  * This node represents a span node, with a className, a list of children, and
4018  * an inline style. It also contains information about its height, depth, and
4019  * maxFontSize.
4020  *
4021  * Represents two types with different uses: SvgSpan to wrap an SVG and DomSpan
4022  * otherwise. This typesafety is important when HTML builders access a span's
4023  * children.
4024  */
4025 class Span {
4026   constructor(classes, children, options, style) {
4027     this.children = void 0;
4028     this.attributes = void 0;
4029     this.classes = void 0;
4030     this.height = void 0;
4031     this.depth = void 0;
4032     this.width = void 0;
4033     this.maxFontSize = void 0;
4034     this.style = void 0;
4035     initNode.call(this, classes, options, style);
4036     this.children = children || [];
4037   }
4038   /**
4039    * Sets an arbitrary attribute on the span. Warning: use this wisely. Not
4040    * all browsers support attributes the same, and having too many custom
4041    * attributes is probably bad.
4042    */
4043 
4044 
4045   setAttribute(attribute, value) {
4046     this.attributes[attribute] = value;
4047   }
4048 
4049   hasClass(className) {
4050     return utils.contains(this.classes, className);
4051   }
4052 
4053   toNode() {
4054     return toNode.call(this, "span");
4055   }
4056 
4057   toMarkup() {
4058     return toMarkup.call(this, "span");
4059   }

4157 var iCombinations = {
4158   'î': '\u0131\u0302',
4159   'ï': '\u0131\u0308',
4160   'í': '\u0131\u0301',
4161   // 'ī': '\u0131\u0304', // enable when we add Extended Latin
4162   'ì': '\u0131\u0300'
4163 };
4164 /**
4165  * A symbol node contains information about a single symbol. It either renders
4166  * to a single text node, or a span with a single text node in it, depending on
4167  * whether it has CSS classes, styles, or needs italic correction.
4168  */
4169 
4170 class SymbolNode {
4171   constructor(text, height, depth, italic, skew, width, classes, style) {
4172     this.text = void 0;
4173     this.height = void 0;
4174     this.depth = void 0;
4175     this.italic = void 0;
4176     this.skew = void 0;
4177     this.width = void 0;
4178     this.maxFontSize = void 0;
4179     this.classes = void 0;
4180     this.style = void 0;
4181     this.text = text;
4182     this.height = height || 0;
4183     this.depth = depth || 0;
4184     this.italic = italic || 0;
4185     this.skew = skew || 0;
4186     this.width = width || 0;
4187     this.classes = classes || [];
4188     this.style = style || {};
4189     this.maxFontSize = 0; // Mark text from non-Latin scripts with specific classes so that we
4190     // can specify which fonts to use.  This allows us to render these
4191     // characters with a serif font in situations where the browser would
4192     // either default to a sans serif or render a placeholder character.
4193     // We use CSS class names like cjk_fallback, hangul_fallback and
4194     // brahmic_fallback. See ./unicodeScripts.js for the set of possible
4195     // script names
4196 
4197     var script = scriptFromCodepoint(this.text.charCodeAt(0));
4198 
4199     if (script) {
4200       this.classes.push(script + "_fallback");
4201     }
4202 
4203     if (/[îïíì]/.test(this.text)) {
4204       // add ī when we add Extended Latin
4205       this.text = iCombinations[this.text];
4206     }
4207   }
4208 
4209   hasClass(className) {
4210     return utils.contains(this.classes, className);
4211   }
4212   /**
4213    * Creates a text node or span from a symbol node. Note that a span is only
4214    * created if it is needed.
4215    */
4216 
4217 
4218   toNode() {
4219     var node = document.createTextNode(this.text);
4220     var span = null;
4221 
4222     if (this.italic > 0) {
4223       span = document.createElement("span");
4224       span.style.marginRight = makeEm(this.italic);
4225     }
4226 
4227     if (this.classes.length > 0) {
4228       span = span || document.createElement("span");
4229       span.className = createClass(this.classes);
4230     }
4231 
4232     for (var style in this.style) {
4233       if (this.style.hasOwnProperty(style)) {
4234         span = span || document.createElement("span"); // $FlowFixMe Flow doesn't seem to understand span.style's type.
4235 
4236         span.style[style] = this.style[style];
4237       }
4238     }
4239 
4240     if (span) {
4241       span.appendChild(node);
4242       return span;
4243     } else {
4244       return node;
4245     }
4246   }
4247   /**
4248    * Creates markup for a symbol node.
4249    */
4250 
4251 
4252   toMarkup() {
4253     // TODO(alpert): More duplication than I'd like from
4254     // span.prototype.toMarkup and symbolNode.prototype.toNode...
4255     var needsSpan = false;
4256     var markup = "<span";
4257 
4258     if (this.classes.length) {
4259       needsSpan = true;
4260       markup += " class=\"";
4261       markup += utils.escape(createClass(this.classes));
4262       markup += "\"";
4263     }
4264 
4265     var styles = "";
4266 
4267     if (this.italic > 0) {
4268       styles += "margin-right:" + this.italic + "em;";
4269     }
4270 
4271     for (var style in this.style) {
4272       if (this.style.hasOwnProperty(style)) {
4273         styles += utils.hyphenate(style) + ":" + this.style[style] + ";";
4274       }
4275     }
4276 
4277     if (styles) {
4278       needsSpan = true;
4279       markup += " style=\"" + utils.escape(styles) + "\"";
4280     }
4281 
4282     var escaped = utils.escape(this.text);
4283 
4284     if (needsSpan) {
4285       markup += ">";
4286       markup += escaped;
4287       markup += "</span>";
4288       return markup;
4289     } else {
4290       return escaped;
4291     }
4292   }
4293 
4294 }

4422 /**
4423  * This file holds a list of all no-argument functions and single-character
4424  * symbols (like 'a' or ';').
4425  *
4426  * For each of the symbols, there are three properties they can have:
4427  * - font (required): the font to be used for this symbol. Either "main" (the
4428      normal font), or "ams" (the ams fonts).
4429  * - group (required): the ParseNode group type the symbol should have (i.e.
4430      "textord", "mathord", etc).
4431      See https://github.com/KaTeX/KaTeX/wiki/Examining-TeX#group-types
4432  * - replace: the character that this symbol or function should be
4433  *   replaced with (i.e. "\phi" has a replace value of "\u03d5", the phi
4434  *   character in the main font).
4435  *
4436  * The outermost map in the table indicates what mode the symbols should be
4437  * accepted in (e.g. "math" or "text").
4438  */
4439 // Some of these have a "-token" suffix since these are also used as `ParseNode`
4440 // types for raw text tokens, and we want to avoid conflicts with higher-level
4441 // `ParseNode` types. These `ParseNode`s are constructed within `Parser` by
4442 // looking up the `symbols` map.
4443 var ATOMS = {
4444   "bin": 1,
4445   "close": 1,
4446   "inner": 1,
4447   "open": 1,
4448   "punct": 1,
4449   "rel": 1
4450 };
4451 var NON_ATOMS = {
4452   "accent-token": 1,
4453   "mathord": 1,
4454   "op-token": 1,
4455   "spacing": 1,
4456   "textord": 1
4457 };
4458 var symbols = {
4459   "math": {},
4460   "text": {}
4461 };
4462 /** `acceptUnicodeChar = true` is only applicable if `replace` is set. */
4463 
4464 function defineSymbol(mode, font, group, replace, name, acceptUnicodeChar) {
4465   symbols[mode][name] = {
4466     font,
4467     group,
4468     replace
4469   };
4470 
4471   if (acceptUnicodeChar && replace) {
4472     symbols[mode][replace] = symbols[mode][name];
4473   }
4474 } // Some abbreviations for commonly used strings.
4475 // This helps minify the code, and also spotting typos using jshint.
4476 // modes:
4477 
4478 var math = "math";
4479 var text = "text"; // fonts:
4480 
4481 var main = "main";
4482 var ams = "ams"; // groups:
4483 
4484 var accent = "accent-token";
4485 var bin = "bin";
4486 var close = "close";
4487 var inner = "inner";
4488 var mathord = "mathord";
4489 var op = "op-token";
4490 var open = "open";
4491 var punct = "punct";
4492 var rel = "rel";
4493 var spacing = "spacing";
4494 var textord = "textord"; // Now comes the symbol table

5151 defineSymbol(text, ams, textord, "\u2720", "\\maltese"); // There are lots of symbols which are the same, so we add them in afterwards.
5152 // All of these are textords in math mode
5153 
5154 var mathTextSymbols = "0123456789/@.\"";
5155 
5156 for (var i = 0; i < mathTextSymbols.length; i++) {
5157   var ch = mathTextSymbols.charAt(i);
5158   defineSymbol(math, main, textord, ch, ch);
5159 } // All of these are textords in text mode
5160 
5161 
5162 var textSymbols = "0123456789!@*()-=+\";:?/.,";
5163 
5164 for (var _i = 0; _i < textSymbols.length; _i++) {
5165   var _ch = textSymbols.charAt(_i);
5166 
5167   defineSymbol(text, main, textord, _ch, _ch);
5168 } // All of these are textords in text mode, and mathords in math mode
5169 
5170 
5171 var letters = "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz";
5172 
5173 for (var _i2 = 0; _i2 < letters.length; _i2++) {
5174   var _ch2 = letters.charAt(_i2);
5175 
5176   defineSymbol(math, main, mathord, _ch2, _ch2);
5177   defineSymbol(text, main, textord, _ch2, _ch2);
5178 } // Blackboard bold and script letters in Unicode range
5179 
5180 
5181 defineSymbol(math, ams, textord, "C", "\u2102"); // blackboard bold
5182 
5183 defineSymbol(text, ams, textord, "C", "\u2102");
5184 defineSymbol(math, ams, textord, "H", "\u210D");
5185 defineSymbol(text, ams, textord, "H", "\u210D");
5186 defineSymbol(math, ams, textord, "N", "\u2115");
5187 defineSymbol(text, ams, textord, "N", "\u2115");
5188 defineSymbol(math, ams, textord, "P", "\u2119");
5189 defineSymbol(text, ams, textord, "P", "\u2119");
5190 defineSymbol(math, ams, textord, "Q", "\u211A");
5191 defineSymbol(text, ams, textord, "Q", "\u211A");
5192 defineSymbol(math, ams, textord, "R", "\u211D");
5193 defineSymbol(text, ams, textord, "R", "\u211D");
5194 defineSymbol(math, ams, textord, "Z", "\u2124");
5195 defineSymbol(text, ams, textord, "Z", "\u2124");
5196 defineSymbol(math, main, mathord, "h", "\u210E"); // italic h, Planck constant
5197 
5198 defineSymbol(text, main, mathord, "h", "\u210E"); // The next loop loads wide (surrogate pair) characters.
5199 // We support some letters in the Unicode range U+1D400 to U+1D7FF,
5200 // Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols.
5201 // Some editors do not deal well with wide characters. So don't write the
5202 // string into this file. Instead, create the string from the surrogate pair.
5203 
5204 var wideChar = "";
5205 
5206 for (var _i3 = 0; _i3 < letters.length; _i3++) {
5207   var _ch3 = letters.charAt(_i3); // The hex numbers in the next line are a surrogate pair.
5208   // 0xD835 is the high surrogate for all letters in the range we support.
5209   // 0xDC00 is the low surrogate for bold A.
5210 
5211 
5212   wideChar = String.fromCharCode(0xD835, 0xDC00 + _i3); // A-Z a-z bold
5213 
5214   defineSymbol(math, main, mathord, _ch3, wideChar);
5215   defineSymbol(text, main, textord, _ch3, wideChar);
5216   wideChar = String.fromCharCode(0xD835, 0xDC34 + _i3); // A-Z a-z italic
5217 
5218   defineSymbol(math, main, mathord, _ch3, wideChar);

5303 
5304 /**
5305  * This file provides support for Unicode range U+1D400 to U+1D7FF,
5306  * Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols.
5307  *
5308  * Function wideCharacterFont takes a wide character as input and returns
5309  * the font information necessary to render it properly.
5310  */
5311 /**
5312  * Data below is from https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U1D400.pdf
5313  * That document sorts characters into groups by font type, say bold or italic.
5314  *
5315  * In the arrays below, each subarray consists three elements:
5316  *      * The CSS class of that group when in math mode.
5317  *      * The CSS class of that group when in text mode.
5318  *      * The font name, so that KaTeX can get font metrics.
5319  */
5320 
5321 var wideLatinLetterData = [["mathbf", "textbf", "Main-Bold"], // A-Z bold upright
5322 ["mathbf", "textbf", "Main-Bold"], // a-z bold upright
5323 ["mathnormal", "textit", "Math-Italic"], // A-Z italic
5324 ["mathnormal", "textit", "Math-Italic"], // a-z italic
5325 ["boldsymbol", "boldsymbol", "Main-BoldItalic"], // A-Z bold italic
5326 ["boldsymbol", "boldsymbol", "Main-BoldItalic"], // a-z bold italic
5327 // Map fancy A-Z letters to script, not calligraphic.
5328 // This aligns with unicode-math and math fonts (except Cambria Math).
5329 ["mathscr", "textscr", "Script-Regular"], // A-Z script
5330 ["", "", ""], // a-z script.  No font
5331 ["", "", ""], // A-Z bold script. No font
5332 ["", "", ""], // a-z bold script. No font
5333 ["mathfrak", "textfrak", "Fraktur-Regular"], // A-Z Fraktur
5334 ["mathfrak", "textfrak", "Fraktur-Regular"], // a-z Fraktur
5335 ["mathbb", "textbb", "AMS-Regular"], // A-Z double-struck
5336 ["mathbb", "textbb", "AMS-Regular"], // k double-struck
5337 // Note that we are using a bold font, but font metrics for regular Fraktur.
5338 ["mathboldfrak", "textboldfrak", "Fraktur-Regular"], // A-Z bold Fraktur
5339 ["mathboldfrak", "textboldfrak", "Fraktur-Regular"], // a-z bold Fraktur
5340 ["mathsf", "textsf", "SansSerif-Regular"], // A-Z sans-serif
5341 ["mathsf", "textsf", "SansSerif-Regular"], // a-z sans-serif
5342 ["mathboldsf", "textboldsf", "SansSerif-Bold"], // A-Z bold sans-serif
5343 ["mathboldsf", "textboldsf", "SansSerif-Bold"], // a-z bold sans-serif
5344 ["mathitsf", "textitsf", "SansSerif-Italic"], // A-Z italic sans-serif
5345 ["mathitsf", "textitsf", "SansSerif-Italic"], // a-z italic sans-serif
5346 ["", "", ""], // A-Z bold italic sans. No font
5347 ["", "", ""], // a-z bold italic sans. No font
5348 ["mathtt", "texttt", "Typewriter-Regular"], // A-Z monospace
5349 ["mathtt", "texttt", "Typewriter-Regular"] // a-z monospace
5350 ];
5351 var wideNumeralData = [["mathbf", "textbf", "Main-Bold"], // 0-9 bold
5352 ["", "", ""], // 0-9 double-struck. No KaTeX font.
5353 ["mathsf", "textsf", "SansSerif-Regular"], // 0-9 sans-serif
5354 ["mathboldsf", "textboldsf", "SansSerif-Bold"], // 0-9 bold sans-serif
5355 ["mathtt", "texttt", "Typewriter-Regular"] // 0-9 monospace
5356 ];
5357 var wideCharacterFont = function wideCharacterFont(wideChar, mode) {
5358   // IE doesn't support codePointAt(). So work with the surrogate pair.
5359   var H = wideChar.charCodeAt(0); // high surrogate
5360 
5361   var L = wideChar.charCodeAt(1); // low surrogate
5362 
5363   var codePoint = (H - 0xD800) * 0x400 + (L - 0xDC00) + 0x10000;
5364   var j = mode === "math" ? 0 : 1; // column index for CSS class.
5365 
5366   if (0x1D400 <= codePoint && codePoint < 0x1D6A4) {
5367     // wideLatinLetterData contains exactly 26 chars on each row.
5368     // So we can calculate the relevant row. No traverse necessary.
5369     var i = Math.floor((codePoint - 0x1D400) / 26);
5370     return [wideLatinLetterData[i][2], wideLatinLetterData[i][j]];
5371   } else if (0x1D7CE <= codePoint && codePoint <= 0x1D7FF) {
5372     // Numerals, ten per row.
5373     var _i = Math.floor((codePoint - 0x1D7CE) / 10);
5374 
5375     return [wideNumeralData[_i][2], wideNumeralData[_i][j]];
5376   } else if (codePoint === 0x1D6A5 || codePoint === 0x1D6A6) {
5377     // dotless i or j
5378     return [wideLatinLetterData[0][2], wideLatinLetterData[0][j]];
5379   } else if (0x1D6A6 < codePoint && codePoint < 0x1D7CE) {
5380     // Greek letters. Not supported, yet.
5381     return ["", ""];
5382   } else {
5383     // We don't support any wide characters outside 1D400–1D7FF.
5384     throw new ParseError("Unsupported character: " + wideChar);
5385   }
5386 };
5387 
5388 /* eslint no-console:0 */
5389 
5390 /**
5391  * Looks up the given symbol in fontMetrics, after applying any symbol
5392  * replacements defined in symbol.js
5393  */
5394 var lookupSymbol = function lookupSymbol(value, // TODO(#963): Use a union type for this.
5395 fontName, mode) {
5396   // Replace the value with its replaced value from symbol.js
5397   if (symbols[mode][value] && symbols[mode][value].replace) {
5398     value = symbols[mode][value].replace;
5399   }
5400 
5401   return {
5402     value: value,
5403     metrics: getCharacterMetrics(value, fontName, mode)
5404   };
5405 };
5406 /**
5407  * Makes a symbolNode after translation via the list of symbols in symbols.js.
5408  * Correctly pulls out metrics for the character, and optionally takes a list of
5409  * classes to be attached to the node.
5410  *
5411  * TODO: make argument order closer to makeSpan
5412  * TODO: add a separate argument for math class (e.g. `mop`, `mbin`), which
5413  * should if present come first in `classes`.
5414  * TODO(#953): Make `options` mandatory and always pass it in.
5415  */
5416 
5417 
5418 var makeSymbol = function makeSymbol(value, fontName, mode, options, classes) {
5419   var lookup = lookupSymbol(value, fontName, mode);
5420   var metrics = lookup.metrics;
5421   value = lookup.value;
5422   var symbolNode;
5423 
5424   if (metrics) {
5425     var italic = metrics.italic;
5426 
5427     if (mode === "text" || options && options.font === "mathit") {
5428       italic = 0;
5429     }
5430 
5431     symbolNode = new SymbolNode(value, metrics.height, metrics.depth, italic, metrics.skew, metrics.width, classes);
5432   } else {
5433     // TODO(emily): Figure out a good way to only print this in development
5434     typeof console !== "undefined" && console.warn("No character metrics " + ("for '" + value + "' in style '" + fontName + "' and mode '" + mode + "'"));
5435     symbolNode = new SymbolNode(value, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, classes);
5436   }
5437 
5438   if (options) {
5439     symbolNode.maxFontSize = options.sizeMultiplier;
5440 
5441     if (options.style.isTight()) {
5442       symbolNode.classes.push("mtight");
5443     }
5444 
5445     var color = options.getColor();
5446 
5447     if (color) {
5448       symbolNode.style.color = color;
5449     }
5450   }
5451 
5452   return symbolNode;
5453 };
5454 /**
5455  * Makes a symbol in Main-Regular or AMS-Regular.
5456  * Used for rel, bin, open, close, inner, and punct.
5457  */
5458 
5459 
5460 var mathsym = function mathsym(value, mode, options, classes) {
5461   if (classes === void 0) {
5462     classes = [];
5463   }
5464 
5465   // Decide what font to render the symbol in by its entry in the symbols
5466   // table.
5467   // Have a special case for when the value = \ because the \ is used as a
5468   // textord in unsupported command errors but cannot be parsed as a regular
5469   // text ordinal and is therefore not present as a symbol in the symbols
5470   // table for text, as well as a special case for boldsymbol because it
5471   // can be used for bold + and -
5472   if (options.font === "boldsymbol" && lookupSymbol(value, "Main-Bold", mode).metrics) {
5473     return makeSymbol(value, "Main-Bold", mode, options, classes.concat(["mathbf"]));
5474   } else if (value === "\\" || symbols[mode][value].font === "main") {
5475     return makeSymbol(value, "Main-Regular", mode, options, classes);
5476   } else {
5477     return makeSymbol(value, "AMS-Regular", mode, options, classes.concat(["amsrm"]));
5478   }
5479 };
5480 /**
5481  * Determines which of the two font names (Main-Bold and Math-BoldItalic) and
5482  * corresponding style tags (mathbf or boldsymbol) to use for font "boldsymbol",
5483  * depending on the symbol.  Use this function instead of fontMap for font
5484  * "boldsymbol".
5485  */
5486 
5487 
5488 var boldsymbol = function boldsymbol(value, mode, options, classes, type) {
5489   if (type !== "textord" && lookupSymbol(value, "Math-BoldItalic", mode).metrics) {
5490     return {
5491       fontName: "Math-BoldItalic",
5492       fontClass: "boldsymbol"
5493     };
5494   } else {
5495     // Some glyphs do not exist in Math-BoldItalic so we need to use
5496     // Main-Bold instead.
5497     return {
5498       fontName: "Main-Bold",
5499       fontClass: "mathbf"
5500     };
5501   }
5502 };
5503 /**
5504  * Makes either a mathord or textord in the correct font and color.
5505  */
5506 
5507 
5508 var makeOrd = function makeOrd(group, options, type) {
5509   var mode = group.mode;
5510   var text = group.text;
5511   var classes = ["mord"]; // Math mode or Old font (i.e. \rm)
5512 
5513   var isFont = mode === "math" || mode === "text" && options.font;
5514   var fontOrFamily = isFont ? options.font : options.fontFamily;
5515   var wideFontName = "";
5516   var wideFontClass = "";
5517 
5518   if (text.charCodeAt(0) === 0xD835) {
5519     [wideFontName, wideFontClass] = wideCharacterFont(text, mode);
5520   }
5521 
5522   if (wideFontName.length > 0) {
5523     // surrogate pairs get special treatment
5524     return makeSymbol(text, wideFontName, mode, options, classes.concat(wideFontClass));
5525   } else if (fontOrFamily) {
5526     var fontName;
5527     var fontClasses;
5528 
5529     if (fontOrFamily === "boldsymbol") {
5530       var fontData = boldsymbol(text, mode, options, classes, type);
5531       fontName = fontData.fontName;
5532       fontClasses = [fontData.fontClass];
5533     } else if (isFont) {
5534       fontName = fontMap[fontOrFamily].fontName;
5535       fontClasses = [fontOrFamily];
5536     } else {
5537       fontName = retrieveTextFontName(fontOrFamily, options.fontWeight, options.fontShape);
5538       fontClasses = [fontOrFamily, options.fontWeight, options.fontShape];
5539     }
5540 
5541     if (lookupSymbol(text, fontName, mode).metrics) {
5542       return makeSymbol(text, fontName, mode, options, classes.concat(fontClasses));
5543     } else if (ligatures.hasOwnProperty(text) && fontName.slice(0, 10) === "Typewriter") {
5544       // Deconstruct ligatures in monospace fonts (\texttt, \tt).
5545       var parts = [];
5546 
5547       for (var i = 0; i < text.length; i++) {
5548         parts.push(makeSymbol(text[i], fontName, mode, options, classes.concat(fontClasses)));
5549       }
5550 
5551       return makeFragment(parts);
5552     }
5553   } // Makes a symbol in the default font for mathords and textords.
5554 
5555 
5556   if (type === "mathord") {
5557     return makeSymbol(text, "Math-Italic", mode, options, classes.concat(["mathnormal"]));
5558   } else if (type === "textord") {
5559     var font = symbols[mode][text] && symbols[mode][text].font;
5560 
5561     if (font === "ams") {
5562       var _fontName = retrieveTextFontName("amsrm", options.fontWeight, options.fontShape);
5563 
5564       return makeSymbol(text, _fontName, mode, options, classes.concat("amsrm", options.fontWeight, options.fontShape));
5565     } else if (font === "main" || !font) {
5566       var _fontName2 = retrieveTextFontName("textrm", options.fontWeight, options.fontShape);
5567 
5568       return makeSymbol(text, _fontName2, mode, options, classes.concat(options.fontWeight, options.fontShape));
5569     } else {
5570       // fonts added by plugins
5571       var _fontName3 = retrieveTextFontName(font, options.fontWeight, options.fontShape); // We add font name as a css class
5572 
5573 
5574       return makeSymbol(text, _fontName3, mode, options, classes.concat(_fontName3, options.fontWeight, options.fontShape));
5575     }
5576   } else {
5577     throw new Error("unexpected type: " + type + " in makeOrd");
5578   }
5579 };
5580 /**
5581  * Returns true if subsequent symbolNodes have the same classes, skew, maxFont,
5582  * and styles.
5583  */
5584 
5585 
5586 var canCombine = (prev, next) => {
5587   if (createClass(prev.classes) !== createClass(next.classes) || prev.skew !== next.skew || prev.maxFontSize !== next.maxFontSize) {
5588     return false;
5589   } // If prev and next both are just "mbin"s or "mord"s we don't combine them
5590   // so that the proper spacing can be preserved.
5591 
5592 
5593   if (prev.classes.length === 1) {
5594     var cls = prev.classes[0];
5595 
5596     if (cls === "mbin" || cls === "mord") {
5597       return false;
5598     }
5599   }
5600 
5601   for (var style in prev.style) {
5602     if (prev.style.hasOwnProperty(style) && prev.style[style] !== next.style[style]) {
5603       return false;
5604     }
5605   }
5606 
5607   for (var _style in next.style) {
5608     if (next.style.hasOwnProperty(_style) && prev.style[_style] !== next.style[_style]) {
5609       return false;
5610     }
5611   }
5612 
5613   return true;
5614 };
5615 /**
5616  * Combine consecutive domTree.symbolNodes into a single symbolNode.
5617  * Note: this function mutates the argument.
5618  */
5619 
5620 
5621 var tryCombineChars = chars => {
5622   for (var i = 0; i < chars.length - 1; i++) {
5623     var prev = chars[i];
5624     var next = chars[i + 1];
5625 
5626     if (prev instanceof SymbolNode && next instanceof SymbolNode && canCombine(prev, next)) {
5627       prev.text += next.text;
5628       prev.height = Math.max(prev.height, next.height);
5629       prev.depth = Math.max(prev.depth, next.depth); // Use the last character's italic correction since we use
5630       // it to add padding to the right of the span created from
5631       // the combined characters.
5632 
5633       prev.italic = next.italic;
5634       chars.splice(i + 1, 1);
5635       i--;
5636     }
5637   }
5638 
5639   return chars;
5640 };
5641 /**
5642  * Calculate the height, depth, and maxFontSize of an element based on its
5643  * children.
5644  */
5645 
5646 
5647 var sizeElementFromChildren = function sizeElementFromChildren(elem) {
5648   var height = 0;
5649   var depth = 0;
5650   var maxFontSize = 0;
5651 
5652   for (var i = 0; i < elem.children.length; i++) {
5653     var child = elem.children[i];
5654 
5655     if (child.height > height) {
5656       height = child.height;
5657     }
5658 
5659     if (child.depth > depth) {
5660       depth = child.depth;
5661     }
5662 
5663     if (child.maxFontSize > maxFontSize) {
5664       maxFontSize = child.maxFontSize;
5665     }
5666   }
5667 
5668   elem.height = height;
5669   elem.depth = depth;
5670   elem.maxFontSize = maxFontSize;
5671 };
5672 /**
5673  * Makes a span with the given list of classes, list of children, and options.
5674  *
5675  * TODO(#953): Ensure that `options` is always provided (currently some call
5676  * sites don't pass it) and make the type below mandatory.
5677  * TODO: add a separate argument for math class (e.g. `mop`, `mbin`), which
5678  * should if present come first in `classes`.
5679  */
5680 
5681 
5682 var makeSpan$2 = function makeSpan(classes, children, options, style) {
5683   var span = new Span(classes, children, options, style);
5684   sizeElementFromChildren(span);
5685   return span;
5686 }; // SVG one is simpler -- doesn't require height, depth, max-font setting.

5692 var makeLineSpan = function makeLineSpan(className, options, thickness) {
5693   var line = makeSpan$2([className], [], options);
5694   line.height = Math.max(thickness || options.fontMetrics().defaultRuleThickness, options.minRuleThickness);
5695   line.style.borderBottomWidth = makeEm(line.height);
5696   line.maxFontSize = 1.0;
5697   return line;
5698 };
