5732 }; // These are exact object types to catch typos in the names of the optional fields.
5733 
5734 
5735 // Computes the updated `children` list and the overall depth.
5736 //
5737 // This helper function for makeVList makes it easier to enforce type safety by
5738 // allowing early exits (returns) in the logic.
5739 var getVListChildrenAndDepth = function getVListChildrenAndDepth(params) {
5740   if (params.positionType === "individualShift") {
5741     var oldChildren = params.children;
5742     var children = [oldChildren[0]]; // Add in kerns to the list of params.children to get each element to be
5743     // shifted to the correct specified shift
5744 
5745     var _depth = -oldChildren[0].shift - oldChildren[0].elem.depth;
5746 
5747     var currPos = _depth;
5748 
5749     for (var i = 1; i < oldChildren.length; i++) {
5750       var diff = -oldChildren[i].shift - currPos - oldChildren[i].elem.depth;
5751       var size = diff - (oldChildren[i - 1].elem.height + oldChildren[i - 1].elem.depth);
5752       currPos = currPos + diff;
5753       children.push({
5754         type: "kern",
5755         size
5756       });
5757       children.push(oldChildren[i]);
5758     }
5759 
5760     return {
5761       children,
5762       depth: _depth
5763     };
5764   }
5765 
5766   var depth;
5767 
5768   if (params.positionType === "top") {
5769     // We always start at the bottom, so calculate the bottom by adding up
5770     // all the sizes
5771     var bottom = params.positionData;
5772 
5773     for (var _i = 0; _i < params.children.length; _i++) {
5774       var child = params.children[_i];
5775       bottom -= child.type === "kern" ? child.size : child.elem.height + child.elem.depth;
5776     }
5777 
5778     depth = bottom;
5779   } else if (params.positionType === "bottom") {
5780     depth = -params.positionData;
5781   } else {
5782     var firstChild = params.children[0];
5783 
5784     if (firstChild.type !== "elem") {
5785       throw new Error('First child must have type "elem".');
5786     }
5787 
5788     if (params.positionType === "shift") {
5789       depth = -firstChild.elem.depth - params.positionData;
5790     } else if (params.positionType === "firstBaseline") {
5791       depth = -firstChild.elem.depth;
5792     } else {
5793       throw new Error("Invalid positionType " + params.positionType + ".");
5794     }
5795   }
5796 
5797   return {
5798     children: params.children,
5799     depth
5800   };
5801 };
5802 /**
5803  * Makes a vertical list by stacking elements and kerns on top of each other.
5804  * Allows for many different ways of specifying the positioning method.
5805  *
5806  * See VListParam documentation above.
5807  */
5808 
5809 
5810 var makeVList = function makeVList(params, options) {
5811   var {
5812     children,
5813     depth
5814   } = getVListChildrenAndDepth(params); // Create a strut that is taller than any list item. The strut is added to
5815   // each item, where it will determine the item's baseline. Since it has
5816   // `overflow:hidden`, the strut's top edge will sit on the item's line box's
5817   // top edge and the strut's bottom edge will sit on the item's baseline,
5818   // with no additional line-height spacing. This allows the item baseline to
5819   // be positioned precisely without worrying about font ascent and
5820   // line-height.
5821 
5822   var pstrutSize = 0;
5823 
5824   for (var i = 0; i < children.length; i++) {
5825     var child = children[i];
5826 
5827     if (child.type === "elem") {
5828       var elem = child.elem;
5829       pstrutSize = Math.max(pstrutSize, elem.maxFontSize, elem.height);
5830     }
5831   }
5832 
5833   pstrutSize += 2;
5834   var pstrut = makeSpan$2(["pstrut"], []);
5835   pstrut.style.height = makeEm(pstrutSize); // Create a new list of actual children at the correct offsets
5836 
5837   var realChildren = [];
5838   var minPos = depth;
5839   var maxPos = depth;
5840   var currPos = depth;
5841 
5842   for (var _i2 = 0; _i2 < children.length; _i2++) {
5843     var _child = children[_i2];
5844 
5845     if (_child.type === "kern") {
5846       currPos += _child.size;
5847     } else {
5848       var _elem = _child.elem;
5849       var classes = _child.wrapperClasses || [];
5850       var style = _child.wrapperStyle || {};
5851       var childWrap = makeSpan$2(classes, [pstrut, _elem], undefined, style);
5852       childWrap.style.top = makeEm(-pstrutSize - currPos - _elem.depth);
5853 
5854       if (_child.marginLeft) {
5855         childWrap.style.marginLeft = _child.marginLeft;
5856       }
5857 
5858       if (_child.marginRight) {
5859         childWrap.style.marginRight = _child.marginRight;
5860       }
5861 
5862       realChildren.push(childWrap);
5863       currPos += _elem.height + _elem.depth;
5864     }
5865 
5866     minPos = Math.min(minPos, currPos);
5867     maxPos = Math.max(maxPos, currPos);
5868   } // The vlist contents go in a table-cell with `vertical-align:bottom`.
5869   // This cell's bottom edge will determine the containing table's baseline
5870   // without overly expanding the containing line-box.
5871 
5872 
5873   var vlist = makeSpan$2(["vlist"], realChildren);
5874   vlist.style.height = makeEm(maxPos); // A second row is used if necessary to represent the vlist's depth.
5875 
5876   var rows;
5877 
5878   if (minPos < 0) {
5879     // We will define depth in an empty span with display: table-cell.
5880     // It should render with the height that we define. But Chrome, in
5881     // contenteditable mode only, treats that span as if it contains some
5882     // text content. And that min-height over-rides our desired height.
5883     // So we put another empty span inside the depth strut span.
5884     var emptySpan = makeSpan$2([], []);
5885     var depthStrut = makeSpan$2(["vlist"], [emptySpan]);
5886     depthStrut.style.height = makeEm(-minPos); // Safari wants the first row to have inline content; otherwise it
5887     // puts the bottom of the *second* row on the baseline.
5888 
5889     var topStrut = makeSpan$2(["vlist-s"], [new SymbolNode("\u200b")]);
5890     rows = [makeSpan$2(["vlist-r"], [vlist, topStrut]), makeSpan$2(["vlist-r"], [depthStrut])];
5891   } else {
5892     rows = [makeSpan$2(["vlist-r"], [vlist])];
5893   }
5894 
5895   var vtable = makeSpan$2(["vlist-t"], rows);
5896 
5897   if (rows.length === 2) {
5898     vtable.classes.push("vlist-t2");
5899   }
5900 
5901   vtable.height = maxPos;
5902   vtable.depth = -minPos;
5903   return vtable;
5904 }; // Glue is a concept from TeX which is a flexible space between elements in
5905 // either a vertical or horizontal list. In KaTeX, at least for now, it's
5906 // static space between elements in a horizontal layout.
5907 
5908 
5909 var makeGlue = (measurement, options) => {
5910   // Make an empty span for the space
5911   var rule = makeSpan$2(["mspace"], [], options);
5912   var size = calculateSize(measurement, options);
5913   rule.style.marginRight = makeEm(size);
5914   return rule;
5915 }; // Takes font options, and returns the appropriate fontLookup name
5916 
5917 
5918 var retrieveTextFontName = function retrieveTextFontName(fontFamily, fontWeight, fontShape) {
5919   var baseFontName = "";
5920 
5921   switch (fontFamily) {
5922     case "amsrm":
5923       baseFontName = "AMS";
5924       break;
5925 
5926     case "textrm":
5927       baseFontName = "Main";
5928       break;
5929 
5930     case "textsf":
5931       baseFontName = "SansSerif";
5932       break;
5933 
5934     case "texttt":
5935       baseFontName = "Typewriter";
5936       break;
5937 
5938     default:
5939       baseFontName = fontFamily;
5940     // use fonts added by a plugin
5941   }
5942 
5943   var fontStylesName;
5944 
5945   if (fontWeight === "textbf" && fontShape === "textit") {
5946     fontStylesName = "BoldItalic";
5947   } else if (fontWeight === "textbf") {
5948     fontStylesName = "Bold";
5949   } else if (fontWeight === "textit") {
5950     fontStylesName = "Italic";
5951   } else {
5952     fontStylesName = "Regular";
5953   }
5954 
5955   return baseFontName + "-" + fontStylesName;
5956 };

6031 var staticSvg = function staticSvg(value, options) {
6032   // Create a span with inline SVG for the element.
6033   var [pathName, width, height] = svgData[value];
6034   var path = new PathNode(pathName);
6035   var svgNode = new SvgNode([path], {
6036     "width": makeEm(width),
6037     "height": makeEm(height),
6038     // Override CSS rule `.katex svg { width: 100% }`
6039     "style": "width:" + makeEm(width),
6040     "viewBox": "0 0 " + 1000 * width + " " + 1000 * height,
6041     "preserveAspectRatio": "xMinYMin"
6042   });
6043   var span = makeSvgSpan(["overlay"], [svgNode], options);
6044   span.height = height;
6045   span.style.height = makeEm(height);
6046   span.style.width = makeEm(width);
6047   return span;
6048 };

6161 /** Context provided to function handlers for error messages. */
6162 // Note: reverse the order of the return type union will cause a flow error.
6163 // See https://github.com/facebook/flow/issues/3663.
6164 // More general version of `HtmlBuilder` for nodes (e.g. \sum, accent types)
6165 // whose presence impacts super/subscripting. In this case, ParseNode<"supsub">
6166 // delegates its HTML building to the HtmlBuilder corresponding to these nodes.

6168 /**
6169  * Final function spec for use at parse time.
6170  * This is almost identical to `FunctionPropSpec`, except it
6171  * 1. includes the function handler, and
6172  * 2. requires all arguments except argTypes.
6173  * It is generated by `defineFunction()` below.
6174  */
6175 
6176 /**
6177  * All registered functions.
6178  * `functions.js` just exports this same dictionary again and makes it public.
6179  * `Parser.js` requires this dictionary.
6180  */
6181 var _functions = {};
6182 /**
6183  * All HTML builders. Should be only used in the `define*` and the `build*ML`
6184  * functions.
6185  */
6186 
6187 var _htmlGroupBuilders = {};
6188 /**
6189  * All MathML builders. Should be only used in the `define*` and the `build*ML`
6190  * functions.
6191  */
6192 
6193 var _mathmlGroupBuilders = {};
6194 function defineFunction(_ref) {
6195   var {
6196     type,
6197     names,
6198     props,
6199     handler,
6200     htmlBuilder,
6201     mathmlBuilder
6202   } = _ref;
6203   // Set default values of functions
6204   var data = {
6205     type,
6206     numArgs: props.numArgs,
6207     argTypes: props.argTypes,
6208     allowedInArgument: !!props.allowedInArgument,
6209     allowedInText: !!props.allowedInText,
6210     allowedInMath: props.allowedInMath === undefined ? true : props.allowedInMath,
6211     numOptionalArgs: props.numOptionalArgs || 0,
6212     infix: !!props.infix,
6213     primitive: !!props.primitive,
6214     handler: handler
6215   };
6216 
6217   for (var i = 0; i < names.length; ++i) {
6218     _functions[names[i]] = data;
6219   }
6220 
6221   if (type) {
6222     if (htmlBuilder) {
6223       _htmlGroupBuilders[type] = htmlBuilder;
6224     }
6225 
6226     if (mathmlBuilder) {
6227       _mathmlGroupBuilders[type] = mathmlBuilder;
6228     }
6229   }
6230 }
6231 /**
6232  * Use this to register only the HTML and MathML builders for a function (e.g.
6233  * if the function's ParseNode is generated in Parser.js rather than via a
6234  * stand-alone handler provided to `defineFunction`).
6235  */
6236 
6237 function defineFunctionBuilders(_ref2) {
6238   var {
6239     type,
6240     htmlBuilder,
6241     mathmlBuilder
6242   } = _ref2;
6243   defineFunction({
6244     type,
6245     names: [],
6246     props: {
6247       numArgs: 0
6248     },
6249 
6250     handler() {
6251       throw new Error('Should never be called.');
6252     },
6253 
6254     htmlBuilder,
6255     mathmlBuilder
6256   });
6257 }
6258 var normalizeArgument = function normalizeArgument(arg) {
6259   return arg.type === "ordgroup" && arg.body.length === 1 ? arg.body[0] : arg;
6260 }; // Since the corresponding buildHTML/buildMathML function expects a
6261 // list of elements, we normalize for different kinds of arguments
6262 
6263 var ordargument = function ordargument(arg) {
6264   return arg.type === "ordgroup" ? arg.body : [arg];
6265 };
6266 
6267 /**
6268  * This file does the main work of building a domTree structure from a parse
6269  * tree. The entry point is the `buildHTML` function, which takes a parse tree.
6270  * Then, the buildExpression, buildGroup, and various groupBuilders functions
6271  * are called, to produce a final HTML tree.
6272  */
6273 var makeSpan$1 = buildCommon.makeSpan; // Binary atoms (first class `mbin`) change into ordinary atoms (`mord`)
6274 // depending on their surroundings. See TeXbook pg. 442-446, Rules 5 and 6,
6275 // and the text before Rule 19.
6276 
6277 var binLeftCanceller = ["leftmost", "mbin", "mopen", "mrel", "mop", "mpunct"];
6278 var binRightCanceller = ["rightmost", "mrel", "mclose", "mpunct"];
6279 var styleMap$1 = {
6280   "display": Style$1.DISPLAY,
6281   "text": Style$1.TEXT,
6282   "script": Style$1.SCRIPT,
6283   "scriptscript": Style$1.SCRIPTSCRIPT
6284 };
6285 var DomEnum = {
6286   mord: "mord",
6287   mop: "mop",
6288   mbin: "mbin",
6289   mrel: "mrel",
6290   mopen: "mopen",
6291   mclose: "mclose",
6292   mpunct: "mpunct",
6293   minner: "minner"
6294 };
6295 
6296 /**
6297  * Take a list of nodes, build them in order, and return a list of the built
6298  * nodes. documentFragments are flattened into their contents, so the
6299  * returned list contains no fragments. `isRealGroup` is true if `expression`
6300  * is a real group (no atoms will be added on either side), as opposed to
6301  * a partial group (e.g. one created by \color). `surrounding` is an array
6302  * consisting type of nodes that will be added to the left and right.
6303  */
6304 var buildExpression$1 = function buildExpression(expression, options, isRealGroup, surrounding) {
6305   if (surrounding === void 0) {
6306     surrounding = [null, null];
6307   }
6308 
6309   // Parse expressions into `groups`.
6310   var groups = [];
6311 
6312   for (var i = 0; i < expression.length; i++) {
6313     var output = buildGroup$1(expression[i], options);
6314 
6315     if (output instanceof DocumentFragment) {
6316       var children = output.children;
6317       groups.push(...children);
6318     } else {
6319       groups.push(output);
6320     }
6321   } // Combine consecutive domTree.symbolNodes into a single symbolNode.
6322 
6323 
6324   buildCommon.tryCombineChars(groups); // If `expression` is a partial group, let the parent handle spacings
6325   // to avoid processing groups multiple times.
6326 
6327   if (!isRealGroup) {
6328     return groups;
6329   }
6330 
6331   var glueOptions = options;
6332 
6333   if (expression.length === 1) {
6334     var node = expression[0];
6335 
6336     if (node.type === "sizing") {
6337       glueOptions = options.havingSize(node.size);
6338     } else if (node.type === "styling") {
6339       glueOptions = options.havingStyle(styleMap$1[node.style]);
6340     }
6341   } // Dummy spans for determining spacings between surrounding atoms.
6342   // If `expression` has no atoms on the left or right, class "leftmost"
6343   // or "rightmost", respectively, is used to indicate it.
6344 
6345 
6346   var dummyPrev = makeSpan$1([surrounding[0] || "leftmost"], [], options);
6347   var dummyNext = makeSpan$1([surrounding[1] || "rightmost"], [], options); // TODO: These code assumes that a node's math class is the first element
6348   // of its `classes` array. A later cleanup should ensure this, for
6349   // instance by changing the signature of `makeSpan`.
6350   // Before determining what spaces to insert, perform bin cancellation.
6351   // Binary operators change to ordinary symbols in some contexts.
6352 
6353   var isRoot = isRealGroup === "root";
6354   traverseNonSpaceNodes(groups, (node, prev) => {
6355     var prevType = prev.classes[0];
6356     var type = node.classes[0];
6357 
6358     if (prevType === "mbin" && utils.contains(binRightCanceller, type)) {
6359       prev.classes[0] = "mord";
6360     } else if (type === "mbin" && utils.contains(binLeftCanceller, prevType)) {
6361       node.classes[0] = "mord";
6362     }
6363   }, {
6364     node: dummyPrev
6365   }, dummyNext, isRoot);
6366   traverseNonSpaceNodes(groups, (node, prev) => {
6367     var prevType = getTypeOfDomTree(prev);
6368     var type = getTypeOfDomTree(node); // 'mtight' indicates that the node is script or scriptscript style.
6369 
6370     var space = prevType && type ? node.hasClass("mtight") ? tightSpacings[prevType][type] : spacings[prevType][type] : null;
6371 
6372     if (space) {
6373       // Insert glue (spacing) after the `prev`.
6374       return buildCommon.makeGlue(space, glueOptions);
6375     }
6376   }, {
6377     node: dummyPrev
6378   }, dummyNext, isRoot);
6379   return groups;
6380 }; // Depth-first traverse non-space `nodes`, calling `callback` with the current and
6381 // previous node as arguments, optionally returning a node to insert after the
6382 // previous node. `prev` is an object with the previous node and `insertAfter`
6383 // function to insert after it. `next` is a node that will be added to the right.
6384 // Used for bin cancellation and inserting spacings.
6385 
6386 var traverseNonSpaceNodes = function traverseNonSpaceNodes(nodes, callback, prev, next, isRoot) {
6387   if (next) {
6388     // temporarily append the right node, if exists
6389     nodes.push(next);
6390   }
6391 
6392   var i = 0;
6393 
6394   for (; i < nodes.length; i++) {
6395     var node = nodes[i];
6396     var partialGroup = checkPartialGroup(node);
6397 
6398     if (partialGroup) {
6399       // Recursive DFS
6400       // $FlowFixMe: make nodes a $ReadOnlyArray by returning a new array
6401       traverseNonSpaceNodes(partialGroup.children, callback, prev, null, isRoot);
6402       continue;
6403     } // Ignore explicit spaces (e.g., \;, \,) when determining what implicit
6404     // spacing should go between atoms of different classes
6405 
6406 
6407     var nonspace = !node.hasClass("mspace");
6408 
6409     if (nonspace) {
6410       var result = callback(node, prev.node);
6411 
6412       if (result) {
6413         if (prev.insertAfter) {
6414           prev.insertAfter(result);
6415         } else {
6416           // insert at front
6417           nodes.unshift(result);
6418           i++;
6419         }
6420       }
6421     }
6422 
6423     if (nonspace) {
6424       prev.node = node;
6425     } else if (isRoot && node.hasClass("newline")) {
6426       prev.node = makeSpan$1(["leftmost"]); // treat like beginning of line
6427     }
6428 
6429     prev.insertAfter = (index => n => {
6430       nodes.splice(index + 1, 0, n);
6431       i++;
6432     })(i);
6433   }
6434 
6435   if (next) {
6436     nodes.pop();
6437   }
6438 }; // Check if given node is a partial group, i.e., does not affect spacing around.
6439 
6440 
6441 var checkPartialGroup = function checkPartialGroup(node) {
6442   if (node instanceof DocumentFragment || node instanceof Anchor || node instanceof Span && node.hasClass("enclosing")) {
6443     return node;
6444   }
6445 
6446   return null;
6447 }; // Return the outermost node of a domTree.
6448 
6449 
6450 var getOutermostNode = function getOutermostNode(node, side) {
6451   var partialGroup = checkPartialGroup(node);
6452 
6453   if (partialGroup) {
6454     var children = partialGroup.children;
6455 
6456     if (children.length) {
6457       if (side === "right") {
6458         return getOutermostNode(children[children.length - 1], "right");
6459       } else if (side === "left") {
6460         return getOutermostNode(children[0], "left");
6461       }
6462     }
6463   }
6464 
6465   return node;
6466 }; // Return math atom class (mclass) of a domTree.
6467 // If `side` is given, it will get the type of the outermost node at given side.
6468 
6469 
6470 var getTypeOfDomTree = function getTypeOfDomTree(node, side) {
6471   if (!node) {
6472     return null;
6473   }
6474 
6475   if (side) {
6476     node = getOutermostNode(node, side);
6477   } // This makes a lot of assumptions as to where the type of atom
6478   // appears.  We should do a better job of enforcing this.
6479 
6480 
6481   return DomEnum[node.classes[0]] || null;
6482 };
6483 var makeNullDelimiter = function makeNullDelimiter(options, classes) {
6484   var moreClasses = ["nulldelimiter"].concat(options.baseSizingClasses());
6485   return makeSpan$1(classes.concat(moreClasses));
6486 };
6487 /**
6488  * buildGroup is the function that takes a group and calls the correct groupType
6489  * function for it. It also handles the interaction of size and style changes
6490  * between parents and children.
6491  */
6492 
6493 var buildGroup$1 = function buildGroup(group, options, baseOptions) {
6494   if (!group) {
6495     return makeSpan$1();
6496   }
6497 
6498   if (_htmlGroupBuilders[group.type]) {
6499     // Call the groupBuilders function
6500     // $FlowFixMe
6501     var groupNode = _htmlGroupBuilders[group.type](group, options); // If the size changed between the parent and the current group, account
6502     // for that size difference.
6503 
6504     if (baseOptions && options.size !== baseOptions.size) {
6505       groupNode = makeSpan$1(options.sizingClasses(baseOptions), [groupNode], options);
6506       var multiplier = options.sizeMultiplier / baseOptions.sizeMultiplier;
6507       groupNode.height *= multiplier;
6508       groupNode.depth *= multiplier;
6509     }
6510 
6511     return groupNode;
6512   } else {
6513     throw new ParseError("Got group of unknown type: '" + group.type + "'");
6514   }
6515 };
6516 /**
6517  * Combine an array of HTML DOM nodes (e.g., the output of `buildExpression`)
6518  * into an unbreakable HTML node of class .base, with proper struts to
6519  * guarantee correct vertical extent.  `buildHTML` calls this repeatedly to
6520  * make up the entire expression as a sequence of unbreakable units.
6521  */
6522 
6523 function buildHTMLUnbreakable(children, options) {
6524   // Compute height and depth of this chunk.
6525   var body = makeSpan$1(["base"], children, options); // Add strut, which ensures that the top of the HTML element falls at
6526   // the height of the expression, and the bottom of the HTML element
6527   // falls at the depth of the expression.
6528 
6529   var strut = makeSpan$1(["strut"]);
6530   strut.style.height = makeEm(body.height + body.depth);
6531 
6532   if (body.depth) {
6533     strut.style.verticalAlign = makeEm(-body.depth);
6534   }
6535 
6536   body.children.unshift(strut);
6537   return body;
6538 }
6539 /**
6540  * Take an entire parse tree, and build it into an appropriate set of HTML
6541  * nodes.
6542  */
6543 
6544 
6545 function buildHTML(tree, options) {
6546   // Strip off outer tag wrapper for processing below.
6547   var tag = null;
6548 
6549   if (tree.length === 1 && tree[0].type === "tag") {
6550     tag = tree[0].tag;
6551     tree = tree[0].body;
6552   } // Build the expression contained in the tree
6553 
6554 
6555   var expression = buildExpression$1(tree, options, "root");
6556   var eqnNum;
6557 
6558   if (expression.length === 2 && expression[1].hasClass("tag")) {
6559     // An environment with automatic equation numbers, e.g. {gather}.
6560     eqnNum = expression.pop();
6561   }
6562 
6563   var children = []; // Create one base node for each chunk between potential line breaks.
6564   // The TeXBook [p.173] says "A formula will be broken only after a
6565   // relation symbol like $=$ or $<$ or $\rightarrow$, or after a binary
6566   // operation symbol like $+$ or $-$ or $\times$, where the relation or
6567   // binary operation is on the ``outer level'' of the formula (i.e., not
6568   // enclosed in {...} and not part of an \over construction)."
6569 
6570   var parts = [];
6571 
6572   for (var i = 0; i < expression.length; i++) {
6573     parts.push(expression[i]);
6574 
6575     if (expression[i].hasClass("mbin") || expression[i].hasClass("mrel") || expression[i].hasClass("allowbreak")) {
6576       // Put any post-operator glue on same line as operator.
6577       // Watch for \nobreak along the way, and stop at \newline.
6578       var nobreak = false;
6579 
6580       while (i < expression.length - 1 && expression[i + 1].hasClass("mspace") && !expression[i + 1].hasClass("newline")) {
6581         i++;
6582         parts.push(expression[i]);
6583 
6584         if (expression[i].hasClass("nobreak")) {
6585           nobreak = true;
6586         }
6587       } // Don't allow break if \nobreak among the post-operator glue.
6588 
6589 
6590       if (!nobreak) {
6591         children.push(buildHTMLUnbreakable(parts, options));
6592         parts = [];
6593       }
6594     } else if (expression[i].hasClass("newline")) {
6595       // Write the line except the newline
6596       parts.pop();
6597 
6598       if (parts.length > 0) {
6599         children.push(buildHTMLUnbreakable(parts, options));
6600         parts = [];
6601       } // Put the newline at the top level
6602 
6603 
6604       children.push(expression[i]);
6605     }
6606   }
6607 
6608   if (parts.length > 0) {
6609     children.push(buildHTMLUnbreakable(parts, options));
6610   } // Now, if there was a tag, build it too and append it as a final child.
6611 
6612 
6613   var tagChild;
6614 
6615   if (tag) {
6616     tagChild = buildHTMLUnbreakable(buildExpression$1(tag, options, true));
6617     tagChild.classes = ["tag"];
6618     children.push(tagChild);
6619   } else if (eqnNum) {
6620     children.push(eqnNum);
6621   }
6622 
6623   var htmlNode = makeSpan$1(["katex-html"], children);
6624   htmlNode.setAttribute("aria-hidden", "true"); // Adjust the strut of the tag to be the maximum height of all children
6625   // (the height of the enclosing htmlNode) for proper vertical alignment.
6626 
6627   if (tagChild) {
6628     var strut = tagChild.children[0];
6629     strut.style.height = makeEm(htmlNode.height + htmlNode.depth);
6630 
6631     if (htmlNode.depth) {
6632       strut.style.verticalAlign = makeEm(-htmlNode.depth);
6633     }
6634   }
6635 
6636   return htmlNode;
6637 }
6638 
6639 /**
6640  * These objects store data about MathML nodes. This is the MathML equivalent
6641  * of the types in domTree.js. Since MathML handles its own rendering, and
6642  * since we're mainly using MathML to improve accessibility, we don't manage
6643  * any of the styling state that the plain DOM nodes do.
6644  *
6645  * The `toNode` and `toMarkup` functions work similarly to how they do in
6646  * domTree.js, creating namespaced DOM nodes and HTML text markup respectively.
6647  */
6648 function newDocumentFragment(children) {
6649   return new DocumentFragment(children);
6650 }
6651 /**
6652  * This node represents a general purpose MathML node of any type. The
6653  * constructor requires the type of node to create (for example, `"mo"` or
6654  * `"mspace"`, corresponding to `<mo>` and `<mspace>` tags).
6655  */
6656 
6657 class MathNode {
6658   constructor(type, children, classes) {
6659     this.type = void 0;
6660     this.attributes = void 0;
6661     this.children = void 0;
6662     this.classes = void 0;
6663     this.type = type;
6664     this.attributes = {};
6665     this.children = children || [];
6666     this.classes = classes || [];
6667   }
6668   /**
6669    * Sets an attribute on a MathML node. MathML depends on attributes to convey a
6670    * semantic content, so this is used heavily.
6671    */
6672 
6673 
6674   setAttribute(name, value) {
6675     this.attributes[name] = value;
6676   }
6677   /**
6678    * Gets an attribute on a MathML node.
6679    */
6680 
6681 
6682   getAttribute(name) {
6683     return this.attributes[name];
6684   }
6685   /**
6686    * Converts the math node into a MathML-namespaced DOM element.
6687    */
6688 
6689 
6690   toNode() {
6691     var node = document.createElementNS("http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML", this.type);
6692 
6693     for (var attr in this.attributes) {
6694       if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(this.attributes, attr)) {
6695         node.setAttribute(attr, this.attributes[attr]);
6696       }
6697     }
6698 
6699     if (this.classes.length > 0) {
6700       node.className = createClass(this.classes);
6701     }
6702 
6703     for (var i = 0; i < this.children.length; i++) {
6704       // Combine multiple TextNodes into one TextNode, to prevent
6705       // screen readers from reading each as a separate word [#3995]
6706       if (this.children[i] instanceof TextNode && this.children[i + 1] instanceof TextNode) {
6707         var text = this.children[i].toText() + this.children[++i].toText();
6708 
6709         while (this.children[i + 1] instanceof TextNode) {
6710           text += this.children[++i].toText();
6711         }
6712 
6713         node.appendChild(new TextNode(text).toNode());
6714       } else {
6715         node.appendChild(this.children[i].toNode());
6716       }
6717     }
6718 
6719     return node;
6720   }
6721   /**
6722    * Converts the math node into an HTML markup string.
6723    */
6724 
6725 
6726   toMarkup() {
6727     var markup = "<" + this.type; // Add the attributes
6728 
6729     for (var attr in this.attributes) {
6730       if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(this.attributes, attr)) {
6731         markup += " " + attr + "=\"";
6732         markup += utils.escape(this.attributes[attr]);
6733         markup += "\"";
6734       }
6735     }
6736 
6737     if (this.classes.length > 0) {
6738       markup += " class =\"" + utils.escape(createClass(this.classes)) + "\"";
6739     }
6740 
6741     markup += ">";
6742 
6743     for (var i = 0; i < this.children.length; i++) {
6744       markup += this.children[i].toMarkup();
6745     }
6746 
6747     markup += "</" + this.type + ">";
6748     return markup;
6749   }
6750   /**
6751    * Converts the math node into a string, similar to innerText, but escaped.
6752    */
6753 
6754 
6755   toText() {
6756     return this.children.map(child => child.toText()).join("");
6757   }
6758 
6759 }
6760 /**
6761  * This node represents a piece of text.
6762  */
6763 
6764 class TextNode {
6765   constructor(text) {
6766     this.text = void 0;
6767     this.text = text;
6768   }
6769   /**
6770    * Converts the text node into a DOM text node.
6771    */
6772 
6773 
6774   toNode() {
6775     return document.createTextNode(this.text);
6776   }
6777   /**
6778    * Converts the text node into escaped HTML markup
6779    * (representing the text itself).
6780    */
6781 
6782 
6783   toMarkup() {
6784     return utils.escape(this.toText());
6785   }
6786   /**
6787    * Converts the text node into a string
6788    * (representing the text itself).
6789    */
6790 
6791 
6792   toText() {
6793     return this.text;
6794   }
6795 
6796 }
6797 /**
6798  * This node represents a space, but may render as <mspace.../> or as text,
6799  * depending on the width.
6800  */
6801 
6802 class SpaceNode {
6803   /**
6804    * Create a Space node with width given in CSS ems.
6805    */
6806   constructor(width) {
6807     this.width = void 0;
6808     this.character = void 0;
6809     this.width = width; // See https://www.w3.org/TR/2000/WD-MathML2-20000328/chapter6.html
6810     // for a table of space-like characters.  We use Unicode
6811     // representations instead of &LongNames; as it's not clear how to
6812     // make the latter via document.createTextNode.
6813 
6814     if (width >= 0.05555 && width <= 0.05556) {
6815       this.character = "\u200a"; // &VeryThinSpace;
6816     } else if (width >= 0.1666 && width <= 0.1667) {
6817       this.character = "\u2009"; // &ThinSpace;
6818     } else if (width >= 0.2222 && width <= 0.2223) {
6819       this.character = "\u2005"; // &MediumSpace;
6820     } else if (width >= 0.2777 && width <= 0.2778) {
6821       this.character = "\u2005\u200a"; // &ThickSpace;
6822     } else if (width >= -0.05556 && width <= -0.05555) {
6823       this.character = "\u200a\u2063"; // &NegativeVeryThinSpace;
6824     } else if (width >= -0.1667 && width <= -0.1666) {
6825       this.character = "\u2009\u2063"; // &NegativeThinSpace;
6826     } else if (width >= -0.2223 && width <= -0.2222) {
6827       this.character = "\u205f\u2063"; // &NegativeMediumSpace;
6828     } else if (width >= -0.2778 && width <= -0.2777) {
6829       this.character = "\u2005\u2063"; // &NegativeThickSpace;
6830     } else {
6831       this.character = null;
6832     }
6833   }
6834   /**
6835    * Converts the math node into a MathML-namespaced DOM element.
6836    */
6837 
6838 
6839   toNode() {
6840     if (this.character) {
6841       return document.createTextNode(this.character);
6842     } else {
6843       var node = document.createElementNS("http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML", "mspace");
6844       node.setAttribute("width", makeEm(this.width));
6845       return node;
6846     }
6847   }
6848   /**
6849    * Converts the math node into an HTML markup string.
6850    */
6851 
6852 
6853   toMarkup() {
6854     if (this.character) {
6855       return "<mtext>" + this.character + "</mtext>";
6856     } else {
6857       return "<mspace width=\"" + makeEm(this.width) + "\"/>";
6858     }
6859   }
6860   /**
6861    * Converts the math node into a string, similar to innerText.
6862    */
6863 
6864 
6865   toText() {
6866     if (this.character) {
6867       return this.character;
6868     } else {
6869       return " ";
6870     }
6871   }
6872 
6873 }
6874 
6875 var mathMLTree = {
6876   MathNode,
6877   TextNode,
6878   SpaceNode,
6879   newDocumentFragment
6880 };
6881 
6882 /**
6883  * This file converts a parse tree into a corresponding MathML tree. The main
6884  * entry point is the `buildMathML` function, which takes a parse tree from the
6885  * parser.
6886  */
6887 
6888 /**
6889  * Takes a symbol and converts it into a MathML text node after performing
6890  * optional replacement from symbols.js.
6891  */
6892 var makeText = function makeText(text, mode, options) {
6893   if (symbols[mode][text] && symbols[mode][text].replace && text.charCodeAt(0) !== 0xD835 && !(ligatures.hasOwnProperty(text) && options && (options.fontFamily && options.fontFamily.slice(4, 6) === "tt" || options.font && options.font.slice(4, 6) === "tt"))) {
6894     text = symbols[mode][text].replace;
6895   }
6896 
6897   return new mathMLTree.TextNode(text);
6898 };
6899 /**
6900  * Wrap the given array of nodes in an <mrow> node if needed, i.e.,
6901  * unless the array has length 1.  Always returns a single node.
6902  */
6903 
6904 var makeRow = function makeRow(body) {
6905   if (body.length === 1) {
6906     return body[0];
6907   } else {
6908     return new mathMLTree.MathNode("mrow", body);
6909   }
6910 };
6911 /**
6912  * Returns the math variant as a string or null if none is required.
6913  */
6914 
6915 var getVariant = function getVariant(group, options) {
6916   // Handle \text... font specifiers as best we can.
6917   // MathML has a limited list of allowable mathvariant specifiers; see
6918   // https://www.w3.org/TR/MathML3/chapter3.html#presm.commatt
6919   if (options.fontFamily === "texttt") {
6920     return "monospace";
6921   } else if (options.fontFamily === "textsf") {
6922     if (options.fontShape === "textit" && options.fontWeight === "textbf") {
6923       return "sans-serif-bold-italic";
6924     } else if (options.fontShape === "textit") {
6925       return "sans-serif-italic";
6926     } else if (options.fontWeight === "textbf") {
6927       return "bold-sans-serif";
6928     } else {
6929       return "sans-serif";
6930     }
6931   } else if (options.fontShape === "textit" && options.fontWeight === "textbf") {
6932     return "bold-italic";
6933   } else if (options.fontShape === "textit") {
6934     return "italic";
6935   } else if (options.fontWeight === "textbf") {
6936     return "bold";
6937   }
6938 
6939   var font = options.font;
6940 
6941   if (!font || font === "mathnormal") {
6942     return null;
6943   }
6944 
6945   var mode = group.mode;
6946 
6947   if (font === "mathit") {
6948     return "italic";
6949   } else if (font === "boldsymbol") {
6950     return group.type === "textord" ? "bold" : "bold-italic";
6951   } else if (font === "mathbf") {
6952     return "bold";
6953   } else if (font === "mathbb") {
6954     return "double-struck";
6955   } else if (font === "mathsfit") {
6956     return "sans-serif-italic";
6957   } else if (font === "mathfrak") {
6958     return "fraktur";
6959   } else if (font === "mathscr" || font === "mathcal") {
6960     // MathML makes no distinction between script and calligraphic
6961     return "script";
6962   } else if (font === "mathsf") {
6963     return "sans-serif";
6964   } else if (font === "mathtt") {
6965     return "monospace";
6966   }
6967 
6968   var text = group.text;
6969 
6970   if (utils.contains(["\\imath", "\\jmath"], text)) {
6971     return null;
6972   }
6973 
6974   if (symbols[mode][text] && symbols[mode][text].replace) {
6975     text = symbols[mode][text].replace;
6976   }
6977 
6978   var fontName = buildCommon.fontMap[font].fontName;
6979 
6980   if (getCharacterMetrics(text, fontName, mode)) {
6981     return buildCommon.fontMap[font].variant;
6982   }
6983 
6984   return null;
6985 };
6986 /**
6987  * Check for <mi>.</mi> which is how a dot renders in MathML,
6988  * or <mo separator="true" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">,</mo>
6989  * which is how a braced comma {,} renders in MathML
6990  */
6991 
6992 function isNumberPunctuation(group) {
6993   if (!group) {
6994     return false;
6995   }
6996 
6997   if (group.type === 'mi' && group.children.length === 1) {
6998     var child = group.children[0];
6999     return child instanceof TextNode && child.text === '.';
7000   } else if (group.type === 'mo' && group.children.length === 1 && group.getAttribute('separator') === 'true' && group.getAttribute('lspace') === '0em' && group.getAttribute('rspace') === '0em') {
7001     var _child = group.children[0];
7002     return _child instanceof TextNode && _child.text === ',';
7003   } else {
7004     return false;
7005   }
7006 }
7007 /**
7008  * Takes a list of nodes, builds them, and returns a list of the generated
7009  * MathML nodes.  Also combine consecutive <mtext> outputs into a single
7010  * <mtext> tag.
7011  */
7012 
7013 
7014 var buildExpression = function buildExpression(expression, options, isOrdgroup) {
7015   if (expression.length === 1) {
7016     var group = buildGroup(expression[0], options);
7017 
7018     if (isOrdgroup && group instanceof MathNode && group.type === "mo") {
7019       // When TeX writers want to suppress spacing on an operator,
7020       // they often put the operator by itself inside braces.
7021       group.setAttribute("lspace", "0em");
7022       group.setAttribute("rspace", "0em");
7023     }
7024 
7025     return [group];
7026   }
7027 
7028   var groups = [];
7029   var lastGroup;
7030 
7031   for (var i = 0; i < expression.length; i++) {
7032     var _group = buildGroup(expression[i], options);
7033 
7034     if (_group instanceof MathNode && lastGroup instanceof MathNode) {
7035       // Concatenate adjacent <mtext>s
7036       if (_group.type === 'mtext' && lastGroup.type === 'mtext' && _group.getAttribute('mathvariant') === lastGroup.getAttribute('mathvariant')) {
7037         lastGroup.children.push(..._group.children);
7038         continue; // Concatenate adjacent <mn>s
7039       } else if (_group.type === 'mn' && lastGroup.type === 'mn') {
7040         lastGroup.children.push(..._group.children);
7041         continue; // Concatenate <mn>...</mn> followed by <mi>.</mi>
7042       } else if (isNumberPunctuation(_group) && lastGroup.type === 'mn') {
7043         lastGroup.children.push(..._group.children);
7044         continue; // Concatenate <mi>.</mi> followed by <mn>...</mn>
7045       } else if (_group.type === 'mn' && isNumberPunctuation(lastGroup)) {
7046         _group.children = [...lastGroup.children, ..._group.children];
7047         groups.pop(); // Put preceding <mn>...</mn> or <mi>.</mi> inside base of
7048         // <msup><mn>...base...</mn>...exponent...</msup> (or <msub>)
7049       } else if ((_group.type === 'msup' || _group.type === 'msub') && _group.children.length >= 1 && (lastGroup.type === 'mn' || isNumberPunctuation(lastGroup))) {
7050         var base = _group.children[0];
7051 
7052         if (base instanceof MathNode && base.type === 'mn') {
7053           base.children = [...lastGroup.children, ...base.children];
7054           groups.pop();
7055         } // \not
7056 
7057       } else if (lastGroup.type === 'mi' && lastGroup.children.length === 1) {
7058         var lastChild = lastGroup.children[0];
7059 
7060         if (lastChild instanceof TextNode && lastChild.text === '\u0338' && (_group.type === 'mo' || _group.type === 'mi' || _group.type === 'mn')) {
7061           var child = _group.children[0];
7062 
7063           if (child instanceof TextNode && child.text.length > 0) {
7064             // Overlay with combining character long solidus
7065             child.text = child.text.slice(0, 1) + "\u0338" + child.text.slice(1);
7066             groups.pop();
7067           }
7068         }
7069       }
7070     }
7071 
7072     groups.push(_group);
7073     lastGroup = _group;
7074   }
7075 
7076   return groups;
7077 };
7078 /**
7079  * Equivalent to buildExpression, but wraps the elements in an <mrow>
7080  * if there's more than one.  Returns a single node instead of an array.
7081  */
7082 
7083 var buildExpressionRow = function buildExpressionRow(expression, options, isOrdgroup) {
7084   return makeRow(buildExpression(expression, options, isOrdgroup));
7085 };
7086 /**
7087  * Takes a group from the parser and calls the appropriate groupBuilders function
7088  * on it to produce a MathML node.
7089  */
7090 
7091 var buildGroup = function buildGroup(group, options) {
7092   if (!group) {
7093     return new mathMLTree.MathNode("mrow");
7094   }
7095 
7096   if (_mathmlGroupBuilders[group.type]) {
7097     // Call the groupBuilders function
7098     // $FlowFixMe
7099     var result = _mathmlGroupBuilders[group.type](group, options); // $FlowFixMe
7100 
7101     return result;
7102   } else {
7103     throw new ParseError("Got group of unknown type: '" + group.type + "'");
7104   }
7105 };
7106 /**
7107  * Takes a full parse tree and settings and builds a MathML representation of
7108  * it. In particular, we put the elements from building the parse tree into a
7109  * <semantics> tag so we can also include that TeX source as an annotation.
7110  *
7111  * Note that we actually return a domTree element with a `<math>` inside it so
7112  * we can do appropriate styling.
7113  */
7114 
7115 function buildMathML(tree, texExpression, options, isDisplayMode, forMathmlOnly) {
7116   var expression = buildExpression(tree, options); // TODO: Make a pass thru the MathML similar to buildHTML.traverseNonSpaceNodes
7117   // and add spacing nodes. This is necessary only adjacent to math operators
7118   // like \sin or \lim or to subsup elements that contain math operators.
7119   // MathML takes care of the other spacing issues.
7120   // Wrap up the expression in an mrow so it is presented in the semantics
7121   // tag correctly, unless it's a single <mrow> or <mtable>.
7122 
7123   var wrapper;
7124 
7125   if (expression.length === 1 && expression[0] instanceof MathNode && utils.contains(["mrow", "mtable"], expression[0].type)) {
7126     wrapper = expression[0];
7127   } else {
7128     wrapper = new mathMLTree.MathNode("mrow", expression);
7129   } // Build a TeX annotation of the source
7130 
7131 
7132   var annotation = new mathMLTree.MathNode("annotation", [new mathMLTree.TextNode(texExpression)]);
7133   annotation.setAttribute("encoding", "application/x-tex");
7134   var semantics = new mathMLTree.MathNode("semantics", [wrapper, annotation]);
7135   var math = new mathMLTree.MathNode("math", [semantics]);
7136   math.setAttribute("xmlns", "http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML");
7137 
7138   if (isDisplayMode) {
7139     math.setAttribute("display", "block");
7140   } // You can't style <math> nodes, so we wrap the node in a span.
7141   // NOTE: The span class is not typed to have <math> nodes as children, and
7142   // we don't want to make the children type more generic since the children
7143   // of span are expected to have more fields in `buildHtml` contexts.
7144 
7145 
7146   var wrapperClass = forMathmlOnly ? "katex" : "katex-mathml"; // $FlowFixMe
7147 
7148   return buildCommon.makeSpan([wrapperClass], [math]);
7149 }
7150 
7151 var optionsFromSettings = function optionsFromSettings(settings) {
7152   return new Options({
7153     style: settings.displayMode ? Style$1.DISPLAY : Style$1.TEXT,
7154     maxSize: settings.maxSize,
7155     minRuleThickness: settings.minRuleThickness
7156   });
7157 };
7158 
7159 var displayWrap = function displayWrap(node, settings) {
7160   if (settings.displayMode) {
7161     var classes = ["katex-display"];
7162 
7163     if (settings.leqno) {
7164       classes.push("leqno");
7165     }
7166 
7167     if (settings.fleqn) {
7168       classes.push("fleqn");
7169     }
7170 
7171     node = buildCommon.makeSpan(classes, [node]);
7172   }
7173 
7174   return node;
7175 };
7176 
7177 var buildTree = function buildTree(tree, expression, settings) {
7178   var options = optionsFromSettings(settings);
7179   var katexNode;
7180 
7181   if (settings.output === "mathml") {
7182     return buildMathML(tree, expression, options, settings.displayMode, true);
7183   } else if (settings.output === "html") {
7184     var htmlNode = buildHTML(tree, options);
7185     katexNode = buildCommon.makeSpan(["katex"], [htmlNode]);
7186   } else {
7187     var mathMLNode = buildMathML(tree, expression, options, settings.displayMode, false);
7188 
7189     var _htmlNode = buildHTML(tree, options);
7190 
7191     katexNode = buildCommon.makeSpan(["katex"], [mathMLNode, _htmlNode]);
7192   }
7193 
7194   return displayWrap(katexNode, settings);
7195 };
7196 var buildHTMLTree = function buildHTMLTree(tree, expression, settings) {
7197   var options = optionsFromSettings(settings);
7198   var htmlNode = buildHTML(tree, options);
7199   var katexNode = buildCommon.makeSpan(["katex"], [htmlNode]);
7200   return displayWrap(katexNode, settings);
7201 };

7255 var mathMLnode = function mathMLnode(label) {

7259 }; // Many of the KaTeX SVG images have been adapted from glyphs in KaTeX fonts.
7260 // Copyright (c) 2009-2010, Design Science, Inc. (<www.mathjax.org>)
7261 // Copyright (c) 2014-2017 Khan Academy (<www.khanacademy.org>)
7262 // Licensed under the SIL Open Font License, Version 1.1.
7263 // See \nhttp://scripts.sil.org/OFL
7264 // Very Long SVGs
7265 //    Many of the KaTeX stretchy wide elements use a long SVG image and an
7266 //    overflow: hidden tactic to achieve a stretchy image while avoiding
7267 //    distortion of arrowheads or brace corners.
7268 //    The SVG typically contains a very long (400 em) arrow.
7269 //    The SVG is in a container span that has overflow: hidden, so the span
7270 //    acts like a window that exposes only part of the  SVG.
7271 //    The SVG always has a longer, thinner aspect ratio than the container span.
7272 //    After the SVG fills 100% of the height of the container span,
7273 //    there is a long arrow shaft left over. That left-over shaft is not shown.
7274 //    Instead, it is sliced off because the span's CSS has overflow: hidden.
7275 //    Thus, the reader sees an arrow that matches the subject matter width
7276 //    without distortion.
7277 //    Some functions, such as \cancel, need to vary their aspect ratio. These
7278 //    functions do not get the overflow SVG treatment.
7279 // Second Brush Stroke
7280 //    Low resolution monitors struggle to display images in fine detail.
7281 //    So browsers apply anti-aliasing. A long straight arrow shaft therefore
7282 //    will sometimes appear as if it has a blurred edge.
7283 //    To mitigate this, these SVG files contain a second "brush-stroke" on the
7284 //    arrow shafts. That is, a second long thin rectangular SVG path has been
7285 //    written directly on top of each arrow shaft. This reinforcement causes
7286 //    some of the screen pixels to display as black instead of the anti-aliased
7287 //    gray pixel that a  single path would generate. So we get arrow shafts
7288 //    whose edges appear to be sharper.
7289 // In the katexImagesData object just below, the dimensions all
7290 // correspond to path geometry inside the relevant SVG.
7291 // For example, \overrightarrow uses the same arrowhead as glyph U+2192
7292 // from the KaTeX Main font. The scaling factor is 1000.
7293 // That is, inside the font, that arrowhead is 522 units tall, which
7294 // corresponds to 0.522 em inside the document.
7295 
7296

7346 var groupLength = function groupLength(arg) {
7347   if (arg.type === "ordgroup") {
7348     return arg.body.length;
7349   } else {
7350     return 1;

7354 var svgSpan = function svgSpan(group, options) {
7355   // Create a span with inline SVG for the element.
7356   function buildSvgSpan_() {
7357     var viewBoxWidth = 400000; // default
7358 
7359     var label = group.label.slice(1);
7360 
7361     if (utils.contains(["widehat", "widecheck", "widetilde", "utilde"], label)) {
7362       // Each type in the `if` statement corresponds to one of the ParseNode
7363       // types below. This narrowing is required to access `grp.base`.
7364       // $FlowFixMe
7365       var grp = group; // There are four SVG images available for each function.
7366       // Choose a taller image when there are more characters.
7367 
7368       var numChars = groupLength(grp.base);
7369       var viewBoxHeight;
7370       var pathName;
7371 
7372       var _height;
7373 
7374       if (numChars > 5) {
7375         if (label === "widehat" || label === "widecheck") {
7376           viewBoxHeight = 420;
7377           viewBoxWidth = 2364;
7378           _height = 0.42;
7379           pathName = label + "4";
7380         } else {
7381           viewBoxHeight = 312;
7382           viewBoxWidth = 2340;
7383           _height = 0.34;
7384           pathName = "tilde4";
7385         }
7386       } else {
7387         var imgIndex = [1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3][numChars];
7388 
7389         if (label === "widehat" || label === "widecheck") {
7390           viewBoxWidth = [0, 1062, 2364, 2364, 2364][imgIndex];
7391           viewBoxHeight = [0, 239, 300, 360, 420][imgIndex];
7392           _height = [0, 0.24, 0.3, 0.3, 0.36, 0.42][imgIndex];
7393           pathName = label + imgIndex;
7394         } else {
7395           viewBoxWidth = [0, 600, 1033, 2339, 2340][imgIndex];
7396           viewBoxHeight = [0, 260, 286, 306, 312][imgIndex];
7397           _height = [0, 0.26, 0.286, 0.3, 0.306, 0.34][imgIndex];
7398           pathName = "tilde" + imgIndex;
7399         }
7400       }
7401 
7402       var path = new PathNode(pathName);
7403       var svgNode = new SvgNode([path], {
7404         "width": "100%",
7405         "height": makeEm(_height),
7406         "viewBox": "0 0 " + viewBoxWidth + " " + viewBoxHeight,
7407         "preserveAspectRatio": "none"
7408       });
7409       return {
7410         span: buildCommon.makeSvgSpan([], [svgNode], options),
7411         minWidth: 0,
7412         height: _height
7413       };
7414     } else {
7415       var spans = [];
7416       var data = katexImagesData[label];
7417       var [paths, _minWidth, _viewBoxHeight] = data;
7418 
7419       var _height2 = _viewBoxHeight / 1000;
7420 
7421       var numSvgChildren = paths.length;
7422       var widthClasses;
7423       var aligns;
7424 
7425       if (numSvgChildren === 1) {
7426         // $FlowFixMe: All these cases must be of the 4-tuple type.
7427         var align1 = data[3];
7428         widthClasses = ["hide-tail"];
7429         aligns = [align1];
7430       } else if (numSvgChildren === 2) {
7431         widthClasses = ["halfarrow-left", "halfarrow-right"];
7432         aligns = ["xMinYMin", "xMaxYMin"];
7433       } else if (numSvgChildren === 3) {
7434         widthClasses = ["brace-left", "brace-center", "brace-right"];
7435         aligns = ["xMinYMin", "xMidYMin", "xMaxYMin"];
7436       } else {
7437         throw new Error("Correct katexImagesData or update code here to support\n                    " + numSvgChildren + " children.");
7438       }
7439 
7440       for (var i = 0; i < numSvgChildren; i++) {
7441         var _path = new PathNode(paths[i]);
7442 
7443         var _svgNode = new SvgNode([_path], {
7444           "width": "400em",
7445           "height": makeEm(_height2),
7446           "viewBox": "0 0 " + viewBoxWidth + " " + _viewBoxHeight,
7447           "preserveAspectRatio": aligns[i] + " slice"
7448         });
7449 
7450         var _span = buildCommon.makeSvgSpan([widthClasses[i]], [_svgNode], options);
7451 
7452         if (numSvgChildren === 1) {
7453           return {
7454             span: _span,
7455             minWidth: _minWidth,
7456             height: _height2
7457           };
7458         } else {
7459           _span.style.height = makeEm(_height2);
7460           spans.push(_span);
7461         }
7462       }
7463 
7464       return {
7465         span: buildCommon.makeSpan(["stretchy"], spans, options),
7466         minWidth: _minWidth,
7467         height: _height2
7468       };
7469     }
7470   } // buildSvgSpan_()
7471 
7472 
7473   var {
7474     span,
7475     minWidth,
7476     height
7477   } = buildSvgSpan_(); // Note that we are returning span.depth = 0.
7478   // Any adjustments relative to the baseline must be done in buildHTML.
7479 
7480   span.height = height;
7481   span.style.height = makeEm(height);
7482 
7483   if (minWidth > 0) {
7484     span.style.minWidth = makeEm(minWidth);
7485   }
7486 
7487   return span;
7488 };

7490 var encloseSpan = function encloseSpan(inner, label, topPad, bottomPad, options) {
7491   // Return an image span for \cancel, \bcancel, \xcancel, \fbox, or \angl
7492   var img;
7493   var totalHeight = inner.height + inner.depth + topPad + bottomPad;
7494 
7495   if (/fbox|color|angl/.test(label)) {
7496     img = buildCommon.makeSpan(["stretchy", label], [], options);
7497 
7498     if (label === "fbox") {
7499       var color = options.color && options.getColor();
7500 
7501       if (color) {
7502         img.style.borderColor = color;
7503       }
7504     }
7505   } else {
7506     // \cancel, \bcancel, or \xcancel
7507     // Since \cancel's SVG is inline and it omits the viewBox attribute,
7508     // its stroke-width will not vary with span area.
7509     var lines = [];
7510 
7511     if (/^[bx]cancel$/.test(label)) {
7512       lines.push(new LineNode({
7513         "x1": "0",
7514         "y1": "0",
7515         "x2": "100%",
7516         "y2": "100%",
7517         "stroke-width": "0.046em"
7518       }));
7519     }
7520 
7521     if (/^x?cancel$/.test(label)) {
7522       lines.push(new LineNode({
7523         "x1": "0",
7524         "y1": "100%",
7525         "x2": "100%",
7526         "y2": "0",
7527         "stroke-width": "0.046em"
7528       }));
7529     }
7530 
7531     var svgNode = new SvgNode(lines, {
7532       "width": "100%",
7533       "height": makeEm(totalHeight)
7534     });
7535     img = buildCommon.makeSvgSpan([], [svgNode], options);
7536   }
7537 
7538   img.height = totalHeight;
7539   img.style.height = makeEm(totalHeight);
7540   return img;
7541 };

7549 /**
7550  * Asserts that the node is of the given type and returns it with stricter
7551  * typing. Throws if the node's type does not match.
7552  */
7553 function assertNodeType(node, type) {
7554   if (!node || node.type !== type) {
7555     throw new Error("Expected node of type " + type + ", but got " + (node ? "node of type " + node.type : String(node)));
7556   } // $FlowFixMe, >=0.125
7557 
7558 
7559   return node;
7560 }
7561 /**
7562  * Returns the node more strictly typed iff it is of the given type. Otherwise,
7563  * returns null.
7564  */
7565 
7566 function assertSymbolNodeType(node) {
7567   var typedNode = checkSymbolNodeType(node);
7568 
7569   if (!typedNode) {
7570     throw new Error("Expected node of symbol group type, but got " + (node ? "node of type " + node.type : String(node)));
7571   }
7572 
7573   return typedNode;
7574 }
7575 /**
7576  * Returns the node more strictly typed iff it is of the given type. Otherwise,
7577  * returns null.
7578  */
7579 
7580 function checkSymbolNodeType(node) {
7581   if (node && (node.type === "atom" || NON_ATOMS.hasOwnProperty(node.type))) {
7582     // $FlowFixMe
7583     return node;
7584   }
7585 
7586   return null;
7587 }
7588 
7589 // NOTE: Unlike most `htmlBuilder`s, this one handles not only "accent", but
7590 // also "supsub" since an accent can affect super/subscripting.
7591 var htmlBuilder$a = (grp, options) => {
7592   // Accents are handled in the TeXbook pg. 443, rule 12.
7593   var base;
7594   var group;
7595   var supSubGroup;
7596 
7597   if (grp && grp.type === "supsub") {
7598     // If our base is a character box, and we have superscripts and
7599     // subscripts, the supsub will defer to us. In particular, we want
7600     // to attach the superscripts and subscripts to the inner body (so
7601     // that the position of the superscripts and subscripts won't be
7602     // affected by the height of the accent). We accomplish this by
7603     // sticking the base of the accent into the base of the supsub, and
7604     // rendering that, while keeping track of where the accent is.
7605     // The real accent group is the base of the supsub group
7606     group = assertNodeType(grp.base, "accent"); // The character box is the base of the accent group
7607 
7608     base = group.base; // Stick the character box into the base of the supsub group
7609 
7610     grp.base = base; // Rerender the supsub group with its new base, and store that
7611     // result.
7612 
7613     supSubGroup = assertSpan(buildGroup$1(grp, options)); // reset original base
7614 
7615     grp.base = group;
7616   } else {
7617     group = assertNodeType(grp, "accent");
7618     base = group.base;
7619   } // Build the base group
7620 
7621 
7622   var body = buildGroup$1(base, options.havingCrampedStyle()); // Does the accent need to shift for the skew of a character?
7623 
7624   var mustShift = group.isShifty && utils.isCharacterBox(base); // Calculate the skew of the accent. This is based on the line "If the
7625   // nucleus is not a single character, let s = 0; otherwise set s to the
7626   // kern amount for the nucleus followed by the \skewchar of its font."
7627   // Note that our skew metrics are just the kern between each character
7628   // and the skewchar.
7629 
7630   var skew = 0;
7631 
7632   if (mustShift) {
7633     // If the base is a character box, then we want the skew of the
7634     // innermost character. To do that, we find the innermost character:
7635     var baseChar = utils.getBaseElem(base); // Then, we render its group to get the symbol inside it
7636 
7637     var baseGroup = buildGroup$1(baseChar, options.havingCrampedStyle()); // Finally, we pull the skew off of the symbol.
7638 
7639     skew = assertSymbolDomNode(baseGroup).skew; // Note that we now throw away baseGroup, because the layers we
7640     // removed with getBaseElem might contain things like \color which
7641     // we can't get rid of.
7642     // TODO(emily): Find a better way to get the skew
7643   }
7644 
7645   var accentBelow = group.label === "\\c"; // calculate the amount of space between the body and the accent
7646 
7647   var clearance = accentBelow ? body.height + body.depth : Math.min(body.height, options.fontMetrics().xHeight); // Build the accent
7648 
7649   var accentBody;
7650 
7651   if (!group.isStretchy) {
7652     var accent;
7653     var width;
7654 
7655     if (group.label === "\\vec") {
7656       // Before version 0.9, \vec used the combining font glyph U+20D7.
7657       // But browsers, especially Safari, are not consistent in how they
7658       // render combining characters when not preceded by a character.
7659       // So now we use an SVG.
7660       // If Safari reforms, we should consider reverting to the glyph.
7661       accent = buildCommon.staticSvg("vec", options);
7662       width = buildCommon.svgData.vec[1];
7663     } else {
7664       accent = buildCommon.makeOrd({
7665         mode: group.mode,
7666         text: group.label
7667       }, options, "textord");
7668       accent = assertSymbolDomNode(accent); // Remove the italic correction of the accent, because it only serves to
7669       // shift the accent over to a place we don't want.
7670 
7671       accent.italic = 0;
7672       width = accent.width;
7673 
7674       if (accentBelow) {
7675         clearance += accent.depth;
7676       }
7677     }
7678 
7679     accentBody = buildCommon.makeSpan(["accent-body"], [accent]); // "Full" accents expand the width of the resulting symbol to be
7680     // at least the width of the accent, and overlap directly onto the
7681     // character without any vertical offset.
7682 
7683     var accentFull = group.label === "\\textcircled";
7684 
7685     if (accentFull) {
7686       accentBody.classes.push('accent-full');
7687       clearance = body.height;
7688     } // Shift the accent over by the skew.
7689 
7690 
7691     var left = skew; // CSS defines `.katex .accent .accent-body:not(.accent-full) { width: 0 }`
7692     // so that the accent doesn't contribute to the bounding box.
7693     // We need to shift the character by its width (effectively half
7694     // its width) to compensate.
7695 
7696     if (!accentFull) {
7697       left -= width / 2;
7698     }
7699 
7700     accentBody.style.left = makeEm(left); // \textcircled uses the \bigcirc glyph, so it needs some
7701     // vertical adjustment to match LaTeX.
7702 
7703     if (group.label === "\\textcircled") {
7704       accentBody.style.top = ".2em";
7705     }
7706 
7707     accentBody = buildCommon.makeVList({
7708       positionType: "firstBaseline",
7709       children: [{
7710         type: "elem",
7711         elem: body
7712       }, {
7713         type: "kern",
7714         size: -clearance
7715       }, {
7716         type: "elem",
7717         elem: accentBody
7718       }]
7719     }, options);
7720   } else {
7721     accentBody = stretchy.svgSpan(group, options);
7722     accentBody = buildCommon.makeVList({
7723       positionType: "firstBaseline",
7724       children: [{
7725         type: "elem",
7726         elem: body
7727       }, {
7728         type: "elem",
7729         elem: accentBody,
7730         wrapperClasses: ["svg-align"],
7731         wrapperStyle: skew > 0 ? {
7732           width: "calc(100% - " + makeEm(2 * skew) + ")",
7733           marginLeft: makeEm(2 * skew)
7734         } : undefined
7735       }]
7736     }, options);
7737   }
7738 
7739   var accentWrap = buildCommon.makeSpan(["mord", "accent"], [accentBody], options);
7740 
7741   if (supSubGroup) {
7742     // Here, we replace the "base" child of the supsub with our newly
7743     // generated accent.
7744     supSubGroup.children[0] = accentWrap; // Since we don't rerun the height calculation after replacing the
7745     // accent, we manually recalculate height.
7746 
7747     supSubGroup.height = Math.max(accentWrap.height, supSubGroup.height); // Accents should always be ords, even when their innards are not.
7748 
7749     supSubGroup.classes[0] = "mord";
7750     return supSubGroup;
7751   } else {
7752     return accentWrap;
7753   }
7754 };

8015 function mathmlBuilder$8(group, options) {

8020     node = new mathMLTree.MathNode("mpadded", inner);
8021   } else if (group.mclass === "mord") {
8022     if (group.isCharacterBox) {
8023       node = inner[0];

8025     } else {

8027     }

8030       node = inner[0];
8031       node.type = "mo";

8033       node = new mathMLTree.MathNode("mo", inner);
8034     } // Set spacing based on what is the most likely adjacent atom type.
8035     // See TeXbook p170.
8036 
8037 
8038     if (group.mclass === "mbin") {
8039       node.attributes.lspace = "0.22em"; // medium space
8040 
8041       node.attributes.rspace = "0.22em";
8042     } else if (group.mclass === "mpunct") {
8043       node.attributes.lspace = "0em";
8044       node.attributes.rspace = "0.17em"; // thinspace
8045     } else if (group.mclass === "mopen" || group.mclass === "mclose") {
8046       node.attributes.lspace = "0em";
8047       node.attributes.rspace = "0em";
8048     } else if (group.mclass === "minner") {
8049       node.attributes.lspace = "0.0556em"; // 1 mu is the most likely option
8050

8053     // Ref: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/MathML/Element/mo
8054 
8055   }

8088 var binrelClass = arg => {
8089   // \binrel@ spacing varies with (bin|rel|ord) of the atom in the argument.
8090   // (by rendering separately and with {}s before and after, and measuring
8091   // the change in spacing).  We'll do roughly the same by detecting the
8092   // atom type directly.
8093   var atom = arg.type === "ordgroup" && arg.body.length ? arg.body[0] : arg;
8094 
8095   if (atom.type === "atom" && (atom.family === "bin" || atom.family === "rel")) {
8096     return "m" + atom.family;
8097   } else {
8098     return "mord";
8099   }
8100 }; // \@binrel{x}{y} renders like y but as mbin/mrel/mord if x is mbin/mrel/mord.
8101 // This is equivalent to \binrel@{x}\binrel@@{y} in AMSTeX.
8102

8105   names: ["\\@binrel"],
8106   props: {
8107     numArgs: 2
8108   },

8116       mode: parser.mode,

8118       body: ordargument(args[1]),
8119       isCharacterBox: utils.isCharacterBox(args[1])
8120     };

8229 var newCell = () => {
8230   // Create an empty cell, to be filled below with parse nodes.
8231   // The parseTree from this module must be constructed like the
8232   // one created by parseArray(), so an empty CD cell must
8233   // be a ParseNode<"styling">. And CD is always displaystyle.
8234   // So these values are fixed and flow can do implicit typing.
8235   return {
8236     type: "styling",
8237     body: [],
8238     mode: "math",
8239     style: "display"

8251 function cdArrow(arrowChar, labels, parser) {
8252   // Return a parse tree of an arrow and its labels.
8253   // This acts in a way similar to a macro expansion.
8254   var funcName = cdArrowFunctionName[arrowChar];
8255 
8256   switch (funcName) {
8257     case "\\\\cdrightarrow":
8258     case "\\\\cdleftarrow":
8259       return parser.callFunction(funcName, [labels[0]], [labels[1]]);
8260 
8261     case "\\uparrow":
8262     case "\\downarrow":
8263       {
8264         var leftLabel = parser.callFunction("\\\\cdleft", [labels[0]], []);
8265         var bareArrow = {
8266           type: "atom",
8267           text: funcName,
8268           mode: "math",
8269           family: "rel"
8270         };
8271         var sizedArrow = parser.callFunction("\\Big", [bareArrow], []);
8272         var rightLabel = parser.callFunction("\\\\cdright", [labels[1]], []);
8273         var arrowGroup = {
8274           type: "ordgroup",
8275           mode: "math",
8276           body: [leftLabel, sizedArrow, rightLabel]
8277         };
8278         return parser.callFunction("\\\\cdparent", [arrowGroup], []);
8279       }
8280 
8281     case "\\\\cdlongequal":
8282       return parser.callFunction("\\\\cdlongequal", [], []);
8283 
8284     case "\\Vert":
8285       {
8286         var arrow = {
8287           type: "textord",
8288           text: "\\Vert",
8289           mode: "math"
8290         };
8291         return parser.callFunction("\\Big", [arrow], []);
8292       }
8293 
8294     default:
8295       return {
8296         type: "textord",
8297         text: " ",
8298         mode: "math"
8299       };
8300   }
8301 }

8303 function parseCD(parser) {
8304   // Get the array's parse nodes with \\ temporarily mapped to \cr.
8305   var parsedRows = [];
8306   parser.gullet.beginGroup();
8307   parser.gullet.macros.set("\\cr", "\\\\\\relax");
8308   parser.gullet.beginGroup();
8309 
8310   while (true) {
8311     // eslint-disable-line no-constant-condition
8312     // Get the parse nodes for the next row.
8313     parsedRows.push(parser.parseExpression(false, "\\\\"));
8314     parser.gullet.endGroup();
8315     parser.gullet.beginGroup();
8316     var next = parser.fetch().text;
8317 
8318     if (next === "&" || next === "\\\\") {
8319       parser.consume();
8320     } else if (next === "\\end") {
8321       if (parsedRows[parsedRows.length - 1].length === 0) {
8322         parsedRows.pop(); // final row ended in \\
8323       }
8324 
8325       break;
8326     } else {
8327       throw new ParseError("Expected \\\\ or \\cr or \\end", parser.nextToken);
8328     }
8329   }
8330 
8331   var row = [];
8332   var body = [row]; // Loop thru the parse nodes. Collect them into cells and arrows.
8333 
8334   for (var i = 0; i < parsedRows.length; i++) {
8335     // Start a new row.
8336     var rowNodes = parsedRows[i]; // Create the first cell.
8337 
8338     var cell = newCell();
8339 
8340     for (var j = 0; j < rowNodes.length; j++) {
8341       if (!isStartOfArrow(rowNodes[j])) {
8342         // If a parseNode is not an arrow, it goes into a cell.
8343         cell.body.push(rowNodes[j]);
8344       } else {
8345         // Parse node j is an "@", the start of an arrow.
8346         // Before starting on the arrow, push the cell into `row`.
8347         row.push(cell); // Now collect parseNodes into an arrow.
8348         // The character after "@" defines the arrow type.
8349 
8350         j += 1;
8351         var arrowChar = assertSymbolNodeType(rowNodes[j]).text; // Create two empty label nodes. We may or may not use them.
8352 
8353         var labels = new Array(2);
8354         labels[0] = {
8355           type: "ordgroup",
8356           mode: "math",
8357           body: []
8358         };
8359         labels[1] = {
8360           type: "ordgroup",
8361           mode: "math",
8362           body: []
8363         }; // Process the arrow.
8364 
8365         if ("=|.".indexOf(arrowChar) > -1) ; else if ("<>AV".indexOf(arrowChar) > -1) {
8366           // Four arrows, `@>>>`, `@<<<`, `@AAA`, and `@VVV`, each take
8367           // two optional labels. E.g. the right-point arrow syntax is
8368           // really:  @>{optional label}>{optional label}>
8369           // Collect parseNodes into labels.
8370           for (var labelNum = 0; labelNum < 2; labelNum++) {
8371             var inLabel = true;
8372 
8373             for (var k = j + 1; k < rowNodes.length; k++) {
8374               if (isLabelEnd(rowNodes[k], arrowChar)) {
8375                 inLabel = false;
8376                 j = k;
8377                 break;
8378               }
8379 
8380               if (isStartOfArrow(rowNodes[k])) {
8381                 throw new ParseError("Missing a " + arrowChar + " character to complete a CD arrow.", rowNodes[k]);
8382               }
8383 
8384               labels[labelNum].body.push(rowNodes[k]);
8385             }
8386 
8387             if (inLabel) {
8388               // isLabelEnd never returned a true.
8389               throw new ParseError("Missing a " + arrowChar + " character to complete a CD arrow.", rowNodes[j]);
8390             }
8391           }
8392         } else {
8393           throw new ParseError("Expected one of \"<>AV=|.\" after @", rowNodes[j]);
8394         } // Now join the arrow to its labels.
8395 
8396 
8397         var arrow = cdArrow(arrowChar, labels, parser); // Wrap the arrow in  ParseNode<"styling">.
8398         // This is done to match parseArray() behavior.
8399 
8400         var wrappedArrow = {
8401           type: "styling",
8402           body: [arrow],
8403           mode: "math",
8404           style: "display" // CD is always displaystyle.
8405 
8406         };
8407         row.push(wrappedArrow); // In CD's syntax, cells are implicit. That is, everything that
8408         // is not an arrow gets collected into a cell. So create an empty
8409         // cell now. It will collect upcoming parseNodes.
8410 
8411         cell = newCell();
8412       }
8413     }
8414 
8415     if (i % 2 === 0) {
8416       // Even-numbered rows consist of: cell, arrow, cell, arrow, ... cell
8417       // The last cell is not yet pushed into `row`, so:
8418       row.push(cell);
8419     } else {
8420       // Odd-numbered rows consist of: vert arrow, empty cell, ... vert arrow
8421       // Remove the empty cell that was placed at the beginning of `row`.
8422       row.shift();
8423     }
8424 
8425     row = [];
8426     body.push(row);
8427   } // End row group
8428 
8429 
8430   parser.gullet.endGroup(); // End array group defining \\
8431 
8432   parser.gullet.endGroup(); // define column separation.
8433 
8434   var cols = new Array(body[0].length).fill({
8435     type: "align",
8436     align: "c",
8437     pregap: 0.25,
8438     // CD package sets \enskip between columns.
8439     postgap: 0.25 // So pre and post each get half an \enskip, i.e. 0.25em.
8440 
8441   });
8442   return {
8443     type: "array",
8444     mode: "math",
8445     body,
8446     arraystretch: 1,
8447     addJot: true,
8448     rowGaps: [null],
8449     cols,
8450     colSeparationType: "CD",
8451     hLinesBeforeRow: new Array(body.length + 1).fill([])
8452   };
8453 } // The functions below are not available for general use.
8454 // They are here only for internal use by the {CD} environment in placing labels
8455 // next to vertical arrows.
8456 // We don't need any such functions for horizontal arrows because we can reuse
8457 // the functionality that already exists for extensible arrows.
8458

8546 defineFunction({
8547   type: "textord",
8548   names: ["\\@char"],
8549   props: {
8550     numArgs: 1,
8551     allowedInText: true
8552   },
8553 
8554   handler(_ref, args) {
8555     var {
8556       parser
8557     } = _ref;
8558     var arg = assertNodeType(args[0], "ordgroup");
8559     var group = arg.body;
8560     var number = "";
8561 
8562     for (var i = 0; i < group.length; i++) {
8563       var node = assertNodeType(group[i], "textord");
8564       number += node.text;
8565     }
8566 
8567     var code = parseInt(number);
8568     var text;
8569 
8570     if (isNaN(code)) {
8571       throw new ParseError("\\@char has non-numeric argument " + number); // If we drop IE support, the following code could be replaced with
8572       // text = String.fromCodePoint(code)
8573     } else if (code < 0 || code >= 0x10ffff) {
8574       throw new ParseError("\\@char with invalid code point " + number);
8575     } else if (code <= 0xffff) {
8576       text = String.fromCharCode(code);
8577     } else {
8578       // Astral code point; split into surrogate halves
8579       code -= 0x10000;
8580       text = String.fromCharCode((code >> 10) + 0xd800, (code & 0x3ff) + 0xdc00);
8581     }
8582 
8583     return {
8584       type: "textord",
8585       mode: parser.mode,
8586       text: text
8587     };
8588   }
8589
