11085 var alignedHandler = function alignedHandler(context, args) {
11086   if (context.envName.indexOf("ed") === -1) {
11087     validateAmsEnvironmentContext(context);
11088   }
11089 
11090   var cols = [];
11091   var separationType = context.envName.indexOf("at") > -1 ? "alignat" : "align";
11092   var isSplit = context.envName === "split";
11093   var res = parseArray(context.parser, {
11094     cols,
11095     addJot: true,
11096     autoTag: isSplit ? undefined : getAutoTag(context.envName),
11097     emptySingleRow: true,
11098     colSeparationType: separationType,
11099     maxNumCols: isSplit ? 2 : undefined,
11100     leqno: context.parser.settings.leqno
11101   }, "display"); // Determining number of columns.
11102   // 1. If the first argument is given, we use it as a number of columns,
11103   //    and makes sure that each row doesn't exceed that number.
11104   // 2. Otherwise, just count number of columns = maximum number
11105   //    of cells in each row ("aligned" mode -- isAligned will be true).
11106   //
11107   // At the same time, prepend empty group {} at beginning of every second
11108   // cell in each row (starting with second cell) so that operators become
11109   // binary.  This behavior is implemented in amsmath's \start@aligned.
11110 
11111   var numMaths;
11112   var numCols = 0;
11113   var emptyGroup = {
11114     type: "ordgroup",
11115     mode: context.mode,
11116     body: []
11117   };
11118 
11119   if (args[0] && args[0].type === "ordgroup") {
11120     var arg0 = "";
11121 
11122     for (var i = 0; i < args[0].body.length; i++) {
11123       var textord = assertNodeType(args[0].body[i], "textord");
11124       arg0 += textord.text;
11125     }
11126 
11127     numMaths = Number(arg0);
11128     numCols = numMaths * 2;
11129   }
11130 
11131   var isAligned = !numCols;
11132   res.body.forEach(function (row) {
11133     for (var _i4 = 1; _i4 < row.length; _i4 += 2) {
11134       // Modify ordgroup node within styling node
11135       var styling = assertNodeType(row[_i4], "styling");
11136       var ordgroup = assertNodeType(styling.body[0], "ordgroup");
11137       ordgroup.body.unshift(emptyGroup);
11138     }
11139 
11140     if (!isAligned) {
11141       // Case 1
11142       var curMaths = row.length / 2;
11143 
11144       if (numMaths < curMaths) {
11145         throw new ParseError("Too many math in a row: " + ("expected " + numMaths + ", but got " + curMaths), row[0]);
11146       }
11147     } else if (numCols < row.length) {
11148       // Case 2
11149       numCols = row.length;
11150     }
11151   }); // Adjusting alignment.
11152   // In aligned mode, we add one \qquad between columns;
11153   // otherwise we add nothing.
11154 
11155   for (var _i5 = 0; _i5 < numCols; ++_i5) {
11156     var align = "r";
11157     var pregap = 0;
11158 
11159     if (_i5 % 2 === 1) {
11160       align = "l";
11161     } else if (_i5 > 0 && isAligned) {
11162       // "aligned" mode.
11163       pregap = 1; // add one \quad
11164     }
11165 
11166     cols[_i5] = {
11167       type: "align",
11168       align: align,
11169       pregap: pregap,
11170       postgap: 0
11171     };
11172   }
11173 
11174   res.colSeparationType = isAligned ? "align" : "alignat";
11175   return res;

11722 var adjustStyle = (size, originalStyle) => {
11723   // Figure out what style this fraction should be in based on the
11724   // function used
11725   var style = originalStyle;
11726 
11727   if (size === "display") {
11728     // Get display style as a default.
11729     // If incoming style is sub/sup, use style.text() to get correct size.
11730     style = style.id >= Style$1.SCRIPT.id ? style.text() : Style$1.DISPLAY;
11731   } else if (size === "text" && style.size === Style$1.DISPLAY.size) {
11732     // We're in a \tfrac but incoming style is displaystyle, so:
11733     style = Style$1.TEXT;
11734   } else if (size === "script") {
11735     style = Style$1.SCRIPT;
11736   } else if (size === "scriptscript") {
11737     style = Style$1.SCRIPTSCRIPT;
11738   }
11739 
11740   return style;
11741 };

11743 var htmlBuilder$4 = (group, options) => {
11744   // Fractions are handled in the TeXbook on pages 444-445, rules 15(a-e).
11745   var style = adjustStyle(group.size, options.style);
11746   var nstyle = style.fracNum();
11747   var dstyle = style.fracDen();
11748   var newOptions;
11749   newOptions = options.havingStyle(nstyle);
11750   var numerm = buildGroup$1(group.numer, newOptions, options);
11751 
11752   if (group.continued) {
11753     // \cfrac inserts a \strut into the numerator.
11754     // Get \strut dimensions from TeXbook page 353.
11755     var hStrut = 8.5 / options.fontMetrics().ptPerEm;
11756     var dStrut = 3.5 / options.fontMetrics().ptPerEm;
11757     numerm.height = numerm.height < hStrut ? hStrut : numerm.height;
11758     numerm.depth = numerm.depth < dStrut ? dStrut : numerm.depth;
11759   }
11760 
11761   newOptions = options.havingStyle(dstyle);
11762   var denomm = buildGroup$1(group.denom, newOptions, options);
11763   var rule;
11764   var ruleWidth;
11765   var ruleSpacing;
11766 
11767   if (group.hasBarLine) {
11768     if (group.barSize) {
11769       ruleWidth = calculateSize(group.barSize, options);
11770       rule = buildCommon.makeLineSpan("frac-line", options, ruleWidth);
11771     } else {
11772       rule = buildCommon.makeLineSpan("frac-line", options);
11773     }
11774 
11775     ruleWidth = rule.height;
11776     ruleSpacing = rule.height;
11777   } else {
11778     rule = null;
11779     ruleWidth = 0;
11780     ruleSpacing = options.fontMetrics().defaultRuleThickness;
11781   } // Rule 15b
11782 
11783 
11784   var numShift;
11785   var clearance;
11786   var denomShift;
11787 
11788   if (style.size === Style$1.DISPLAY.size || group.size === "display") {
11789     numShift = options.fontMetrics().num1;
11790 
11791     if (ruleWidth > 0) {
11792       clearance = 3 * ruleSpacing;
11793     } else {
11794       clearance = 7 * ruleSpacing;
11795     }
11796 
11797     denomShift = options.fontMetrics().denom1;
11798   } else {
11799     if (ruleWidth > 0) {
11800       numShift = options.fontMetrics().num2;
11801       clearance = ruleSpacing;
11802     } else {
11803       numShift = options.fontMetrics().num3;
11804       clearance = 3 * ruleSpacing;
11805     }
11806 
11807     denomShift = options.fontMetrics().denom2;
11808   }
11809 
11810   var frac;
11811 
11812   if (!rule) {
11813     // Rule 15c
11814     var candidateClearance = numShift - numerm.depth - (denomm.height - denomShift);
11815 
11816     if (candidateClearance < clearance) {
11817       numShift += 0.5 * (clearance - candidateClearance);
11818       denomShift += 0.5 * (clearance - candidateClearance);
11819     }
11820 
11821     frac = buildCommon.makeVList({
11822       positionType: "individualShift",
11823       children: [{
11824         type: "elem",
11825         elem: denomm,
11826         shift: denomShift
11827       }, {
11828         type: "elem",
11829         elem: numerm,
11830         shift: -numShift
11831       }]
11832     }, options);
11833   } else {
11834     // Rule 15d
11835     var axisHeight = options.fontMetrics().axisHeight;
11836 
11837     if (numShift - numerm.depth - (axisHeight + 0.5 * ruleWidth) < clearance) {
11838       numShift += clearance - (numShift - numerm.depth - (axisHeight + 0.5 * ruleWidth));
11839     }
11840 
11841     if (axisHeight - 0.5 * ruleWidth - (denomm.height - denomShift) < clearance) {
11842       denomShift += clearance - (axisHeight - 0.5 * ruleWidth - (denomm.height - denomShift));
11843     }
11844 
11845     var midShift = -(axisHeight - 0.5 * ruleWidth);
11846     frac = buildCommon.makeVList({
11847       positionType: "individualShift",
11848       children: [{
11849         type: "elem",
11850         elem: denomm,
11851         shift: denomShift
11852       }, {
11853         type: "elem",
11854         elem: rule,
11855         shift: midShift
11856       }, {
11857         type: "elem",
11858         elem: numerm,
11859         shift: -numShift
11860       }]
11861     }, options);
11862   } // Since we manually change the style sometimes (with \dfrac or \tfrac),
11863   // account for the possible size change here.
11864 
11865 
11866   newOptions = options.havingStyle(style);
11867   frac.height *= newOptions.sizeMultiplier / options.sizeMultiplier;
11868   frac.depth *= newOptions.sizeMultiplier / options.sizeMultiplier; // Rule 15e
11869 
11870   var delimSize;
11871 
11872   if (style.size === Style$1.DISPLAY.size) {
11873     delimSize = options.fontMetrics().delim1;
11874   } else if (style.size === Style$1.SCRIPTSCRIPT.size) {
11875     delimSize = options.havingStyle(Style$1.SCRIPT).fontMetrics().delim2;
11876   } else {
11877     delimSize = options.fontMetrics().delim2;
11878   }
11879 
11880   var leftDelim;
11881   var rightDelim;
11882 
11883   if (group.leftDelim == null) {
11884     leftDelim = makeNullDelimiter(options, ["mopen"]);
11885   } else {
11886     leftDelim = delimiter.customSizedDelim(group.leftDelim, delimSize, true, options.havingStyle(style), group.mode, ["mopen"]);
11887   }
11888 
11889   if (group.continued) {
11890     rightDelim = buildCommon.makeSpan([]); // zero width for \cfrac
11891   } else if (group.rightDelim == null) {
11892     rightDelim = makeNullDelimiter(options, ["mclose"]);
11893   } else {
11894     rightDelim = delimiter.customSizedDelim(group.rightDelim, delimSize, true, options.havingStyle(style), group.mode, ["mclose"]);
11895   }
11896 
11897   return buildCommon.makeSpan(["mord"].concat(newOptions.sizingClasses(options)), [leftDelim, buildCommon.makeSpan(["mfrac"], [frac]), rightDelim], options);

12646 var sizeData = function sizeData(str) {
12647   if (/^[-+]? *(\d+(\.\d*)?|\.\d+)$/.test(str)) {
12648     // str is a number with no unit specified.
12649     // default unit is bp, per graphix package.
12650     return {
12651       number: +str,
12652       unit: "bp"
12653     };
12654   } else {
12655     var match = /([-+]?) *(\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+) *([a-z]{2})/.exec(str);
12656 
12657     if (!match) {
12658       throw new ParseError("Invalid size: '" + str + "' in \\includegraphics");
12659     }
12660 
12661     var data = {
12662       number: +(match[1] + match[2]),
12663       // sign + magnitude, cast to number
12664       unit: match[3]
12665     };
12666 
12667     if (!validUnit(data)) {
12668       throw new ParseError("Invalid unit: '" + data.unit + "' in \\includegraphics.");
12669     }
12670 
12671     return data;
12672   }
12673 };

13040 var assembleSupSub = (base, supGroup, subGroup, options, style, slant, baseShift) => {

13042   var subIsSingleCharacter = subGroup && utils.isCharacterBox(subGroup);
13043   var sub;
13044   var sup; // We manually have to handle the superscripts and subscripts. This,
13045   // aside from the kern calculations, is copied from supsub.
13046 
13047   if (supGroup) {
13048     var elem = buildGroup$1(supGroup, options.havingStyle(style.sup()), options);
13049     sup = {
13050       elem,
13051       kern: Math.max(options.fontMetrics().bigOpSpacing1, options.fontMetrics().bigOpSpacing3 - elem.depth)
13052     };
13053   }
13054 
13055   if (subGroup) {
13056     var _elem = buildGroup$1(subGroup, options.havingStyle(style.sub()), options);
13057 
13058     sub = {
13059       elem: _elem,
13060       kern: Math.max(options.fontMetrics().bigOpSpacing2, options.fontMetrics().bigOpSpacing4 - _elem.height)
13061     };
13062   } // Build the final group as a vlist of the possible subscript, base,
13063   // and possible superscript.
13064 
13065 
13066   var finalGroup;
13067 
13068   if (sup && sub) {
13069     var bottom = options.fontMetrics().bigOpSpacing5 + sub.elem.height + sub.elem.depth + sub.kern + base.depth + baseShift;
13070     finalGroup = buildCommon.makeVList({
13071       positionType: "bottom",
13072       positionData: bottom,
13073       children: [{
13074         type: "kern",
13075         size: options.fontMetrics().bigOpSpacing5
13076       }, {
13077         type: "elem",
13078         elem: sub.elem,
13079         marginLeft: makeEm(-slant)
13080       }, {
13081         type: "kern",
13082         size: sub.kern
13083       }, {
13084         type: "elem",
13085         elem: base
13086       }, {
13087         type: "kern",
13088         size: sup.kern
13089       }, {
13090         type: "elem",
13091         elem: sup.elem,
13092         marginLeft: makeEm(slant)
13093       }, {
13094         type: "kern",
13095         size: options.fontMetrics().bigOpSpacing5
13096       }]
13097     }, options);
13098   } else if (sub) {
13099     var top = base.height - baseShift; // Shift the limits by the slant of the symbol. Note
13100     // that we are supposed to shift the limits by 1/2 of the slant,
13101     // but since we are centering the limits adding a full slant of
13102     // margin will shift by 1/2 that.
13103 
13104     finalGroup = buildCommon.makeVList({
13105       positionType: "top",
13106       positionData: top,
13107       children: [{
13108         type: "kern",
13109         size: options.fontMetrics().bigOpSpacing5
13110       }, {
13111         type: "elem",
13112         elem: sub.elem,
13113         marginLeft: makeEm(-slant)
13114       }, {
13115         type: "kern",
13116         size: sub.kern
13117       }, {
13118         type: "elem",
13119         elem: base
13120       }]
13121     }, options);
13122   } else if (sup) {
13123     var _bottom = base.depth + baseShift;
13124 
13125     finalGroup = buildCommon.makeVList({
13126       positionType: "bottom",
13127       positionData: _bottom,
13128       children: [{
13129         type: "elem",
13130         elem: base
13131       }, {
13132         type: "kern",
13133         size: sup.kern
13134       }, {
13135         type: "elem",
13136         elem: sup.elem,
13137         marginLeft: makeEm(slant)
13138       }, {
13139         type: "kern",
13140         size: options.fontMetrics().bigOpSpacing5
13141       }]
13142     }, options);
13143   } else {
13144     // This case probably shouldn't occur (this would mean the
13145     // supsub was sending us a group with no superscript or
13146     // subscript) but be safe.
13147     return base;
13148   }
13149 
13150   var parts = [finalGroup];
13151 
13152   if (sub && slant !== 0 && !subIsSingleCharacter) {
13153     // A negative margin-left was applied to the lower limit.
13154     // Avoid an overlap by placing a spacer on the left on the group.
13155     var spacer = buildCommon.makeSpan(["mspace"], [], options);
13156     spacer.style.marginRight = makeEm(slant);
13157     parts.unshift(spacer);
13158   }
13159 
13160   return buildCommon.makeSpan(["mop", "op-limits"], parts, options);
13161 };

13163 // Limits, symbols
13164 // Most operators have a large successor symbol, but these don't.
13165 var noSuccessor = ["\\smallint"]; // NOTE: Unlike most `htmlBuilder`s, this one handles not only "op", but also
13166 // "supsub" since some of them (like \int) can affect super/subscripting.
13167 
13168 var htmlBuilder$2 = (grp, options) => {
13169   // Operators are handled in the TeXbook pg. 443-444, rule 13(a).
13170   var supGroup;
13171   var subGroup;
13172   var hasLimits = false;
13173   var group;
13174 
13175   if (grp.type === "supsub") {
13176     // If we have limits, supsub will pass us its group to handle. Pull
13177     // out the superscript and subscript and set the group to the op in
13178     // its base.
13179     supGroup = grp.sup;
13180     subGroup = grp.sub;
13181     group = assertNodeType(grp.base, "op");
13182     hasLimits = true;
13183   } else {
13184     group = assertNodeType(grp, "op");
13185   }
13186 
13187   var style = options.style;
13188   var large = false;
13189 
13190   if (style.size === Style$1.DISPLAY.size && group.symbol && !utils.contains(noSuccessor, group.name)) {
13191     // Most symbol operators get larger in displaystyle (rule 13)
13192     large = true;
13193   }
13194 
13195   var base;
13196 
13197   if (group.symbol) {
13198     // If this is a symbol, create the symbol.
13199     var fontName = large ? "Size2-Regular" : "Size1-Regular";
13200     var stash = "";
13201 
13202     if (group.name === "\\oiint" || group.name === "\\oiiint") {
13203       // No font glyphs yet, so use a glyph w/o the oval.
13204       // TODO: When font glyphs are available, delete this code.
13205       stash = group.name.slice(1);
13206       group.name = stash === "oiint" ? "\\iint" : "\\iiint";
13207     }
13208 
13209     base = buildCommon.makeSymbol(group.name, fontName, "math", options, ["mop", "op-symbol", large ? "large-op" : "small-op"]);
13210 
13211     if (stash.length > 0) {
13212       // We're in \oiint or \oiiint. Overlay the oval.
13213       // TODO: When font glyphs are available, delete this code.
13214       var italic = base.italic;
13215       var oval = buildCommon.staticSvg(stash + "Size" + (large ? "2" : "1"), options);
13216       base = buildCommon.makeVList({
13217         positionType: "individualShift",
13218         children: [{
13219           type: "elem",
13220           elem: base,
13221           shift: 0
13222         }, {
13223           type: "elem",
13224           elem: oval,
13225           shift: large ? 0.08 : 0
13226         }]
13227       }, options);
13228       group.name = "\\" + stash;
13229       base.classes.unshift("mop"); // $FlowFixMe
13230 
13231       base.italic = italic;
13232     }
13233   } else if (group.body) {
13234     // If this is a list, compose that list.
13235     var inner = buildExpression$1(group.body, options, true);
13236 
13237     if (inner.length === 1 && inner[0] instanceof SymbolNode) {
13238       base = inner[0];
13239       base.classes[0] = "mop"; // replace old mclass
13240     } else {
13241       base = buildCommon.makeSpan(["mop"], inner, options);
13242     }
13243   } else {
13244     // Otherwise, this is a text operator. Build the text from the
13245     // operator's name.
13246     var output = [];
13247 
13248     for (var i = 1; i < group.name.length; i++) {
13249       output.push(buildCommon.mathsym(group.name[i], group.mode, options));
13250     }
13251 
13252     base = buildCommon.makeSpan(["mop"], output, options);
13253   } // If content of op is a single symbol, shift it vertically.
13254 
13255 
13256   var baseShift = 0;
13257   var slant = 0;
13258 
13259   if ((base instanceof SymbolNode || group.name === "\\oiint" || group.name === "\\oiiint") && !group.suppressBaseShift) {
13260     // We suppress the shift of the base of \overset and \underset. Otherwise,
13261     // shift the symbol so its center lies on the axis (rule 13). It
13262     // appears that our fonts have the centers of the symbols already
13263     // almost on the axis, so these numbers are very small. Note we
13264     // don't actually apply this here, but instead it is used either in
13265     // the vlist creation or separately when there are no limits.
13266     baseShift = (base.height - base.depth) / 2 - options.fontMetrics().axisHeight; // The slant of the symbol is just its italic correction.
13267     // $FlowFixMe
13268 
13269     slant = base.italic;
13270   }
13271 
13272   if (hasLimits) {
13273     return assembleSupSub(base, supGroup, subGroup, options, style, slant, baseShift);
13274   } else {
13275     if (baseShift) {
13276       base.style.position = "relative";
13277       base.style.top = makeEm(baseShift);
13278     }
13279 
13280     return base;
13281   }
13282 };

13284 var mathmlBuilder$1 = (group, options) => {
13285   var node;
13286 
13287   if (group.symbol) {
13288     // This is a symbol. Just add the symbol.
13289     node = new MathNode("mo", [makeText(group.name, group.mode)]);
13290 
13291     if (utils.contains(noSuccessor, group.name)) {
13292       node.setAttribute("largeop", "false");
13293     }
13294   } else if (group.body) {
13295     // This is an operator with children. Add them.
13296     node = new MathNode("mo", buildExpression(group.body, options));
13297   } else {
13298     // This is a text operator. Add all of the characters from the
13299     // operator's name.
13300     node = new MathNode("mi", [new TextNode(group.name.slice(1))]); // Append an <mo>&ApplyFunction;</mo>.
13301     // ref: https://www.w3.org/TR/REC-MathML/chap3_2.html#sec3.2.4

13304 
13305     if (group.parentIsSupSub) {
13306       node = new MathNode("mrow", [node, operator]);
13307     } else {
13308       node = newDocumentFragment([node, operator]);
13309     }
13310   }
13311 
13312   return node;

13544 var mathmlBuilder = (group, options) => {
13545   // The steps taken here are similar to the html version.
13546   var expression = buildExpression(group.body, options.withFont("mathrm")); // Is expression a string or has it something like a fraction?
13547 
13548   var isAllString = true; // default
13549 
13550   for (var i = 0; i < expression.length; i++) {
13551     var node = expression[i];
13552 
13553     if (node instanceof mathMLTree.SpaceNode) ; else if (node instanceof mathMLTree.MathNode) {
13554       switch (node.type) {
13555         case "mi":
13556         case "mn":
13557         case "ms":
13558         case "mspace":
13559         case "mtext":
13560           break;
13561         // Do nothing yet.
13562 
13563         case "mo":
13564           {
13565             var child = node.children[0];
13566 
13567             if (node.children.length === 1 && child instanceof mathMLTree.TextNode) {
13568               child.text = child.text.replace(/\u2212/, "-").replace(/\u2217/, "*");
13569             } else {
13570               isAllString = false;
13571             }
13572 
13573             break;
13574           }
13575 
13576         default:
13577           isAllString = false;
13578       }
13579     } else {
13580       isAllString = false;
13581     }
13582   }
13583 
13584   if (isAllString) {
13585     // Write a single TextNode instead of multiple nested tags.
13586     var word = expression.map(node => node.toText()).join("");
13587     expression = [new mathMLTree.TextNode(word)];
13588   }
13589 
13590   var identifier = new mathMLTree.MathNode("mi", expression);
13591   identifier.setAttribute("mathvariant", "normal"); // \u2061 is the same as &ApplyFunction;
13592   // ref: https://www.w3schools.com/charsets/ref_html_entities_a.asp
13593 
13594   var operator = new mathMLTree.MathNode("mo", [makeText("\u2061", "text")]);
13595 
13596   if (group.parentIsSupSub) {
13597     return new mathMLTree.MathNode("mrow", [identifier, operator]);
13598   } else {
13599     return mathMLTree.newDocumentFragment([identifier, operator]);
13600   }

13953 function sizingGroup(value, options, baseOptions) {
13954   var inner = buildExpression$1(value, options, false);
13955   var multiplier = options.sizeMultiplier / baseOptions.sizeMultiplier; // Add size-resetting classes to the inner list and set maxFontSize
13956   // manually. Handle nested size changes.
13957 
13958   for (var i = 0; i < inner.length; i++) {
13959     var pos = inner[i].classes.indexOf("sizing");
13960 
13961     if (pos < 0) {
13962       Array.prototype.push.apply(inner[i].classes, options.sizingClasses(baseOptions));
13963     } else if (inner[i].classes[pos + 1] === "reset-size" + options.size) {
13964       // This is a nested size change: e.g., inner[i] is the "b" in
13965       // `\Huge a \small b`. Override the old size (the `reset-` class)
13966       // but not the new size.
13967       inner[i].classes[pos + 1] = "reset-size" + baseOptions.size;
13968     }
13969 
13970     inner[i].height *= multiplier;
13971     inner[i].depth *= multiplier;
13972   }
13973 
13974   return buildCommon.makeFragment(inner);
13975 }
13976 var sizeFuncs = ["\\tiny", "\\sixptsize", "\\scriptsize", "\\footnotesize", "\\small", "\\normalsize", "\\large", "\\Large", "\\LARGE", "\\huge", "\\Huge"];
13977 var htmlBuilder = (group, options) => {
13978   // Handle sizing operators like \Huge. Real TeX doesn't actually allow
13979   // these functions inside of math expressions, so we do some special
13980   // handling.
13981   var newOptions = options.havingSize(group.size);
13982   return sizingGroup(group.body, newOptions, options);
13983 };
13984 defineFunction({
13985   type: "sizing",
13986   names: sizeFuncs,
13987   props: {
13988     numArgs: 0,
13989     allowedInText: true
13990   },
13991   handler: (_ref, args) => {
13992     var {
13993       breakOnTokenText,
13994       funcName,
13995       parser
13996     } = _ref;
13997     var body = parser.parseExpression(false, breakOnTokenText);
13998     return {
13999       type: "sizing",
14000       mode: parser.mode,
14001       // Figure out what size to use based on the list of functions above
14002       size: sizeFuncs.indexOf(funcName) + 1,
14003       body
14004     };
14005   },
14006   htmlBuilder,
14007   mathmlBuilder: (group, options) => {
14008     var newOptions = options.havingSize(group.size);
14009     var inner = buildExpression(group.body, newOptions);
14010     var node = new mathMLTree.MathNode("mstyle", inner); // TODO(emily): This doesn't produce the correct size for nested size
14011     // changes, because we don't keep state of what style we're currently
14012     // in, so we can't reset the size to normal before changing it.  Now
14013     // that we're passing an options parameter we should be able to fix
14014     // this.
14015 
14016     node.setAttribute("mathsize", makeEm(newOptions.sizeMultiplier));
14017     return node;

14021 // smash, with optional [tb], as in AMS
14022 defineFunction({
14023   type: "smash",
14024   names: ["\\smash"],
14025   props: {
14026     numArgs: 1,
14027     numOptionalArgs: 1,
14028     allowedInText: true
14029   },
14030   handler: (_ref, args, optArgs) => {
14031     var {
14032       parser
14033     } = _ref;
14034     var smashHeight = false;
14035     var smashDepth = false;
14036     var tbArg = optArgs[0] && assertNodeType(optArgs[0], "ordgroup");
14037 
14038     if (tbArg) {
14039       // Optional [tb] argument is engaged.
14040       // ref: amsmath: \renewcommand{\smash}[1][tb]{%
14041       //               def\mb@t{\ht}\def\mb@b{\dp}\def\mb@tb{\ht\z@\z@\dp}%
14042       var letter = "";
14043 
14044       for (var i = 0; i < tbArg.body.length; ++i) {
14045         var node = tbArg.body[i]; // $FlowFixMe: Not every node type has a `text` property.
14046 
14047         letter = node.text;
14048 
14049         if (letter === "t") {
14050           smashHeight = true;
14051         } else if (letter === "b") {
14052           smashDepth = true;
14053         } else {
14054           smashHeight = false;
14055           smashDepth = false;
14056           break;
14057         }
14058       }
14059     } else {
14060       smashHeight = true;
14061       smashDepth = true;
14062     }
14063 
14064     var body = args[0];
14065     return {
14066       type: "smash",
14067       mode: parser.mode,
14068       body,
14069       smashHeight,
14070       smashDepth
14071     };
14072   },
14073   htmlBuilder: (group, options) => {
14074     var node = buildCommon.makeSpan([], [buildGroup$1(group.body, options)]);
14075 
14076     if (!group.smashHeight && !group.smashDepth) {
14077       return node;
14078     }
14079 
14080     if (group.smashHeight) {
14081       node.height = 0; // In order to influence makeVList, we have to reset the children.
14082 
14083       if (node.children) {
14084         for (var i = 0; i < node.children.length; i++) {
14085           node.children[i].height = 0;
14086         }
14087       }
14088     }
14089 
14090     if (group.smashDepth) {
14091       node.depth = 0;
14092 
14093       if (node.children) {
14094         for (var _i = 0; _i < node.children.length; _i++) {
14095           node.children[_i].depth = 0;
14096         }
14097       }
14098     } // At this point, we've reset the TeX-like height and depth values.
14099     // But the span still has an HTML line height.
14100     // makeVList applies "display: table-cell", which prevents the browser
14101     // from acting on that line height. So we'll call makeVList now.
14102 
14103 
14104     var smashedNode = buildCommon.makeVList({
14105       positionType: "firstBaseline",
14106       children: [{
14107         type: "elem",
14108         elem: node
14109       }]
14110     }, options); // For spacing, TeX treats \hphantom as a math group (same spacing as ord).
14111 
14112     return buildCommon.makeSpan(["mord"], [smashedNode], options);
14113   },
14114   mathmlBuilder: (group, options) => {
14115     var node = new mathMLTree.MathNode("mpadded", [buildGroup(group.body, options)]);
14116 
14117     if (group.smashHeight) {
14118       node.setAttribute("height", "0px");
14119     }
14120 
14121     if (group.smashDepth) {
14122       node.setAttribute("depth", "0px");
14123     }
14124 
14125     return node;
14126   }

14129 defineFunction({
14130   type: "sqrt",
14131   names: ["\\sqrt"],
14132   props: {
14133     numArgs: 1,
14134     numOptionalArgs: 1
14135   },
14136 
14137   handler(_ref, args, optArgs) {
14138     var {
14139       parser
14140     } = _ref;
14141     var index = optArgs[0];
14142     var body = args[0];
14143     return {
14144       type: "sqrt",
14145       mode: parser.mode,
14146       body,
14147       index
14148     };
14149   },
14150 
14151   htmlBuilder(group, options) {
14152     // Square roots are handled in the TeXbook pg. 443, Rule 11.
14153     // First, we do the same steps as in overline to build the inner group
14154     // and line
14155     var inner = buildGroup$1(group.body, options.havingCrampedStyle());
14156 
14157     if (inner.height === 0) {
14158       // Render a small surd.
14159       inner.height = options.fontMetrics().xHeight;
14160     } // Some groups can return document fragments.  Handle those by wrapping
14161     // them in a span.
14162 
14163 
14164     inner = buildCommon.wrapFragment(inner, options); // Calculate the minimum size for the \surd delimiter
14165 
14166     var metrics = options.fontMetrics();
14167     var theta = metrics.defaultRuleThickness;
14168     var phi = theta;
14169 
14170     if (options.style.id < Style$1.TEXT.id) {
14171       phi = options.fontMetrics().xHeight;
14172     } // Calculate the clearance between the body and line
14173 
14174 
14175     var lineClearance = theta + phi / 4;
14176     var minDelimiterHeight = inner.height + inner.depth + lineClearance + theta; // Create a sqrt SVG of the required minimum size
14177 
14178     var {
14179       span: img,
14180       ruleWidth,
14181       advanceWidth
14182     } = delimiter.sqrtImage(minDelimiterHeight, options);
14183     var delimDepth = img.height - ruleWidth; // Adjust the clearance based on the delimiter size
14184 
14185     if (delimDepth > inner.height + inner.depth + lineClearance) {
14186       lineClearance = (lineClearance + delimDepth - inner.height - inner.depth) / 2;
14187     } // Shift the sqrt image
14188 
14189 
14190     var imgShift = img.height - inner.height - lineClearance - ruleWidth;
14191     inner.style.paddingLeft = makeEm(advanceWidth); // Overlay the image and the argument.
14192 
14193     var body = buildCommon.makeVList({
14194       positionType: "firstBaseline",
14195       children: [{
14196         type: "elem",
14197         elem: inner,
14198         wrapperClasses: ["svg-align"]
14199       }, {
14200         type: "kern",
14201         size: -(inner.height + imgShift)
14202       }, {
14203         type: "elem",
14204         elem: img
14205       }, {
14206         type: "kern",
14207         size: ruleWidth
14208       }]
14209     }, options);
14210 
14211     if (!group.index) {
14212       return buildCommon.makeSpan(["mord", "sqrt"], [body], options);
14213     } else {
14214       // Handle the optional root index
14215       // The index is always in scriptscript style
14216       var newOptions = options.havingStyle(Style$1.SCRIPTSCRIPT);
14217       var rootm = buildGroup$1(group.index, newOptions, options); // The amount the index is shifted by. This is taken from the TeX
14218       // source, in the definition of `\r@@t`.
14219 
14220       var toShift = 0.6 * (body.height - body.depth); // Build a VList with the superscript shifted up correctly
14221 
14222       var rootVList = buildCommon.makeVList({
14223         positionType: "shift",
14224         positionData: -toShift,
14225         children: [{
14226           type: "elem",
14227           elem: rootm
14228         }]
14229       }, options); // Add a class surrounding it so we can add on the appropriate
14230       // kerning
14231 
14232       var rootVListWrap = buildCommon.makeSpan(["root"], [rootVList]);
14233       return buildCommon.makeSpan(["mord", "sqrt"], [rootVListWrap, body], options);
14234     }
14235   },
14236 
14237   mathmlBuilder(group, options) {
14238     var {
14239       body,
14240       index
14241     } = group;
14242     return index ? new mathMLTree.MathNode("mroot", [buildGroup(body, options), buildGroup(index, options)]) : new mathMLTree.MathNode("msqrt", [buildGroup(body, options)]);
14243   }
14244

14311 /**
14312  * Sometimes, groups perform special rules when they have superscripts or
14313  * subscripts attached to them. This function lets the `supsub` group know that
14314  * Sometimes, groups perform special rules when they have superscripts or
14315  * its inner element should handle the superscripts and subscripts instead of
14316  * handling them itself.
14317  */
14318 var htmlBuilderDelegate = function htmlBuilderDelegate(group, options) {
14319   var base = group.base;
14320 
14321   if (!base) {
14322     return null;
14323   } else if (base.type === "op") {
14324     // Operators handle supsubs differently when they have limits
14325     // (e.g. `\displaystyle\sum_2^3`)
14326     var delegate = base.limits && (options.style.size === Style$1.DISPLAY.size || base.alwaysHandleSupSub);
14327     return delegate ? htmlBuilder$2 : null;
14328   } else if (base.type === "operatorname") {
14329     var _delegate = base.alwaysHandleSupSub && (options.style.size === Style$1.DISPLAY.size || base.limits);
14330 
14331     return _delegate ? htmlBuilder$1 : null;
14332   } else if (base.type === "accent") {
14333     return utils.isCharacterBox(base.base) ? htmlBuilder$a : null;
14334   } else if (base.type === "horizBrace") {
14335     var isSup = !group.sub;
14336     return isSup === base.isOver ? htmlBuilder$3 : null;
14337   } else {
14338     return null;
14339   }
14340 }; // Super scripts and subscripts, whose precise placement can depend on other
14341 // functions that precede them.
14342 
14343 
14344 defineFunctionBuilders({
14345   type: "supsub",
14346 
14347   htmlBuilder(group, options) {
14348     // Superscript and subscripts are handled in the TeXbook on page
14349     // 445-446, rules 18(a-f).
14350     // Here is where we defer to the inner group if it should handle
14351     // superscripts and subscripts itself.
14352     var builderDelegate = htmlBuilderDelegate(group, options);
14353 
14354     if (builderDelegate) {
14355       return builderDelegate(group, options);
14356     }
14357 
14358     var {
14359       base: valueBase,
14360       sup: valueSup,
14361       sub: valueSub
14362     } = group;
14363     var base = buildGroup$1(valueBase, options);
14364     var supm;
14365     var subm;
14366     var metrics = options.fontMetrics(); // Rule 18a
14367 
14368     var supShift = 0;
14369     var subShift = 0;
14370     var isCharacterBox = valueBase && utils.isCharacterBox(valueBase);
14371 
14372     if (valueSup) {
14373       var newOptions = options.havingStyle(options.style.sup());
14374       supm = buildGroup$1(valueSup, newOptions, options);
14375 
14376       if (!isCharacterBox) {
14377         supShift = base.height - newOptions.fontMetrics().supDrop * newOptions.sizeMultiplier / options.sizeMultiplier;
14378       }
14379     }
14380 
14381     if (valueSub) {
14382       var _newOptions = options.havingStyle(options.style.sub());
14383 
14384       subm = buildGroup$1(valueSub, _newOptions, options);
14385 
14386       if (!isCharacterBox) {
14387         subShift = base.depth + _newOptions.fontMetrics().subDrop * _newOptions.sizeMultiplier / options.sizeMultiplier;
14388       }
14389     } // Rule 18c
14390 
14391 
14392     var minSupShift;
14393 
14394     if (options.style === Style$1.DISPLAY) {
14395       minSupShift = metrics.sup1;
14396     } else if (options.style.cramped) {
14397       minSupShift = metrics.sup3;
14398     } else {
14399       minSupShift = metrics.sup2;
14400     } // scriptspace is a font-size-independent size, so scale it
14401     // appropriately for use as the marginRight.
14402 
14403 
14404     var multiplier = options.sizeMultiplier;
14405     var marginRight = makeEm(0.5 / metrics.ptPerEm / multiplier);
14406     var marginLeft = null;
14407 
14408     if (subm) {
14409       // Subscripts shouldn't be shifted by the base's italic correction.
14410       // Account for that by shifting the subscript back the appropriate
14411       // amount. Note we only do this when the base is a single symbol.
14412       var isOiint = group.base && group.base.type === "op" && group.base.name && (group.base.name === "\\oiint" || group.base.name === "\\oiiint");
14413 
14414       if (base instanceof SymbolNode || isOiint) {
14415         // $FlowFixMe
14416         marginLeft = makeEm(-base.italic);
14417       }
14418     }
14419 
14420     var supsub;
14421 
14422     if (supm && subm) {
14423       supShift = Math.max(supShift, minSupShift, supm.depth + 0.25 * metrics.xHeight);
14424       subShift = Math.max(subShift, metrics.sub2);
14425       var ruleWidth = metrics.defaultRuleThickness; // Rule 18e
14426 
14427       var maxWidth = 4 * ruleWidth;
14428 
14429       if (supShift - supm.depth - (subm.height - subShift) < maxWidth) {
14430         subShift = maxWidth - (supShift - supm.depth) + subm.height;
14431         var psi = 0.8 * metrics.xHeight - (supShift - supm.depth);
14432 
14433         if (psi > 0) {
14434           supShift += psi;
14435           subShift -= psi;
14436         }
14437       }
14438 
14439       var vlistElem = [{
14440         type: "elem",
14441         elem: subm,
14442         shift: subShift,
14443         marginRight,
14444         marginLeft
14445       }, {
14446         type: "elem",
14447         elem: supm,
14448         shift: -supShift,
14449         marginRight
14450       }];
14451       supsub = buildCommon.makeVList({
14452         positionType: "individualShift",
14453         children: vlistElem
14454       }, options);
14455     } else if (subm) {
14456       // Rule 18b
14457       subShift = Math.max(subShift, metrics.sub1, subm.height - 0.8 * metrics.xHeight);
14458       var _vlistElem = [{
14459         type: "elem",
14460         elem: subm,
14461         marginLeft,
14462         marginRight
14463       }];
14464       supsub = buildCommon.makeVList({
14465         positionType: "shift",
14466         positionData: subShift,
14467         children: _vlistElem
14468       }, options);
14469     } else if (supm) {
14470       // Rule 18c, d
14471       supShift = Math.max(supShift, minSupShift, supm.depth + 0.25 * metrics.xHeight);
14472       supsub = buildCommon.makeVList({
14473         positionType: "shift",
14474         positionData: -supShift,
14475         children: [{
14476           type: "elem",
14477           elem: supm,
14478           marginRight
14479         }]
14480       }, options);
14481     } else {
14482       throw new Error("supsub must have either sup or sub.");
14483     } // Wrap the supsub vlist in a span.msupsub to reset text-align.
14484 
14485 
14486     var mclass = getTypeOfDomTree(base, "right") || "mord";
14487     return buildCommon.makeSpan([mclass], [base, buildCommon.makeSpan(["msupsub"], [supsub])], options);
14488   },
14489 
14490   mathmlBuilder(group, options) {
14491     // Is the inner group a relevant horizonal brace?
14492     var isBrace = false;
14493     var isOver;
14494     var isSup;
14495 
14496     if (group.base && group.base.type === "horizBrace") {
14497       isSup = !!group.sup;
14498 
14499       if (isSup === group.base.isOver) {
14500         isBrace = true;
14501         isOver = group.base.isOver;
14502       }
14503     }
14504 
14505     if (group.base && (group.base.type === "op" || group.base.type === "operatorname")) {
14506       group.base.parentIsSupSub = true;
14507     }
14508 
14509     var children = [buildGroup(group.base, options)];
14510 
14511     if (group.sub) {
14512       children.push(buildGroup(group.sub, options));
14513     }
14514 
14515     if (group.sup) {
14516       children.push(buildGroup(group.sup, options));
14517     }
14518 
14519     var nodeType;
14520 
14521     if (isBrace) {
14522       nodeType = isOver ? "mover" : "munder";
14523     } else if (!group.sub) {
14524       var base = group.base;
14525 
14526       if (base && base.type === "op" && base.limits && (options.style === Style$1.DISPLAY || base.alwaysHandleSupSub)) {
14527         nodeType = "mover";
14528       } else if (base && base.type === "operatorname" && base.alwaysHandleSupSub && (base.limits || options.style === Style$1.DISPLAY)) {
14529         nodeType = "mover";
14530       } else {
14531         nodeType = "msup";
14532       }
14533     } else if (!group.sup) {
14534       var _base = group.base;
14535 
14536       if (_base && _base.type === "op" && _base.limits && (options.style === Style$1.DISPLAY || _base.alwaysHandleSupSub)) {
14537         nodeType = "munder";
14538       } else if (_base && _base.type === "operatorname" && _base.alwaysHandleSupSub && (_base.limits || options.style === Style$1.DISPLAY)) {
14539         nodeType = "munder";
14540       } else {
14541         nodeType = "msub";
14542       }
14543     } else {
14544       var _base2 = group.base;
14545 
14546       if (_base2 && _base2.type === "op" && _base2.limits && options.style === Style$1.DISPLAY) {
14547         nodeType = "munderover";
14548       } else if (_base2 && _base2.type === "operatorname" && _base2.alwaysHandleSupSub && (options.style === Style$1.DISPLAY || _base2.limits)) {
14549         nodeType = "munderover";
14550       } else {
14551         nodeType = "msubsup";
14552       }
14553     }
14554 
14555     return new mathMLTree.MathNode(nodeType, children);
14556   }
14557 
14558 });

14646 var cssSpace = {
14647   "\\nobreak": "nobreak",
14648   "\\allowbreak": "allowbreak"
14649 }; // A lookup table to determine whether a spacing function/symbol should be
14650 // treated like a regular space character.  If a symbol or command is a key
14651 // in this table, then it should be a regular space character.  Furthermore,
14652 // the associated value may have a `className` specifying an extra CSS class
14653 // to add to the created `span`.
14654 
14655 var regularSpace = {
14656   " ": {},
14657   "\\ ": {},
14658   "~": {
14659     className: "nobreak"
14660   },
14661   "\\space": {},
14662   "\\nobreakspace": {
14663     className: "nobreak"
14664   }
14665 }; // ParseNode<"spacing"> created in Parser.js from the "spacing" symbol Groups in
14666 // src/symbols.js.
14667 
14668 defineFunctionBuilders({
14669   type: "spacing",
14670 
14671   htmlBuilder(group, options) {
14672     if (regularSpace.hasOwnProperty(group.text)) {
14673       var className = regularSpace[group.text].className || ""; // Spaces are generated by adding an actual space. Each of these
14674       // things has an entry in the symbols table, so these will be turned
14675       // into appropriate outputs.
14676 
14677       if (group.mode === "text") {
14678         var ord = buildCommon.makeOrd(group, options, "textord");
14679         ord.classes.push(className);
14680         return ord;
14681       } else {
14682         return buildCommon.makeSpan(["mspace", className], [buildCommon.mathsym(group.text, group.mode, options)], options);
14683       }
14684     } else if (cssSpace.hasOwnProperty(group.text)) {
14685       // Spaces based on just a CSS class.
14686       return buildCommon.makeSpan(["mspace", cssSpace[group.text]], [], options);
14687     } else {
14688       throw new ParseError("Unknown type of space \"" + group.text + "\"");
14689     }
14690   },
14691 
14692   mathmlBuilder(group, options) {
14693     var node;
14694 
14695     if (regularSpace.hasOwnProperty(group.text)) {
14696       node = new mathMLTree.MathNode("mtext", [new mathMLTree.TextNode("\u00a0")]);
14697     } else if (cssSpace.hasOwnProperty(group.text)) {
14698       // CSS-based MathML spaces (\nobreak, \allowbreak) are ignored
14699       return new mathMLTree.MathNode("mspace");
14700     } else {
14701       throw new ParseError("Unknown type of space \"" + group.text + "\"");
14702     }
14703 
14704     return node;
14705   }
14706

14732 var textFontFamilies = {
14733   "\\text": undefined,
14734   "\\textrm": "textrm",
14735   "\\textsf": "textsf",
14736   "\\texttt": "texttt",
14737   "\\textnormal": "textrm"
14738 };
14739 var textFontWeights = {
14740   "\\textbf": "textbf",
14741   "\\textmd": "textmd"
14742 };
14743 var textFontShapes = {
14744   "\\textit": "textit",
14745   "\\textup": "textup"
14746 };
14747 
14748 var optionsWithFont = (group, options) => {
14749   var font = group.font; // Checks if the argument is a font family or a font style.
14750 
14751   if (!font) {
14752     return options;
14753   } else if (textFontFamilies[font]) {
14754     return options.withTextFontFamily(textFontFamilies[font]);
14755   } else if (textFontWeights[font]) {
14756     return options.withTextFontWeight(textFontWeights[font]);
14757   } else if (font === "\\emph") {
14758     return options.fontShape === "textit" ? options.withTextFontShape("textup") : options.withTextFontShape("textit");
14759   }
14760 
14761   return options.withTextFontShape(textFontShapes[font]);
14762 };

14948 /**
14949  * Converts verb group into body string.
14950  *
14951  * \verb* replaces each space with an open box \u2423
14952  * \verb replaces each space with a no-break space \xA0
14953  */
14954 
14955 var makeVerb = group => group.body.replace(/ /g, group.star ? '\u2423' : '\xA0');
14956 
14957 /** Include this to ensure that all functions are defined. */
14958 var functions = _functions;
14959 
14960 /**
14961  * The Lexer class handles tokenizing the input in various ways. Since our
14962  * parser expects us to be able to backtrack, the lexer allows lexing from any
14963  * given starting point.
14964  *
14965  * Its main exposed function is the `lex` function, which takes a position to
14966  * lex from and a type of token to lex. It defers to the appropriate `_innerLex`
14967  * function.
14968  *
14969  * The various `_innerLex` functions perform the actual lexing of different
14970  * kinds.
14971  */
14972 
14973 /* The following tokenRegex 
14974  * - matches typical whitespace (but not NBSP etc.) using its first group 
14975  * - does not match any control character \x00-\x1f except whitespace 
14976  * - does not match a bare backslash 
14977  * - matches any ASCII character except those just mentioned 
14978  * - does not match the BMP private use area \uE000-\uF8FF 
14979  * - does not match bare surrogate code units 
14980  * - matches any BMP character except for those just described 
14981  * - matches any valid Unicode surrogate pair 
14982  * - matches a backslash followed by one or more whitespace characters 
14983  * - matches a backslash followed by one or more letters then whitespace 
14984  * - matches a backslash followed by any BMP character 
14985  * Capturing groups: 
14986  *   [1] regular whitespace 
14987  *   [2] backslash followed by whitespace 
14988  *   [3] anything else, which may include: 
14989  *     [4] left character of \verb* 
14990  *     [5] left character of \verb 
14991  *     [6] backslash followed by word, excluding any trailing whitespace 
14992  * Just because the Lexer matches something doesn't mean it's valid input: 
14993  * If there is no matching function or symbol definition, the Parser will 
14994  * still reject the input. 
14995  */
14996 var spaceRegexString = "[ \r\n\t]";
14997 var controlWordRegexString = "\\\\[a-zA-Z@]+";
14998 var controlSymbolRegexString = "\\\\[^\uD800-\uDFFF]";
14999 var controlWordWhitespaceRegexString = "(" + controlWordRegexString + ")" + spaceRegexString + "*";
15000 var controlSpaceRegexString = "\\\\(\n|[ \r\t]+\n?)[ \r\t]*";
15001 var combiningDiacriticalMarkString = "[\u0300-\u036f]";
15002 var combiningDiacriticalMarksEndRegex = new RegExp(combiningDiacriticalMarkString + "+$");
15003 var tokenRegexString = "(" + spaceRegexString + "+)|" + ( // whitespace
15004 controlSpaceRegexString + "|") + // \whitespace
15005 "([!-\\[\\]-\u2027\u202A-\uD7FF\uF900-\uFFFF]" + ( // single codepoint
15006 combiningDiacriticalMarkString + "*") + // ...plus accents
15007 "|[\uD800-\uDBFF][\uDC00-\uDFFF]" + ( // surrogate pair
15008 combiningDiacriticalMarkString + "*") + // ...plus accents
15009 "|\\\\verb\\*([^]).*?\\4" + // \verb*
15010 "|\\\\verb([^*a-zA-Z]).*?\\5" + ( // \verb unstarred
15011 "|" + controlWordWhitespaceRegexString) + ( // \macroName + spaces
15012 "|" + controlSymbolRegexString + ")"); // \\, \', etc.
15013 
15014 /** Main Lexer class */
15015 
15016 class Lexer {
15017   // Category codes. The lexer only supports comment characters (14) for now.
15018   // MacroExpander additionally distinguishes active (13).
15019   constructor(input, settings) {
15020     this.input = void 0;
15021     this.settings = void 0;
15022     this.tokenRegex = void 0;
15023     this.catcodes = void 0;
15024     // Separate accents from characters
15025     this.input = input;
15026     this.settings = settings;
15027     this.tokenRegex = new RegExp(tokenRegexString, 'g');
15028     this.catcodes = {
15029       "%": 14,
15030       // comment character
15031       "~": 13 // active character
15032 
15033     };
15034   }
15035 
15036   setCatcode(char, code) {
15037     this.catcodes[char] = code;
15038   }
15039   /**
15040    * This function lexes a single token.
15041    */
15042 
15043 
15044   lex() {
15045     var input = this.input;
15046     var pos = this.tokenRegex.lastIndex;
15047 
15048     if (pos === input.length) {
15049       return new Token("EOF", new SourceLocation(this, pos, pos));
15050     }
15051 
15052     var match = this.tokenRegex.exec(input);
15053 
15054     if (match === null || match.index !== pos) {
15055       throw new ParseError("Unexpected character: '" + input[pos] + "'", new Token(input[pos], new SourceLocation(this, pos, pos + 1)));
15056     }
15057 
15058     var text = match[6] || match[3] || (match[2] ? "\\ " : " ");
15059 
15060     if (this.catcodes[text] === 14) {
15061       // comment character
15062       var nlIndex = input.indexOf('\n', this.tokenRegex.lastIndex);
15063 
15064       if (nlIndex === -1) {
15065         this.tokenRegex.lastIndex = input.length; // EOF
15066 
15067         this.settings.reportNonstrict("commentAtEnd", "% comment has no terminating newline; LaTeX would " + "fail because of commenting the end of math mode (e.g. $)");
15068       } else {
15069         this.tokenRegex.lastIndex = nlIndex + 1;
15070       }
15071 
15072       return this.lex();
15073     }
15074 
15075     return new Token(text, new SourceLocation(this, pos, this.tokenRegex.lastIndex));
15076   }
15077 
15078 }
15079 
15080 /**
15081  * A `Namespace` refers to a space of nameable things like macros or lengths,
15082  * which can be `set` either globally or local to a nested group, using an
15083  * undo stack similar to how TeX implements this functionality.
15084  * Performance-wise, `get` and local `set` take constant time, while global
15085  * `set` takes time proportional to the depth of group nesting.
15086  */
15087 class Namespace {
15088   /**
15089    * Both arguments are optional.  The first argument is an object of
15090    * built-in mappings which never change.  The second argument is an object
15091    * of initial (global-level) mappings, which will constantly change
15092    * according to any global/top-level `set`s done.
15093    */
15094   constructor(builtins, globalMacros) {
15095     if (builtins === void 0) {
15096       builtins = {};
15097     }
15098 
15099     if (globalMacros === void 0) {
15100       globalMacros = {};
15101     }
15102 
15103     this.current = void 0;
15104     this.builtins = void 0;
15105     this.undefStack = void 0;
15106     this.current = globalMacros;
15107     this.builtins = builtins;
15108     this.undefStack = [];
15109   }
15110   /**
15111    * Start a new nested group, affecting future local `set`s.
15112    */
15113 
15114 
15115   beginGroup() {
15116     this.undefStack.push({});
15117   }
15118   /**
15119    * End current nested group, restoring values before the group began.
15120    */
15121 
15122 
15123   endGroup() {
15124     if (this.undefStack.length === 0) {
15125       throw new ParseError("Unbalanced namespace destruction: attempt " + "to pop global namespace; please report this as a bug");
15126     }
15127 
15128     var undefs = this.undefStack.pop();
15129 
15130     for (var undef in undefs) {
15131       if (undefs.hasOwnProperty(undef)) {
15132         if (undefs[undef] == null) {
15133           delete this.current[undef];
15134         } else {
15135           this.current[undef] = undefs[undef];
15136         }
15137       }
15138     }
15139   }
15140   /**
15141    * Ends all currently nested groups (if any), restoring values before the
15142    * groups began.  Useful in case of an error in the middle of parsing.
15143    */
15144 
15145 
15146   endGroups() {
15147     while (this.undefStack.length > 0) {
15148       this.endGroup();
15149     }
15150   }
15151   /**
15152    * Detect whether `name` has a definition.  Equivalent to
15153    * `get(name) != null`.
15154    */
15155 
15156 
15157   has(name) {
15158     return this.current.hasOwnProperty(name) || this.builtins.hasOwnProperty(name);
15159   }
15160   /**
15161    * Get the current value of a name, or `undefined` if there is no value.
15162    *
15163    * Note: Do not use `if (namespace.get(...))` to detect whether a macro
15164    * is defined, as the definition may be the empty string which evaluates
15165    * to `false` in JavaScript.  Use `if (namespace.get(...) != null)` or
15166    * `if (namespace.has(...))`.
15167    */
15168 
15169 
15170   get(name) {
15171     if (this.current.hasOwnProperty(name)) {
15172       return this.current[name];
15173     } else {
15174       return this.builtins[name];
15175     }
15176   }
15177   /**
15178    * Set the current value of a name, and optionally set it globally too.
15179    * Local set() sets the current value and (when appropriate) adds an undo
15180    * operation to the undo stack.  Global set() may change the undo
15181    * operation at every level, so takes time linear in their number.
15182    * A value of undefined means to delete existing definitions.
15183    */
15184 
15185 
15186   set(name, value, global) {
15187     if (global === void 0) {
15188       global = false;
15189     }
15190 
15191     if (global) {
15192       // Global set is equivalent to setting in all groups.  Simulate this
15193       // by destroying any undos currently scheduled for this name,
15194       // and adding an undo with the *new* value (in case it later gets
15195       // locally reset within this environment).
15196       for (var i = 0; i < this.undefStack.length; i++) {
15197         delete this.undefStack[i][name];
15198       }
15199 
15200       if (this.undefStack.length > 0) {
15201         this.undefStack[this.undefStack.length - 1][name] = value;
15202       }
15203     } else {
15204       // Undo this set at end of this group (possibly to `undefined`),
15205       // unless an undo is already in place, in which case that older
15206       // value is the correct one.
15207       var top = this.undefStack[this.undefStack.length - 1];
15208 
15209       if (top && !top.hasOwnProperty(name)) {
15210         top[name] = this.current[name];
15211       }
15212     }
15213 
15214     if (value == null) {
15215       delete this.current[name];
15216     } else {
15217       this.current[name] = value;
15218     }
15219   }
15220 
15221 }
15222 
15223 /**
15224  * Predefined macros for KaTeX.
15225  * This can be used to define some commands in terms of others.
15226  */
15227 var macros = _macros;
15228 // macro tools
15229 
15230 defineMacro("\\noexpand", function (context) {
15231   // The expansion is the token itself; but that token is interpreted
15232   // as if its meaning were ‘\relax’ if it is a control sequence that
15233   // would ordinarily be expanded by TeX’s expansion rules.
15234   var t = context.popToken();
15235 
15236   if (context.isExpandable(t.text)) {
15237     t.noexpand = true;
15238     t.treatAsRelax = true;
15239   }
15240 
15241   return {
15242     tokens: [t],
15243     numArgs: 0
15244   };
15245 });
15246 defineMacro("\\expandafter", function (context) {
15247   // TeX first reads the token that comes immediately after \expandafter,
15248   // without expanding it; let’s call this token t. Then TeX reads the
15249   // token that comes after t (and possibly more tokens, if that token
15250   // has an argument), replacing it by its expansion. Finally TeX puts
15251   // t back in front of that expansion.
15252   var t = context.popToken();
15253   context.expandOnce(true); // expand only an expandable token
15254 
15255   return {
15256     tokens: [t],
15257     numArgs: 0
15258   };
15259 }); // LaTeX's \@firstoftwo{#1}{#2} expands to #1, skipping #2
15260 // TeX source: \long\def\@firstoftwo#1#2{#1}
15261 
15262 defineMacro("\\@firstoftwo", function (context) {
15263   var args = context.consumeArgs(2);
15264   return {
15265     tokens: args[0],
15266     numArgs: 0
15267   };
15268 }); // LaTeX's \@secondoftwo{#1}{#2} expands to #2, skipping #1
15269 // TeX source: \long\def\@secondoftwo#1#2{#2}
15270 
15271 defineMacro("\\@secondoftwo", function (context) {
15272   var args = context.consumeArgs(2);
15273   return {
15274     tokens: args[1],
15275     numArgs: 0
15276   };
15277 }); // LaTeX's \@ifnextchar{#1}{#2}{#3} looks ahead to the next (unexpanded)
15278 // symbol that isn't a space, consuming any spaces but not consuming the
15279 // first nonspace character.  If that nonspace character matches #1, then
15280 // the macro expands to #2; otherwise, it expands to #3.
15281 
15282 defineMacro("\\@ifnextchar", function (context) {
15283   var args = context.consumeArgs(3); // symbol, if, else
15284 
15285   context.consumeSpaces();
15286   var nextToken = context.future();
15287 
15288   if (args[0].length === 1 && args[0][0].text === nextToken.text) {
15289     return {
15290       tokens: args[1],
15291       numArgs: 0
15292     };
15293   } else {
15294     return {
15295       tokens: args[2],
15296       numArgs: 0
15297     };
15298   }
15299 }); // LaTeX's \@ifstar{#1}{#2} looks ahead to the next (unexpanded) symbol.
15300 // If it is `*`, then it consumes the symbol, and the macro expands to #1;
15301 // otherwise, the macro expands to #2 (without consuming the symbol).
15302 // TeX source: \def\@ifstar#1{\@ifnextchar *{\@firstoftwo{#1}}}
15303 
15304 defineMacro("\\@ifstar", "\\@ifnextchar *{\\@firstoftwo{#1}}"); // LaTeX's \TextOrMath{#1}{#2} expands to #1 in text mode, #2 in math mode
15305 
15306 defineMacro("\\TextOrMath", function (context) {
15307   var args = context.consumeArgs(2);
15308 
15309   if (context.mode === 'text') {
15310     return {
15311       tokens: args[0],
15312       numArgs: 0
15313     };
15314   } else {
15315     return {
15316       tokens: args[1],
15317       numArgs: 0
15318     };
15319   }
15320 }); // Lookup table for parsing numbers in base 8 through 16
15321 
15322 var digitToNumber = {
15323   "0": 0,
15324   "1": 1,
15325   "2": 2,
15326   "3": 3,
15327   "4": 4,
15328   "5": 5,
15329   "6": 6,
15330   "7": 7,
15331   "8": 8,
15332   "9": 9,
15333   "a": 10,
15334   "A": 10,
15335   "b": 11,
15336   "B": 11,
15337   "c": 12,
15338   "C": 12,
15339   "d": 13,
15340   "D": 13,
15341   "e": 14,
15342   "E": 14,
15343   "f": 15,
15344   "F": 15
15345 }; // TeX \char makes a literal character (catcode 12) using the following forms:
15346 // (see The TeXBook, p. 43)
15347 //   \char123  -- decimal
15348 //   \char'123 -- octal
15349 //   \char"123 -- hex
15350 //   \char`x   -- character that can be written (i.e. isn't active)
15351 //   \char`\x  -- character that cannot be written (e.g. %)
15352 // These all refer to characters from the font, so we turn them into special
15353 // calls to a function \@char dealt with in the Parser.
15354 
15355 defineMacro("\\char", function (context) {
15356   var token = context.popToken();
15357   var base;
15358   var number = '';
15359 
15360   if (token.text === "'") {
15361     base = 8;
15362     token = context.popToken();
15363   } else if (token.text === '"') {
15364     base = 16;
15365     token = context.popToken();
15366   } else if (token.text === "`") {
15367     token = context.popToken();
15368 
15369     if (token.text[0] === "\\") {
15370       number = token.text.charCodeAt(1);
15371     } else if (token.text === "EOF") {
15372       throw new ParseError("\\char` missing argument");
15373     } else {
15374       number = token.text.charCodeAt(0);
15375     }
15376   } else {
15377     base = 10;
15378   }
15379 
15380   if (base) {
15381     // Parse a number in the given base, starting with first `token`.
15382     number = digitToNumber[token.text];
15383 
15384     if (number == null || number >= base) {
15385       throw new ParseError("Invalid base-" + base + " digit " + token.text);
15386     }
15387 
15388     var digit;
15389 
15390     while ((digit = digitToNumber[context.future().text]) != null && digit < base) {
15391       number *= base;
15392       number += digit;
15393       context.popToken();
15394     }
15395   }
15396 
15397   return "\\@char{" + number + "}";
15398 }); // \newcommand{\macro}[args]{definition}
15399 // \renewcommand{\macro}[args]{definition}
15400 // TODO: Optional arguments: \newcommand{\macro}[args][default]{definition}
15401 
15402 var newcommand = (context, existsOK, nonexistsOK, skipIfExists) => {
15403   var arg = context.consumeArg().tokens;
15404 
15405   if (arg.length !== 1) {
15406     throw new ParseError("\\newcommand's first argument must be a macro name");
15407   }
15408 
15409   var name = arg[0].text;
15410   var exists = context.isDefined(name);
15411 
15412   if (exists && !existsOK) {
15413     throw new ParseError("\\newcommand{" + name + "} attempting to redefine " + (name + "; use \\renewcommand"));
15414   }
15415 
15416   if (!exists && !nonexistsOK) {
15417     throw new ParseError("\\renewcommand{" + name + "} when command " + name + " " + "does not yet exist; use \\newcommand");
15418   }
15419 
15420   var numArgs = 0;
15421   arg = context.consumeArg().tokens;
15422 
15423   if (arg.length === 1 && arg[0].text === "[") {
15424     var argText = '';
15425     var token = context.expandNextToken();
15426 
15427     while (token.text !== "]" && token.text !== "EOF") {
15428       // TODO: Should properly expand arg, e.g., ignore {}s
15429       argText += token.text;
15430       token = context.expandNextToken();
15431     }
15432 
15433     if (!argText.match(/^\s*[0-9]+\s*$/)) {
15434       throw new ParseError("Invalid number of arguments: " + argText);
15435     }
15436 
15437     numArgs = parseInt(argText);
15438     arg = context.consumeArg().tokens;
15439   }
15440 
15441   if (!(exists && skipIfExists)) {
15442     // Final arg is the expansion of the macro
15443     context.macros.set(name, {
15444       tokens: arg,
15445       numArgs
15446     });
15447   }
15448 
15449   return '';
15450 };
15451 
15452 defineMacro("\\newcommand", context => newcommand(context, false, true, false));
15453 defineMacro("\\renewcommand", context => newcommand(context, true, false, false));
15454 defineMacro("\\providecommand", context => newcommand(context, true, true, true)); // terminal (console) tools
15455 
15456 defineMacro("\\message", context => {
15457   var arg = context.consumeArgs(1)[0]; // eslint-disable-next-line no-console
15458 
15459   console.log(arg.reverse().map(token => token.text).join(""));
15460   return '';
15461 });
15462 defineMacro("\\errmessage", context => {
15463   var arg = context.consumeArgs(1)[0]; // eslint-disable-next-line no-console
15464 
15465   console.error(arg.reverse().map(token => token.text).join(""));
15466   return '';
15467 });
15468 defineMacro("\\show", context => {
15469   var tok = context.popToken();
15470   var name = tok.text; // eslint-disable-next-line no-console
15471 
15472   console.log(tok, context.macros.get(name), functions[name], symbols.math[name], symbols.text[name]);
15473   return '';
15474 }); //////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

15610 defineMacro("\\ddddot", "{\\overset{\\raisebox{-0.1ex}{\\normalsize ....}}{#1}}"); // AMSMath's automatic \dots, based on \mdots@@ macro.
15611 
15612 var dotsByToken = {
15613   ',': '\\dotsc',
15614   '\\not': '\\dotsb',
15615   // \keybin@ checks for the following:
15616   '+': '\\dotsb',
15617   '=': '\\dotsb',
15618   '<': '\\dotsb',
15619   '>': '\\dotsb',
15620   '-': '\\dotsb',
15621   '*': '\\dotsb',
15622   ':': '\\dotsb',
15623   // Symbols whose definition starts with \DOTSB:
15624   '\\DOTSB': '\\dotsb',
15625   '\\coprod': '\\dotsb',
15626   '\\bigvee': '\\dotsb',
15627   '\\bigwedge': '\\dotsb',
15628   '\\biguplus': '\\dotsb',
15629   '\\bigcap': '\\dotsb',
15630   '\\bigcup': '\\dotsb',
15631   '\\prod': '\\dotsb',
15632   '\\sum': '\\dotsb',
15633   '\\bigotimes': '\\dotsb',
15634   '\\bigoplus': '\\dotsb',
15635   '\\bigodot': '\\dotsb',
15636   '\\bigsqcup': '\\dotsb',
15637   '\\And': '\\dotsb',
15638   '\\longrightarrow': '\\dotsb',
15639   '\\Longrightarrow': '\\dotsb',
15640   '\\longleftarrow': '\\dotsb',
15641   '\\Longleftarrow': '\\dotsb',
15642   '\\longleftrightarrow': '\\dotsb',
15643   '\\Longleftrightarrow': '\\dotsb',
15644   '\\mapsto': '\\dotsb',
15645   '\\longmapsto': '\\dotsb',
15646   '\\hookrightarrow': '\\dotsb',
15647   '\\doteq': '\\dotsb',
15648   // Symbols whose definition starts with \mathbin:
15649   '\\mathbin': '\\dotsb',
15650   // Symbols whose definition starts with \mathrel:
15651   '\\mathrel': '\\dotsb',
15652   '\\relbar': '\\dotsb',
15653   '\\Relbar': '\\dotsb',
15654   '\\xrightarrow': '\\dotsb',
15655   '\\xleftarrow': '\\dotsb',
15656   // Symbols whose definition starts with \DOTSI:
15657   '\\DOTSI': '\\dotsi',
15658   '\\int': '\\dotsi',
15659   '\\oint': '\\dotsi',
15660   '\\iint': '\\dotsi',
15661   '\\iiint': '\\dotsi',
15662   '\\iiiint': '\\dotsi',
15663   '\\idotsint': '\\dotsi',
15664   // Symbols whose definition starts with \DOTSX:
15665   '\\DOTSX': '\\dotsx'
15666 };
15667 defineMacro("\\dots", function (context) {
15668   // TODO: If used in text mode, should expand to \textellipsis.
15669   // However, in KaTeX, \textellipsis and \ldots behave the same
15670   // (in text mode), and it's unlikely we'd see any of the math commands
15671   // that affect the behavior of \dots when in text mode.  So fine for now
15672   // (until we support \ifmmode ... \else ... \fi).
15673   var thedots = '\\dotso';
15674   var next = context.expandAfterFuture().text;
15675 
15676   if (next in dotsByToken) {
15677     thedots = dotsByToken[next];
15678   } else if (next.slice(0, 4) === '\\not') {
15679     thedots = '\\dotsb';
15680   } else if (next in symbols.math) {
15681     if (utils.contains(['bin', 'rel'], symbols.math[next].group)) {
15682       thedots = '\\dotsb';
15683     }
15684   }
15685 
15686   return thedots;
15687 });
15688 var spaceAfterDots = {
15689   // \rightdelim@ checks for the following:
15690   ')': true,
15691   ']': true,
15692   '\\rbrack': true,
15693   '\\}': true,
15694   '\\rbrace': true,
15695   '\\rangle': true,
15696   '\\rceil': true,
15697   '\\rfloor': true,
15698   '\\rgroup': true,
15699   '\\rmoustache': true,
15700   '\\right': true,
15701   '\\bigr': true,
15702   '\\biggr': true,
15703   '\\Bigr': true,
15704   '\\Biggr': true,
15705   // \extra@ also tests for the following:
15706   '$': true,
15707   // \extrap@ checks for the following:
15708   ';': true,
15709   '.': true,
15710   ',': true
15711 };
15712 defineMacro("\\dotso", function (context) {
15713   var next = context.future().text;
15714 
15715   if (next in spaceAfterDots) {
15716     return "\\ldots\\,";
15717   } else {
15718     return "\\ldots";
15719   }
15720 });
15721 defineMacro("\\dotsc", function (context) {
15722   var next = context.future().text; // \dotsc uses \extra@ but not \extrap@, instead specially checking for
15723   // ';' and '.', but doesn't check for ','.
15724 
15725   if (next in spaceAfterDots && next !== ',') {
15726     return "\\ldots\\,";
15727   } else {
15728     return "\\ldots";
15729   }
15730 });
15731 defineMacro("\\cdots", function (context) {
15732   var next = context.future().text;
15733 
15734   if (next in spaceAfterDots) {
15735     return "\\@cdots\\,";
15736   } else {
15737     return "\\@cdots";
15738   }
15739 });

16051 defineMacro("\\bra", "\\mathinner{\\langle{#1}|}");
16052 defineMacro("\\ket", "\\mathinner{|{#1}\\rangle}");
16053 defineMacro("\\braket", "\\mathinner{\\langle{#1}\\rangle}");

16057 var braketHelper = one => context => {
16058   var left = context.consumeArg().tokens;
16059   var middle = context.consumeArg().tokens;
16060   var middleDouble = context.consumeArg().tokens;
16061   var right = context.consumeArg().tokens;
16062   var oldMiddle = context.macros.get("|");
16063   var oldMiddleDouble = context.macros.get("\\|");
16064   context.macros.beginGroup();
16065 
16066   var midMacro = double => context => {
16067     if (one) {
16068       // Only modify the first instance of | or \|
16069       context.macros.set("|", oldMiddle);
16070 
16071       if (middleDouble.length) {
16072         context.macros.set("\\|", oldMiddleDouble);
16073       }
16074     }
16075 
16076     var doubled = double;
16077 
16078     if (!double && middleDouble.length) {
16079       // Mimic \@ifnextchar
16080       var nextToken = context.future();
16081 
16082       if (nextToken.text === "|") {
16083         context.popToken();
16084         doubled = true;
16085       }
16086     }
16087 
16088     return {
16089       tokens: doubled ? middleDouble : middle,
16090       numArgs: 0
16091     };
16092   };
16093 
16094   context.macros.set("|", midMacro(false));
16095 
16096   if (middleDouble.length) {
16097     context.macros.set("\\|", midMacro(true));
16098   }
16099 
16100   var arg = context.consumeArg().tokens;
16101   var expanded = context.expandTokens([...right, ...arg, ...left // reversed
16102   ]);
16103   context.macros.endGroup();
16104   return {
16105     tokens: expanded.reverse(),
16106     numArgs: 0
16107   };
16108 };
