16177 /**
16178  * This file contains the “gullet” where macros are expanded
16179  * until only non-macro tokens remain.
16180  */
16181 // List of commands that act like macros but aren't defined as a macro,
16182 // function, or symbol.  Used in `isDefined`.
16183 var implicitCommands = {
16184   "^": true,
16185   // Parser.js
16186   "_": true,
16187   // Parser.js
16188   "\\limits": true,
16189   // Parser.js
16190   "\\nolimits": true // Parser.js
16191 
16192 };
16193 class MacroExpander {
16194   constructor(input, settings, mode) {
16195     this.settings = void 0;
16196     this.expansionCount = void 0;
16197     this.lexer = void 0;
16198     this.macros = void 0;
16199     this.stack = void 0;
16200     this.mode = void 0;
16201     this.settings = settings;
16202     this.expansionCount = 0;
16203     this.feed(input); // Make new global namespace
16204 
16205     this.macros = new Namespace(macros, settings.macros);
16206     this.mode = mode;
16207     this.stack = []; // contains tokens in REVERSE order
16208   }
16209   /**
16210    * Feed a new input string to the same MacroExpander
16211    * (with existing macros etc.).
16212    */
16213 
16214 
16215   feed(input) {
16216     this.lexer = new Lexer(input, this.settings);
16217   }
16218   /**
16219    * Switches between "text" and "math" modes.
16220    */
16221 
16222 
16223   switchMode(newMode) {
16224     this.mode = newMode;
16225   }
16226   /**
16227    * Start a new group nesting within all namespaces.
16228    */
16229 
16230 
16231   beginGroup() {
16232     this.macros.beginGroup();
16233   }
16234   /**
16235    * End current group nesting within all namespaces.
16236    */
16237 
16238 
16239   endGroup() {
16240     this.macros.endGroup();
16241   }
16242   /**
16243    * Ends all currently nested groups (if any), restoring values before the
16244    * groups began.  Useful in case of an error in the middle of parsing.
16245    */
16246 
16247 
16248   endGroups() {
16249     this.macros.endGroups();
16250   }
16251   /**
16252    * Returns the topmost token on the stack, without expanding it.
16253    * Similar in behavior to TeX's `\futurelet`.
16254    */
16255 
16256 
16257   future() {
16258     if (this.stack.length === 0) {
16259       this.pushToken(this.lexer.lex());
16260     }
16261 
16262     return this.stack[this.stack.length - 1];
16263   }
16264   /**
16265    * Remove and return the next unexpanded token.
16266    */
16267 
16268 
16269   popToken() {
16270     this.future(); // ensure non-empty stack
16271 
16272     return this.stack.pop();
16273   }
16274   /**
16275    * Add a given token to the token stack.  In particular, this get be used
16276    * to put back a token returned from one of the other methods.
16277    */
16278 
16279 
16280   pushToken(token) {
16281     this.stack.push(token);
16282   }
16283   /**
16284    * Append an array of tokens to the token stack.
16285    */
16286 
16287 
16288   pushTokens(tokens) {
16289     this.stack.push(...tokens);
16290   }
16291   /**
16292    * Find an macro argument without expanding tokens and append the array of
16293    * tokens to the token stack. Uses Token as a container for the result.
16294    */
16295 
16296 
16297   scanArgument(isOptional) {
16298     var start;
16299     var end;
16300     var tokens;
16301 
16302     if (isOptional) {
16303       this.consumeSpaces(); // \@ifnextchar gobbles any space following it
16304 
16305       if (this.future().text !== "[") {
16306         return null;
16307       }
16308 
16309       start = this.popToken(); // don't include [ in tokens
16310 
16311       ({
16312         tokens,
16313         end
16314       } = this.consumeArg(["]"]));
16315     } else {
16316       ({
16317         tokens,
16318         start,
16319         end
16320       } = this.consumeArg());
16321     } // indicate the end of an argument
16322 
16323 
16324     this.pushToken(new Token("EOF", end.loc));
16325     this.pushTokens(tokens);
16326     return start.range(end, "");
16327   }
16328   /**
16329    * Consume all following space tokens, without expansion.
16330    */
16331 
16332 
16333   consumeSpaces() {
16334     for (;;) {
16335       var token = this.future();
16336 
16337       if (token.text === " ") {
16338         this.stack.pop();
16339       } else {
16340         break;
16341       }
16342     }
16343   }
16344   /**
16345    * Consume an argument from the token stream, and return the resulting array
16346    * of tokens and start/end token.
16347    */
16348 
16349 
16350   consumeArg(delims) {
16351     // The argument for a delimited parameter is the shortest (possibly
16352     // empty) sequence of tokens with properly nested {...} groups that is
16353     // followed ... by this particular list of non-parameter tokens.
16354     // The argument for an undelimited parameter is the next nonblank
16355     // token, unless that token is ‘{’, when the argument will be the
16356     // entire {...} group that follows.
16357     var tokens = [];
16358     var isDelimited = delims && delims.length > 0;
16359 
16360     if (!isDelimited) {
16361       // Ignore spaces between arguments.  As the TeXbook says:
16362       // "After you have said ‘\def\row#1#2{...}’, you are allowed to
16363       //  put spaces between the arguments (e.g., ‘\row x n’), because
16364       //  TeX doesn’t use single spaces as undelimited arguments."
16365       this.consumeSpaces();
16366     }
16367 
16368     var start = this.future();
16369     var tok;
16370     var depth = 0;
16371     var match = 0;
16372 
16373     do {
16374       tok = this.popToken();
16375       tokens.push(tok);
16376 
16377       if (tok.text === "{") {
16378         ++depth;
16379       } else if (tok.text === "}") {
16380         --depth;
16381 
16382         if (depth === -1) {
16383           throw new ParseError("Extra }", tok);
16384         }
16385       } else if (tok.text === "EOF") {
16386         throw new ParseError("Unexpected end of input in a macro argument" + ", expected '" + (delims && isDelimited ? delims[match] : "}") + "'", tok);
16387       }
16388 
16389       if (delims && isDelimited) {
16390         if ((depth === 0 || depth === 1 && delims[match] === "{") && tok.text === delims[match]) {
16391           ++match;
16392 
16393           if (match === delims.length) {
16394             // don't include delims in tokens
16395             tokens.splice(-match, match);
16396             break;
16397           }
16398         } else {
16399           match = 0;
16400         }
16401       }
16402     } while (depth !== 0 || isDelimited); // If the argument found ... has the form ‘{<nested tokens>}’,
16403     // ... the outermost braces enclosing the argument are removed
16404 
16405 
16406     if (start.text === "{" && tokens[tokens.length - 1].text === "}") {
16407       tokens.pop();
16408       tokens.shift();
16409     }
16410 
16411     tokens.reverse(); // to fit in with stack order
16412 
16413     return {
16414       tokens,
16415       start,
16416       end: tok
16417     };
16418   }
16419   /**
16420    * Consume the specified number of (delimited) arguments from the token
16421    * stream and return the resulting array of arguments.
16422    */
16423 
16424 
16425   consumeArgs(numArgs, delimiters) {
16426     if (delimiters) {
16427       if (delimiters.length !== numArgs + 1) {
16428         throw new ParseError("The length of delimiters doesn't match the number of args!");
16429       }
16430 
16431       var delims = delimiters[0];
16432 
16433       for (var i = 0; i < delims.length; i++) {
16434         var tok = this.popToken();
16435 
16436         if (delims[i] !== tok.text) {
16437           throw new ParseError("Use of the macro doesn't match its definition", tok);
16438         }
16439       }
16440     }
16441 
16442     var args = [];
16443 
16444     for (var _i = 0; _i < numArgs; _i++) {
16445       args.push(this.consumeArg(delimiters && delimiters[_i + 1]).tokens);
16446     }
16447 
16448     return args;
16449   }
16450   /**
16451    * Increment `expansionCount` by the specified amount.
16452    * Throw an error if it exceeds `maxExpand`.
16453    */
16454 
16455 
16456   countExpansion(amount) {
16457     this.expansionCount += amount;
16458 
16459     if (this.expansionCount > this.settings.maxExpand) {
16460       throw new ParseError("Too many expansions: infinite loop or " + "need to increase maxExpand setting");
16461     }
16462   }
16463   /**
16464    * Expand the next token only once if possible.
16465    *
16466    * If the token is expanded, the resulting tokens will be pushed onto
16467    * the stack in reverse order, and the number of such tokens will be
16468    * returned.  This number might be zero or positive.
16469    *
16470    * If not, the return value is `false`, and the next token remains at the
16471    * top of the stack.
16472    *
16473    * In either case, the next token will be on the top of the stack,
16474    * or the stack will be empty (in case of empty expansion
16475    * and no other tokens).
16476    *
16477    * Used to implement `expandAfterFuture` and `expandNextToken`.
16478    *
16479    * If expandableOnly, only expandable tokens are expanded and
16480    * an undefined control sequence results in an error.
16481    */
16482 
16483 
16484   expandOnce(expandableOnly) {
16485     var topToken = this.popToken();
16486     var name = topToken.text;
16487     var expansion = !topToken.noexpand ? this._getExpansion(name) : null;
16488 
16489     if (expansion == null || expandableOnly && expansion.unexpandable) {
16490       if (expandableOnly && expansion == null && name[0] === "\\" && !this.isDefined(name)) {
16491         throw new ParseError("Undefined control sequence: " + name);
16492       }
16493 
16494       this.pushToken(topToken);
16495       return false;
16496     }
16497 
16498     this.countExpansion(1);
16499     var tokens = expansion.tokens;
16500     var args = this.consumeArgs(expansion.numArgs, expansion.delimiters);
16501 
16502     if (expansion.numArgs) {
16503       // paste arguments in place of the placeholders
16504       tokens = tokens.slice(); // make a shallow copy
16505 
16506       for (var i = tokens.length - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
16507         var tok = tokens[i];
16508 
16509         if (tok.text === "#") {
16510           if (i === 0) {
16511             throw new ParseError("Incomplete placeholder at end of macro body", tok);
16512           }
16513 
16514           tok = tokens[--i]; // next token on stack
16515 
16516           if (tok.text === "#") {
16517             // ## → #
16518             tokens.splice(i + 1, 1); // drop first #
16519           } else if (/^[1-9]$/.test(tok.text)) {
16520             // replace the placeholder with the indicated argument
16521             tokens.splice(i, 2, ...args[+tok.text - 1]);
16522           } else {
16523             throw new ParseError("Not a valid argument number", tok);
16524           }
16525         }
16526       }
16527     } // Concatenate expansion onto top of stack.
16528 
16529 
16530     this.pushTokens(tokens);
16531     return tokens.length;
16532   }
16533   /**
16534    * Expand the next token only once (if possible), and return the resulting
16535    * top token on the stack (without removing anything from the stack).
16536    * Similar in behavior to TeX's `\expandafter\futurelet`.
16537    * Equivalent to expandOnce() followed by future().
16538    */
16539 
16540 
16541   expandAfterFuture() {
16542     this.expandOnce();
16543     return this.future();
16544   }
16545   /**
16546    * Recursively expand first token, then return first non-expandable token.
16547    */
16548 
16549 
16550   expandNextToken() {
16551     for (;;) {
16552       if (this.expandOnce() === false) {
16553         // fully expanded
16554         var token = this.stack.pop(); // the token after \noexpand is interpreted as if its meaning
16555         // were ‘\relax’
16556 
16557         if (token.treatAsRelax) {
16558           token.text = "\\relax";
16559         }
16560 
16561         return token;
16562       }
16563     } // Flow unable to figure out that this pathway is impossible.
16564     // https://github.com/facebook/flow/issues/4808
16565 
16566 
16567     throw new Error(); // eslint-disable-line no-unreachable
16568   }
16569   /**
16570    * Fully expand the given macro name and return the resulting list of
16571    * tokens, or return `undefined` if no such macro is defined.
16572    */
16573 
16574 
16575   expandMacro(name) {
16576     return this.macros.has(name) ? this.expandTokens([new Token(name)]) : undefined;
16577   }
16578   /**
16579    * Fully expand the given token stream and return the resulting list of
16580    * tokens.  Note that the input tokens are in reverse order, but the
16581    * output tokens are in forward order.
16582    */
16583 
16584 
16585   expandTokens(tokens) {
16586     var output = [];
16587     var oldStackLength = this.stack.length;
16588     this.pushTokens(tokens);
16589 
16590     while (this.stack.length > oldStackLength) {
16591       // Expand only expandable tokens
16592       if (this.expandOnce(true) === false) {
16593         // fully expanded
16594         var token = this.stack.pop();
16595 
16596         if (token.treatAsRelax) {
16597           // the expansion of \noexpand is the token itself
16598           token.noexpand = false;
16599           token.treatAsRelax = false;
16600         }
16601 
16602         output.push(token);
16603       }
16604     } // Count all of these tokens as additional expansions, to prevent
16605     // exponential blowup from linearly many \edef's.
16606 
16607 
16608     this.countExpansion(output.length);
16609     return output;
16610   }
16611   /**
16612    * Fully expand the given macro name and return the result as a string,
16613    * or return `undefined` if no such macro is defined.
16614    */
16615 
16616 
16617   expandMacroAsText(name) {
16618     var tokens = this.expandMacro(name);
16619 
16620     if (tokens) {
16621       return tokens.map(token => token.text).join("");
16622     } else {
16623       return tokens;
16624     }
16625   }
16626   /**
16627    * Returns the expanded macro as a reversed array of tokens and a macro
16628    * argument count.  Or returns `null` if no such macro.
16629    */
16630 
16631 
16632   _getExpansion(name) {
16633     var definition = this.macros.get(name);
16634 
16635     if (definition == null) {
16636       // mainly checking for undefined here
16637       return definition;
16638     } // If a single character has an associated catcode other than 13
16639     // (active character), then don't expand it.
16640 
16641 
16642     if (name.length === 1) {
16643       var catcode = this.lexer.catcodes[name];
16644 
16645       if (catcode != null && catcode !== 13) {
16646         return;
16647       }
16648     }
16649 
16650     var expansion = typeof definition === "function" ? definition(this) : definition;
16651 
16652     if (typeof expansion === "string") {
16653       var numArgs = 0;
16654 
16655       if (expansion.indexOf("#") !== -1) {
16656         var stripped = expansion.replace(/##/g, "");
16657 
16658         while (stripped.indexOf("#" + (numArgs + 1)) !== -1) {
16659           ++numArgs;
16660         }
16661       }
16662 
16663       var bodyLexer = new Lexer(expansion, this.settings);
16664       var tokens = [];
16665       var tok = bodyLexer.lex();
16666 
16667       while (tok.text !== "EOF") {
16668         tokens.push(tok);
16669         tok = bodyLexer.lex();
16670       }
16671 
16672       tokens.reverse(); // to fit in with stack using push and pop
16673 
16674       var expanded = {
16675         tokens,
16676         numArgs
16677       };
16678       return expanded;
16679     }
16680 
16681     return expansion;
16682   }
16683   /**
16684    * Determine whether a command is currently "defined" (has some
16685    * functionality), meaning that it's a macro (in the current group),
16686    * a function, a symbol, or one of the special commands listed in
16687    * `implicitCommands`.
16688    */
16689 
16690 
16691   isDefined(name) {
16692     return this.macros.has(name) || functions.hasOwnProperty(name) || symbols.math.hasOwnProperty(name) || symbols.text.hasOwnProperty(name) || implicitCommands.hasOwnProperty(name);
16693   }
16694   /**
16695    * Determine whether a command is expandable.
16696    */
16697 
16698 
16699   isExpandable(name) {
16700     var macro = this.macros.get(name);
16701     return macro != null ? typeof macro === "string" || typeof macro === "function" || !macro.unexpandable : functions.hasOwnProperty(name) && !functions[name].primitive;
16702   }
16703 
16704 }

17210 /**
17211  * This file contains the parser used to parse out a TeX expression from the
17212  * input. Since TeX isn't context-free, standard parsers don't work particularly
17213  * well.
17214  *
17215  * The strategy of this parser is as such:
17216  *
17217  * The main functions (the `.parse...` ones) take a position in the current
17218  * parse string to parse tokens from. The lexer (found in Lexer.js, stored at
17219  * this.gullet.lexer) also supports pulling out tokens at arbitrary places. When
17220  * individual tokens are needed at a position, the lexer is called to pull out a
17221  * token, which is then used.
17222  *
17223  * The parser has a property called "mode" indicating the mode that
17224  * the parser is currently in. Currently it has to be one of "math" or
17225  * "text", which denotes whether the current environment is a math-y
17226  * one or a text-y one (e.g. inside \text). Currently, this serves to
17227  * limit the functions which can be used in text mode.
17228  *
17229  * The main functions then return an object which contains the useful data that
17230  * was parsed at its given point, and a new position at the end of the parsed
17231  * data. The main functions can call each other and continue the parsing by
17232  * using the returned position as a new starting point.
17233  *
17234  * There are also extra `.handle...` functions, which pull out some reused
17235  * functionality into self-contained functions.
17236  *
17237  * The functions return ParseNodes.
17238  */
17239 class Parser {
17240   constructor(input, settings) {
17241     this.mode = void 0;
17242     this.gullet = void 0;
17243     this.settings = void 0;
17244     this.leftrightDepth = void 0;
17245     this.nextToken = void 0;
17246     // Start in math mode
17247     this.mode = "math"; // Create a new macro expander (gullet) and (indirectly via that) also a
17248     // new lexer (mouth) for this parser (stomach, in the language of TeX)
17249 
17250     this.gullet = new MacroExpander(input, settings, this.mode); // Store the settings for use in parsing
17251 
17252     this.settings = settings; // Count leftright depth (for \middle errors)
17253 
17254     this.leftrightDepth = 0;
17255   }
17256   /**
17257    * Checks a result to make sure it has the right type, and throws an
17258    * appropriate error otherwise.
17259    */
17260 
17261 
17262   expect(text, consume) {
17263     if (consume === void 0) {
17264       consume = true;
17265     }
17266 
17267     if (this.fetch().text !== text) {
17268       throw new ParseError("Expected '" + text + "', got '" + this.fetch().text + "'", this.fetch());
17269     }
17270 
17271     if (consume) {
17272       this.consume();
17273     }
17274   }
17275   /**
17276    * Discards the current lookahead token, considering it consumed.
17277    */
17278 
17279 
17280   consume() {
17281     this.nextToken = null;
17282   }
17283   /**
17284    * Return the current lookahead token, or if there isn't one (at the
17285    * beginning, or if the previous lookahead token was consume()d),
17286    * fetch the next token as the new lookahead token and return it.
17287    */
17288 
17289 
17290   fetch() {
17291     if (this.nextToken == null) {
17292       this.nextToken = this.gullet.expandNextToken();
17293     }
17294 
17295     return this.nextToken;
17296   }
17297   /**
17298    * Switches between "text" and "math" modes.
17299    */
17300 
17301 
17302   switchMode(newMode) {
17303     this.mode = newMode;
17304     this.gullet.switchMode(newMode);
17305   }
17306   /**
17307    * Main parsing function, which parses an entire input.
17308    */
17309 
17310 
17311   parse() {
17312     if (!this.settings.globalGroup) {
17313       // Create a group namespace for the math expression.
17314       // (LaTeX creates a new group for every $...$, $$...$$, \[...\].)
17315       this.gullet.beginGroup();
17316     } // Use old \color behavior (same as LaTeX's \textcolor) if requested.
17317     // We do this within the group for the math expression, so it doesn't
17318     // pollute settings.macros.
17319 
17320 
17321     if (this.settings.colorIsTextColor) {
17322       this.gullet.macros.set("\\color", "\\textcolor");
17323     }
17324 
17325     try {
17326       // Try to parse the input
17327       var parse = this.parseExpression(false); // If we succeeded, make sure there's an EOF at the end
17328 
17329       this.expect("EOF"); // End the group namespace for the expression
17330 
17331       if (!this.settings.globalGroup) {
17332         this.gullet.endGroup();
17333       }
17334 
17335       return parse; // Close any leftover groups in case of a parse error.
17336     } finally {
17337       this.gullet.endGroups();
17338     }
17339   }
17340   /**
17341    * Fully parse a separate sequence of tokens as a separate job.
17342    * Tokens should be specified in reverse order, as in a MacroDefinition.
17343    */
17344 
17345 
17346   subparse(tokens) {
17347     // Save the next token from the current job.
17348     var oldToken = this.nextToken;
17349     this.consume(); // Run the new job, terminating it with an excess '}'
17350 
17351     this.gullet.pushToken(new Token("}"));
17352     this.gullet.pushTokens(tokens);
17353     var parse = this.parseExpression(false);
17354     this.expect("}"); // Restore the next token from the current job.
17355 
17356     this.nextToken = oldToken;
17357     return parse;
17358   }
17359 
17360   /**
17361    * Parses an "expression", which is a list of atoms.
17362    *
17363    * `breakOnInfix`: Should the parsing stop when we hit infix nodes? This
17364    *                 happens when functions have higher precedence han infix
17365    *                 nodes in implicit parses.
17366    *
17367    * `breakOnTokenText`: The text of the token that the expression should end
17368    *                     with, or `null` if something else should end the
17369    *                     expression.
17370    */
17371   parseExpression(breakOnInfix, breakOnTokenText) {
17372     var body = []; // Keep adding atoms to the body until we can't parse any more atoms (either
17373     // we reached the end, a }, or a \right)
17374 
17375     while (true) {
17376       // Ignore spaces in math mode
17377       if (this.mode === "math") {
17378         this.consumeSpaces();
17379       }
17380 
17381       var lex = this.fetch();
17382 
17383       if (Parser.endOfExpression.indexOf(lex.text) !== -1) {
17384         break;
17385       }
17386 
17387       if (breakOnTokenText && lex.text === breakOnTokenText) {
17388         break;
17389       }
17390 
17391       if (breakOnInfix && functions[lex.text] && functions[lex.text].infix) {
17392         break;
17393       }
17394 
17395       var atom = this.parseAtom(breakOnTokenText);
17396 
17397       if (!atom) {
17398         break;
17399       } else if (atom.type === "internal") {
17400         continue;
17401       }
17402 
17403       body.push(atom);
17404     }
17405 
17406     if (this.mode === "text") {
17407       this.formLigatures(body);
17408     }
17409 
17410     return this.handleInfixNodes(body);
17411   }
17412   /**
17413    * Rewrites infix operators such as \over with corresponding commands such
17414    * as \frac.
17415    *
17416    * There can only be one infix operator per group.  If there's more than one
17417    * then the expression is ambiguous.  This can be resolved by adding {}.
17418    */
17419 
17420 
17421   handleInfixNodes(body) {
17422     var overIndex = -1;
17423     var funcName;
17424 
17425     for (var i = 0; i < body.length; i++) {
17426       if (body[i].type === "infix") {
17427         if (overIndex !== -1) {
17428           throw new ParseError("only one infix operator per group", body[i].token);
17429         }
17430 
17431         overIndex = i;
17432         funcName = body[i].replaceWith;
17433       }
17434     }
17435 
17436     if (overIndex !== -1 && funcName) {
17437       var numerNode;
17438       var denomNode;
17439       var numerBody = body.slice(0, overIndex);
17440       var denomBody = body.slice(overIndex + 1);
17441 
17442       if (numerBody.length === 1 && numerBody[0].type === "ordgroup") {
17443         numerNode = numerBody[0];
17444       } else {
17445         numerNode = {
17446           type: "ordgroup",
17447           mode: this.mode,
17448           body: numerBody
17449         };
17450       }
17451 
17452       if (denomBody.length === 1 && denomBody[0].type === "ordgroup") {
17453         denomNode = denomBody[0];
17454       } else {
17455         denomNode = {
17456           type: "ordgroup",
17457           mode: this.mode,
17458           body: denomBody
17459         };
17460       }
17461 
17462       var node;
17463 
17464       if (funcName === "\\\\abovefrac") {
17465         node = this.callFunction(funcName, [numerNode, body[overIndex], denomNode], []);
17466       } else {
17467         node = this.callFunction(funcName, [numerNode, denomNode], []);
17468       }
17469 
17470       return [node];
17471     } else {
17472       return body;
17473     }
17474   }
17475   /**
17476    * Handle a subscript or superscript with nice errors.
17477    */
17478 
17479 
17480   handleSupSubscript(name // For error reporting.
17481   ) {
17482     var symbolToken = this.fetch();
17483     var symbol = symbolToken.text;
17484     this.consume();
17485     this.consumeSpaces(); // ignore spaces before sup/subscript argument
17486 
17487     var group = this.parseGroup(name);
17488 
17489     if (!group) {
17490       throw new ParseError("Expected group after '" + symbol + "'", symbolToken);
17491     }
17492 
17493     return group;
17494   }
17495   /**
17496    * Converts the textual input of an unsupported command into a text node
17497    * contained within a color node whose color is determined by errorColor
17498    */
17499 
17500 
17501   formatUnsupportedCmd(text) {
17502     var textordArray = [];
17503 
17504     for (var i = 0; i < text.length; i++) {
17505       textordArray.push({
17506         type: "textord",
17507         mode: "text",
17508         text: text[i]
17509       });
17510     }
17511 
17512     var textNode = {
17513       type: "text",
17514       mode: this.mode,
17515       body: textordArray
17516     };
17517     var colorNode = {
17518       type: "color",
17519       mode: this.mode,
17520       color: this.settings.errorColor,
17521       body: [textNode]
17522     };
17523     return colorNode;
17524   }
17525   /**
17526    * Parses a group with optional super/subscripts.
17527    */
17528 
17529 
17530   parseAtom(breakOnTokenText) {
17531     // The body of an atom is an implicit group, so that things like
17532     // \left(x\right)^2 work correctly.
17533     var base = this.parseGroup("atom", breakOnTokenText); // In text mode, we don't have superscripts or subscripts
17534 
17535     if (this.mode === "text") {
17536       return base;
17537     } // Note that base may be empty (i.e. null) at this point.
17538 
17539 
17540     var superscript;
17541     var subscript;
17542 
17543     while (true) {
17544       // Guaranteed in math mode, so eat any spaces first.
17545       this.consumeSpaces(); // Lex the first token
17546 
17547       var lex = this.fetch();
17548 
17549       if (lex.text === "\\limits" || lex.text === "\\nolimits") {
17550         // We got a limit control
17551         if (base && base.type === "op") {
17552           var limits = lex.text === "\\limits";
17553           base.limits = limits;
17554           base.alwaysHandleSupSub = true;
17555         } else if (base && base.type === "operatorname") {
17556           if (base.alwaysHandleSupSub) {
17557             base.limits = lex.text === "\\limits";
17558           }
17559         } else {
17560           throw new ParseError("Limit controls must follow a math operator", lex);
17561         }
17562 
17563         this.consume();
17564       } else if (lex.text === "^") {
17565         // We got a superscript start
17566         if (superscript) {
17567           throw new ParseError("Double superscript", lex);
17568         }
17569 
17570         superscript = this.handleSupSubscript("superscript");
17571       } else if (lex.text === "_") {
17572         // We got a subscript start
17573         if (subscript) {
17574           throw new ParseError("Double subscript", lex);
17575         }
17576 
17577         subscript = this.handleSupSubscript("subscript");
17578       } else if (lex.text === "'") {
17579         // We got a prime
17580         if (superscript) {
17581           throw new ParseError("Double superscript", lex);
17582         }
17583 
17584         var prime = {
17585           type: "textord",
17586           mode: this.mode,
17587           text: "\\prime"
17588         }; // Many primes can be grouped together, so we handle this here
17589 
17590         var primes = [prime];
17591         this.consume(); // Keep lexing tokens until we get something that's not a prime
17592 
17593         while (this.fetch().text === "'") {
17594           // For each one, add another prime to the list
17595           primes.push(prime);
17596           this.consume();
17597         } // If there's a superscript following the primes, combine that
17598         // superscript in with the primes.
17599 
17600 
17601         if (this.fetch().text === "^") {
17602           primes.push(this.handleSupSubscript("superscript"));
17603         } // Put everything into an ordgroup as the superscript
17604 
17605 
17606         superscript = {
17607           type: "ordgroup",
17608           mode: this.mode,
17609           body: primes
17610         };
17611       } else if (uSubsAndSups[lex.text]) {
17612         // A Unicode subscript or superscript character.
17613         // We treat these similarly to the unicode-math package.
17614         // So we render a string of Unicode (sub|super)scripts the
17615         // same as a (sub|super)script of regular characters.
17616         var isSub = unicodeSubRegEx.test(lex.text);
17617         var subsupTokens = [];
17618         subsupTokens.push(new Token(uSubsAndSups[lex.text]));
17619         this.consume(); // Continue fetching tokens to fill out the string.
17620 
17621         while (true) {
17622           var token = this.fetch().text;
17623 
17624           if (!uSubsAndSups[token]) {
17625             break;
17626           }
17627 
17628           if (unicodeSubRegEx.test(token) !== isSub) {
17629             break;
17630           }
17631 
17632           subsupTokens.unshift(new Token(uSubsAndSups[token]));
17633           this.consume();
17634         } // Now create a (sub|super)script.
17635 
17636 
17637         var body = this.subparse(subsupTokens);
17638 
17639         if (isSub) {
17640           subscript = {
17641             type: "ordgroup",
17642             mode: "math",
17643             body
17644           };
17645         } else {
17646           superscript = {
17647             type: "ordgroup",
17648             mode: "math",
17649             body
17650           };
17651         }
17652       } else {
17653         // If it wasn't ^, _, or ', stop parsing super/subscripts
17654         break;
17655       }
17656     } // Base must be set if superscript or subscript are set per logic above,
17657     // but need to check here for type check to pass.
17658 
17659 
17660     if (superscript || subscript) {
17661       // If we got either a superscript or subscript, create a supsub
17662       return {
17663         type: "supsub",
17664         mode: this.mode,
17665         base: base,
17666         sup: superscript,
17667         sub: subscript
17668       };
17669     } else {
17670       // Otherwise return the original body
17671       return base;
17672     }
17673   }
17674   /**
17675    * Parses an entire function, including its base and all of its arguments.
17676    */
17677 
17678 
17679   parseFunction(breakOnTokenText, name // For determining its context
17680   ) {
17681     var token = this.fetch();
17682     var func = token.text;
17683     var funcData = functions[func];
17684 
17685     if (!funcData) {
17686       return null;
17687     }
17688 
17689     this.consume(); // consume command token
17690 
17691     if (name && name !== "atom" && !funcData.allowedInArgument) {
17692       throw new ParseError("Got function '" + func + "' with no arguments" + (name ? " as " + name : ""), token);
17693     } else if (this.mode === "text" && !funcData.allowedInText) {
17694       throw new ParseError("Can't use function '" + func + "' in text mode", token);
17695     } else if (this.mode === "math" && funcData.allowedInMath === false) {
17696       throw new ParseError("Can't use function '" + func + "' in math mode", token);
17697     }
17698 
17699     var {
17700       args,
17701       optArgs
17702     } = this.parseArguments(func, funcData);
17703     return this.callFunction(func, args, optArgs, token, breakOnTokenText);
17704   }
17705   /**
17706    * Call a function handler with a suitable context and arguments.
17707    */
17708 
17709 
17710   callFunction(name, args, optArgs, token, breakOnTokenText) {
17711     var context = {
17712       funcName: name,
17713       parser: this,
17714       token,
17715       breakOnTokenText
17716     };
17717     var func = functions[name];
17718 
17719     if (func && func.handler) {
17720       return func.handler(context, args, optArgs);
17721     } else {
17722       throw new ParseError("No function handler for " + name);
17723     }
17724   }
17725   /**
17726    * Parses the arguments of a function or environment
17727    */
17728 
17729 
17730   parseArguments(func, // Should look like "\name" or "\begin{name}".
17731   funcData) {
17732     var totalArgs = funcData.numArgs + funcData.numOptionalArgs;
17733 
17734     if (totalArgs === 0) {
17735       return {
17736         args: [],
17737         optArgs: []
17738       };
17739     }
17740 
17741     var args = [];
17742     var optArgs = [];
17743 
17744     for (var i = 0; i < totalArgs; i++) {
17745       var argType = funcData.argTypes && funcData.argTypes[i];
17746       var isOptional = i < funcData.numOptionalArgs;
17747 
17748       if (funcData.primitive && argType == null || // \sqrt expands into primitive if optional argument doesn't exist
17749       funcData.type === "sqrt" && i === 1 && optArgs[0] == null) {
17750         argType = "primitive";
17751       }
17752 
17753       var arg = this.parseGroupOfType("argument to '" + func + "'", argType, isOptional);
17754 
17755       if (isOptional) {
17756         optArgs.push(arg);
17757       } else if (arg != null) {
17758         args.push(arg);
17759       } else {
17760         // should be unreachable
17761         throw new ParseError("Null argument, please report this as a bug");
17762       }
17763     }
17764 
17765     return {
17766       args,
17767       optArgs
17768     };
17769   }
17770   /**
17771    * Parses a group when the mode is changing.
17772    */
17773 
17774 
17775   parseGroupOfType(name, type, optional) {
17776     switch (type) {
17777       case "color":
17778         return this.parseColorGroup(optional);
17779 
17780       case "size":
17781         return this.parseSizeGroup(optional);
17782 
17783       case "url":
17784         return this.parseUrlGroup(optional);
17785 
17786       case "math":
17787       case "text":
17788         return this.parseArgumentGroup(optional, type);
17789 
17790       case "hbox":
17791         {
17792           // hbox argument type wraps the argument in the equivalent of
17793           // \hbox, which is like \text but switching to \textstyle size.
17794           var group = this.parseArgumentGroup(optional, "text");
17795           return group != null ? {
17796             type: "styling",
17797             mode: group.mode,
17798             body: [group],
17799             style: "text" // simulate \textstyle
17800 
17801           } : null;
17802         }
17803 
17804       case "raw":
17805         {
17806           var token = this.parseStringGroup("raw", optional);
17807           return token != null ? {
17808             type: "raw",
17809             mode: "text",
17810             string: token.text
17811           } : null;
17812         }
17813 
17814       case "primitive":
17815         {
17816           if (optional) {
17817             throw new ParseError("A primitive argument cannot be optional");
17818           }
17819 
17820           var _group = this.parseGroup(name);
17821 
17822           if (_group == null) {
17823             throw new ParseError("Expected group as " + name, this.fetch());
17824           }
17825 
17826           return _group;
17827         }
17828 
17829       case "original":
17830       case null:
17831       case undefined:
17832         return this.parseArgumentGroup(optional);
17833 
17834       default:
17835         throw new ParseError("Unknown group type as " + name, this.fetch());
17836     }
17837   }
17838   /**
17839    * Discard any space tokens, fetching the next non-space token.
17840    */
17841 
17842 
17843   consumeSpaces() {
17844     while (this.fetch().text === " ") {
17845       this.consume();
17846     }
17847   }
17848   /**
17849    * Parses a group, essentially returning the string formed by the
17850    * brace-enclosed tokens plus some position information.
17851    */
17852 
17853 
17854   parseStringGroup(modeName, // Used to describe the mode in error messages.
17855   optional) {
17856     var argToken = this.gullet.scanArgument(optional);
17857 
17858     if (argToken == null) {
17859       return null;
17860     }
17861 
17862     var str = "";
17863     var nextToken;
17864 
17865     while ((nextToken = this.fetch()).text !== "EOF") {
17866       str += nextToken.text;
17867       this.consume();
17868     }
17869 
17870     this.consume(); // consume the end of the argument
17871 
17872     argToken.text = str;
17873     return argToken;
17874   }
17875   /**
17876    * Parses a regex-delimited group: the largest sequence of tokens
17877    * whose concatenated strings match `regex`. Returns the string
17878    * formed by the tokens plus some position information.
17879    */
17880 
17881 
17882   parseRegexGroup(regex, modeName // Used to describe the mode in error messages.
17883   ) {
17884     var firstToken = this.fetch();
17885     var lastToken = firstToken;
17886     var str = "";
17887     var nextToken;
17888 
17889     while ((nextToken = this.fetch()).text !== "EOF" && regex.test(str + nextToken.text)) {
17890       lastToken = nextToken;
17891       str += lastToken.text;
17892       this.consume();
17893     }
17894 
17895     if (str === "") {
17896       throw new ParseError("Invalid " + modeName + ": '" + firstToken.text + "'", firstToken);
17897     }
17898 
17899     return firstToken.range(lastToken, str);
17900   }
17901   /**
17902    * Parses a color description.
17903    */
17904 
17905 
17906   parseColorGroup(optional) {
17907     var res = this.parseStringGroup("color", optional);
17908 
17909     if (res == null) {
17910       return null;
17911     }
17912 
17913     var match = /^(#[a-f0-9]{3}|#?[a-f0-9]{6}|[a-z]+)$/i.exec(res.text);
17914 
17915     if (!match) {
17916       throw new ParseError("Invalid color: '" + res.text + "'", res);
17917     }
17918 
17919     var color = match[0];
17920 
17921     if (/^[0-9a-f]{6}$/i.test(color)) {
17922       // We allow a 6-digit HTML color spec without a leading "#".
17923       // This follows the xcolor package's HTML color model.
17924       // Predefined color names are all missed by this RegEx pattern.
17925       color = "#" + color;
17926     }
17927 
17928     return {
17929       type: "color-token",
17930       mode: this.mode,
17931       color
17932     };
17933   }
17934   /**
17935    * Parses a size specification, consisting of magnitude and unit.
17936    */
17937 
17938 
17939   parseSizeGroup(optional) {
17940     var res;
17941     var isBlank = false; // don't expand before parseStringGroup
17942 
17943     this.gullet.consumeSpaces();
17944 
17945     if (!optional && this.gullet.future().text !== "{") {
17946       res = this.parseRegexGroup(/^[-+]? *(?:$|\d+|\d+\.\d*|\.\d*) *[a-z]{0,2} *$/, "size");
17947     } else {
17948       res = this.parseStringGroup("size", optional);
17949     }
17950 
17951     if (!res) {
17952       return null;
17953     }
17954 
17955     if (!optional && res.text.length === 0) {
17956       // Because we've tested for what is !optional, this block won't
17957       // affect \kern, \hspace, etc. It will capture the mandatory arguments
17958       // to \genfrac and \above.
17959       res.text = "0pt"; // Enable \above{}
17960 
17961       isBlank = true; // This is here specifically for \genfrac
17962     }
17963 
17964     var match = /([-+]?) *(\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+) *([a-z]{2})/.exec(res.text);
17965 
17966     if (!match) {
17967       throw new ParseError("Invalid size: '" + res.text + "'", res);
17968     }
17969 
17970     var data = {
17971       number: +(match[1] + match[2]),
17972       // sign + magnitude, cast to number
17973       unit: match[3]
17974     };
17975 
17976     if (!validUnit(data)) {
17977       throw new ParseError("Invalid unit: '" + data.unit + "'", res);
17978     }
17979 
17980     return {
17981       type: "size",
17982       mode: this.mode,
17983       value: data,
17984       isBlank
17985     };
17986   }
17987   /**
17988    * Parses an URL, checking escaped letters and allowed protocols,
17989    * and setting the catcode of % as an active character (as in \hyperref).
17990    */
17991 
17992 
17993   parseUrlGroup(optional) {
17994     this.gullet.lexer.setCatcode("%", 13); // active character
17995 
17996     this.gullet.lexer.setCatcode("~", 12); // other character
17997 
17998     var res = this.parseStringGroup("url", optional);
17999     this.gullet.lexer.setCatcode("%", 14); // comment character
18000 
18001     this.gullet.lexer.setCatcode("~", 13); // active character
18002 
18003     if (res == null) {
18004       return null;
18005     } // hyperref package allows backslashes alone in href, but doesn't
18006     // generate valid links in such cases; we interpret this as
18007     // "undefined" behaviour, and keep them as-is. Some browser will
18008     // replace backslashes with forward slashes.
18009 
18010 
18011     var url = res.text.replace(/\\([#$%&~_^{}])/g, '$1');
18012     return {
18013       type: "url",
18014       mode: this.mode,
18015       url
18016     };
18017   }
18018   /**
18019    * Parses an argument with the mode specified.
18020    */
18021 
18022 
18023   parseArgumentGroup(optional, mode) {
18024     var argToken = this.gullet.scanArgument(optional);
18025 
18026     if (argToken == null) {
18027       return null;
18028     }
18029 
18030     var outerMode = this.mode;
18031 
18032     if (mode) {
18033       // Switch to specified mode
18034       this.switchMode(mode);
18035     }
18036 
18037     this.gullet.beginGroup();
18038     var expression = this.parseExpression(false, "EOF"); // TODO: find an alternative way to denote the end
18039 
18040     this.expect("EOF"); // expect the end of the argument
18041 
18042     this.gullet.endGroup();
18043     var result = {
18044       type: "ordgroup",
18045       mode: this.mode,
18046       loc: argToken.loc,
18047       body: expression
18048     };
18049 
18050     if (mode) {
18051       // Switch mode back
18052       this.switchMode(outerMode);
18053     }
18054 
18055     return result;
18056   }
18057   /**
18058    * Parses an ordinary group, which is either a single nucleus (like "x")
18059    * or an expression in braces (like "{x+y}") or an implicit group, a group
18060    * that starts at the current position, and ends right before a higher explicit
18061    * group ends, or at EOF.
18062    */
18063 
18064 
18065   parseGroup(name, // For error reporting.
18066   breakOnTokenText) {
18067     var firstToken = this.fetch();
18068     var text = firstToken.text;
18069     var result; // Try to parse an open brace or \begingroup
18070 
18071     if (text === "{" || text === "\\begingroup") {
18072       this.consume();
18073       var groupEnd = text === "{" ? "}" : "\\endgroup";
18074       this.gullet.beginGroup(); // If we get a brace, parse an expression
18075 
18076       var expression = this.parseExpression(false, groupEnd);
18077       var lastToken = this.fetch();
18078       this.expect(groupEnd); // Check that we got a matching closing brace
18079 
18080       this.gullet.endGroup();
18081       result = {
18082         type: "ordgroup",
18083         mode: this.mode,
18084         loc: SourceLocation.range(firstToken, lastToken),
18085         body: expression,
18086         // A group formed by \begingroup...\endgroup is a semi-simple group
18087         // which doesn't affect spacing in math mode, i.e., is transparent.
18088         // https://tex.stackexchange.com/questions/1930/when-should-one-
18089         // use-begingroup-instead-of-bgroup
18090         semisimple: text === "\\begingroup" || undefined
18091       };
18092     } else {
18093       // If there exists a function with this name, parse the function.
18094       // Otherwise, just return a nucleus
18095       result = this.parseFunction(breakOnTokenText, name) || this.parseSymbol();
18096 
18097       if (result == null && text[0] === "\\" && !implicitCommands.hasOwnProperty(text)) {
18098         if (this.settings.throwOnError) {
18099           throw new ParseError("Undefined control sequence: " + text, firstToken);
18100         }
18101 
18102         result = this.formatUnsupportedCmd(text);
18103         this.consume();
18104       }
18105     }
18106 
18107     return result;
18108   }
18109   /**
18110    * Form ligature-like combinations of characters for text mode.
18111    * This includes inputs like "--", "---", "``" and "''".
18112    * The result will simply replace multiple textord nodes with a single
18113    * character in each value by a single textord node having multiple
18114    * characters in its value.  The representation is still ASCII source.
18115    * The group will be modified in place.
18116    */
18117 
18118 
18119   formLigatures(group) {
18120     var n = group.length - 1;
18121 
18122     for (var i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
18123       var a = group[i]; // $FlowFixMe: Not every node type has a `text` property.
18124 
18125       var v = a.text;
18126 
18127       if (v === "-" && group[i + 1].text === "-") {
18128         if (i + 1 < n && group[i + 2].text === "-") {
18129           group.splice(i, 3, {
18130             type: "textord",
18131             mode: "text",
18132             loc: SourceLocation.range(a, group[i + 2]),
18133             text: "---"
18134           });
18135           n -= 2;
18136         } else {
18137           group.splice(i, 2, {
18138             type: "textord",
18139             mode: "text",
18140             loc: SourceLocation.range(a, group[i + 1]),
18141             text: "--"
18142           });
18143           n -= 1;
18144         }
18145       }
18146 
18147       if ((v === "'" || v === "`") && group[i + 1].text === v) {
18148         group.splice(i, 2, {
18149           type: "textord",
18150           mode: "text",
18151           loc: SourceLocation.range(a, group[i + 1]),
18152           text: v + v
18153         });
18154         n -= 1;
18155       }
18156     }
18157   }
18158   /**
18159    * Parse a single symbol out of the string. Here, we handle single character
18160    * symbols and special functions like \verb.
18161    */
18162 
18163 
18164   parseSymbol() {
18165     var nucleus = this.fetch();
18166     var text = nucleus.text;
18167 
18168     if (/^\\verb[^a-zA-Z]/.test(text)) {
18169       this.consume();
18170       var arg = text.slice(5);
18171       var star = arg.charAt(0) === "*";
18172 
18173       if (star) {
18174         arg = arg.slice(1);
18175       } // Lexer's tokenRegex is constructed to always have matching
18176       // first/last characters.
18177 
18178 
18179       if (arg.length < 2 || arg.charAt(0) !== arg.slice(-1)) {
18180         throw new ParseError("\\verb assertion failed --\n                    please report what input caused this bug");
18181       }
18182 
18183       arg = arg.slice(1, -1); // remove first and last char
18184 
18185       return {
18186         type: "verb",
18187         mode: "text",
18188         body: arg,
18189         star
18190       };
18191     } // At this point, we should have a symbol, possibly with accents.
18192     // First expand any accented base symbol according to unicodeSymbols.
18193 
18194 
18195     if (unicodeSymbols.hasOwnProperty(text[0]) && !symbols[this.mode][text[0]]) {
18196       // This behavior is not strict (XeTeX-compatible) in math mode.
18197       if (this.settings.strict && this.mode === "math") {
18198         this.settings.reportNonstrict("unicodeTextInMathMode", "Accented Unicode text character \"" + text[0] + "\" used in " + "math mode", nucleus);
18199       }
18200 
18201       text = unicodeSymbols[text[0]] + text.slice(1);
18202     } // Strip off any combining characters
18203 
18204 
18205     var match = combiningDiacriticalMarksEndRegex.exec(text);
18206 
18207     if (match) {
18208       text = text.substring(0, match.index);
18209 
18210       if (text === 'i') {
18211         text = '\u0131'; // dotless i, in math and text mode
18212       } else if (text === 'j') {
18213         text = '\u0237'; // dotless j, in math and text mode
18214       }
18215     } // Recognize base symbol
18216 
18217 
18218     var symbol;
18219 
18220     if (symbols[this.mode][text]) {
18221       if (this.settings.strict && this.mode === 'math' && extraLatin.indexOf(text) >= 0) {
18222         this.settings.reportNonstrict("unicodeTextInMathMode", "Latin-1/Unicode text character \"" + text[0] + "\" used in " + "math mode", nucleus);
18223       }
18224 
18225       var group = symbols[this.mode][text].group;
18226       var loc = SourceLocation.range(nucleus);
18227       var s;
18228 
18229       if (ATOMS.hasOwnProperty(group)) {
18230         // $FlowFixMe
18231         var family = group;
18232         s = {
18233           type: "atom",
18234           mode: this.mode,
18235           family,
18236           loc,
18237           text
18238         };
18239       } else {
18240         // $FlowFixMe
18241         s = {
18242           type: group,
18243           mode: this.mode,
18244           loc,
18245           text
18246         };
18247       } // $FlowFixMe
18248 
18249 
18250       symbol = s;
18251     } else if (text.charCodeAt(0) >= 0x80) {
18252       // no symbol for e.g. ^
18253       if (this.settings.strict) {
18254         if (!supportedCodepoint(text.charCodeAt(0))) {
18255           this.settings.reportNonstrict("unknownSymbol", "Unrecognized Unicode character \"" + text[0] + "\"" + (" (" + text.charCodeAt(0) + ")"), nucleus);
18256         } else if (this.mode === "math") {
18257           this.settings.reportNonstrict("unicodeTextInMathMode", "Unicode text character \"" + text[0] + "\" used in math mode", nucleus);
18258         }
18259       } // All nonmathematical Unicode characters are rendered as if they
18260       // are in text mode (wrapped in \text) because that's what it
18261       // takes to render them in LaTeX.  Setting `mode: this.mode` is
18262       // another natural choice (the user requested math mode), but
18263       // this makes it more difficult for getCharacterMetrics() to
18264       // distinguish Unicode characters without metrics and those for
18265       // which we want to simulate the letter M.
18266 
18267 
18268       symbol = {
18269         type: "textord",
18270         mode: "text",
18271         loc: SourceLocation.range(nucleus),
18272         text
18273       };
18274     } else {
18275       return null; // EOF, ^, _, {, }, etc.
18276     }
18277 
18278     this.consume(); // Transform combining characters into accents
18279 
18280     if (match) {
18281       for (var i = 0; i < match[0].length; i++) {
18282         var accent = match[0][i];
18283 
18284         if (!unicodeAccents[accent]) {
18285           throw new ParseError("Unknown accent ' " + accent + "'", nucleus);
18286         }
18287 
18288         var command = unicodeAccents[accent][this.mode] || unicodeAccents[accent].text;
18289 
18290         if (!command) {
18291           throw new ParseError("Accent " + accent + " unsupported in " + this.mode + " mode", nucleus);
18292         }
18293 
18294         symbol = {
18295           type: "accent",
18296           mode: this.mode,
18297           loc: SourceLocation.range(nucleus),
18298           label: command,
18299           isStretchy: false,
18300           isShifty: true,
18301           // $FlowFixMe
18302           base: symbol
18303         };
18304       }
18305     } // $FlowFixMe
18306 
18307 
18308     return symbol;
18309   }
18310 
18311 }
18312 Parser.endOfExpression = ["}", "\\endgroup", "\\end", "\\right", "&"];
18313 
18314 /**
18315  * Provides a single function for parsing an expression using a Parser
18316  * TODO(emily): Remove this
18317  */
18318 
18319 /**
18320  * Parses an expression using a Parser, then returns the parsed result.
18321  */
18322 var parseTree = function parseTree(toParse, settings) {
18323   if (!(typeof toParse === 'string' || toParse instanceof String)) {
18324     throw new TypeError('KaTeX can only parse string typed expression');
18325   }
18326 
18327   var parser = new Parser(toParse, settings); // Blank out any \df@tag to avoid spurious "Duplicate \tag" errors
18328 
18329   delete parser.gullet.macros.current["\\df@tag"];
18330   var tree = parser.parse(); // Prevent a color definition from persisting between calls to katex.render().
18331 
18332   delete parser.gullet.macros.current["\\current@color"];
18333   delete parser.gullet.macros.current["\\color"]; // If the input used \tag, it will set the \df@tag macro to the tag.
18334   // In this case, we separately parse the tag and wrap the tree.
18335 
18336   if (parser.gullet.macros.get("\\df@tag")) {
18337     if (!settings.displayMode) {
18338       throw new ParseError("\\tag works only in display equations");
18339     }
18340 
18341     tree = [{
18342       type: "tag",
18343       mode: "text",
18344       body: tree,
18345       tag: parser.subparse([new Token("\\df@tag")])
18346     }];
18347   }
18348 
18349   return tree;
18350 };

18353 
18354 /**
18355  * Parse and build an expression, and place that expression in the DOM node
18356  * given.
18357  */
18358 var render = function render(expression, baseNode, options) {
18359   baseNode.textContent = "";
18360   var node = renderToDomTree(expression, options).toNode();
18361   baseNode.appendChild(node);
18362 }; // KaTeX's styles don't work properly in quirks mode. Print out an error, and
18363 // disable rendering.
18364 
18365 
18366 if (typeof document !== "undefined") {
18367   if (document.compatMode !== "CSS1Compat") {
18368     typeof console !== "undefined" && console.warn("Warning: KaTeX doesn't work in quirks mode. Make sure your " + "website has a suitable doctype.");
18369 
18370     render = function render() {
18371       throw new ParseError("KaTeX doesn't work in quirks mode.");
18372     };
18373   }
18374 }
18375 /**
18376  * Parse and build an expression, and return the markup for that.
18377  */
18378 
18379 
18380 var renderToString = function renderToString(expression, options) {
18381   var markup = renderToDomTree(expression, options).toMarkup();
18382   return markup;
18383 };
18384 /**
18385  * Parse an expression and return the parse tree.
18386  */
18387 
18388 
18389 var generateParseTree = function generateParseTree(expression, options) {
18390   var settings = new Settings(options);
18391   return parseTree(expression, settings);
18392 };
18393 /**
18394  * If the given error is a KaTeX ParseError and options.throwOnError is false,
18395  * renders the invalid LaTeX as a span with hover title giving the KaTeX
18396  * error message.  Otherwise, simply throws the error.
18397  */
18398 
18399 
18400 var renderError = function renderError(error, expression, options) {
18401   if (options.throwOnError || !(error instanceof ParseError)) {
18402     throw error;
18403   }
18404 
18405   var node = buildCommon.makeSpan(["katex-error"], [new SymbolNode(expression)]);
18406   node.setAttribute("title", error.toString());
18407   node.setAttribute("style", "color:" + options.errorColor);
18408   return node;
18409 };
18410 /**
18411  * Generates and returns the katex build tree. This is used for advanced
18412  * use cases (like rendering to custom output).
18413  */
18414 
18415 
18416 var renderToDomTree = function renderToDomTree(expression, options) {
18417   var settings = new Settings(options);
18418 
18419   try {
18420     var tree = parseTree(expression, settings);
18421     return buildTree(tree, expression, settings);
18422   } catch (error) {
18423     return renderError(error, expression, settings);
18424   }
18425 };
18426 /**
18427  * Generates and returns the katex build tree, with just HTML (no MathML).
18428  * This is used for advanced use cases (like rendering to custom output).
18429  */
18430 
18431 
18432 var renderToHTMLTree = function renderToHTMLTree(expression, options) {
18433   var settings = new Settings(options);
18434 
18435   try {
18436     var tree = parseTree(expression, settings);
18437     return buildHTMLTree(tree, expression, settings);
18438   } catch (error) {
18439     return renderError(error, expression, settings);
18440   }
18441 };
